What are these for?

I think these are bad case scenario due to the following reasons:
1. It makes string formatting less obvious: "Wrong parameter %(param_name)s" % {"param_name": param_name} is far more readable than "Wrong parameter %s" % param_name.
2. It disallows for easier string message expansion. The "%(param_name)s %(fooname)s" {"param_name": ..., "fooname": ...} is better than "%s %s" (param_name, fooname). The dict versions allows for easier expansion too.'}, {'account_id': 9545, 'date': '2015-06-09 20:04:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

commit_message:
Eliminated string formatting with single mapping key

This fixes a string formatting bug in Sahara utils, but also changes a
number of other string formatting instances, and adds a hacking rule,
N353, to hopefully avoid this sort of error in the future.

Change-Id: Ic67aa49024b3d3d8701a2dd23569990f34a9e25b

commit_message:
Port middleware to Python 3

* Fix integer division: status_code/100 => status_code//100
* HTTP body type is bytes. Decode the HTTP body from UTF-8 to use it.
  Encode XML and JSON to UTF-8 to produce the HTTP body (for error
  messages).
* Factorize XML/JSON code a little bit more (ex: add the new
  content_type variable)
* Fix test_app on Python 3: decode HTTP from UTF-8 to load JSON
* tox.ini: add api.v2.test_app to Python 3.4

Change-Id: I4f916cba36306f776b01df915c55e314ade6b6ba

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-06-05 10:23:09.000000000', 'message': 'Re-add the StorPool distributed storage driver

Re-add the driver in the exact state as it was when removed,
so that the actual updates may be tracked in follow-up commits.

Implements: blueprint storpool-block-driver
Change-Id: I5c29cb5f679b08b8db664c9f20cf24cbcd7c6c60
'}, {'created': '2015-06-06 11:12:27.000000000', 'message': 'Re-add the StorPool distributed storage driver

Re-add the driver as it was removed, then make the following
six changes (bugfixes and updates):

1. Move the testcase to cinder/tests/unit/

2. Pass the H402 docstring check

Add a period at the end of a single-line docstring.

3. Fall back to the configured template

If the volume type does not specify a template, properly fall back to
the default template from the configuration instead of going with none.

4. Return volume object in _attach_volume()

Catch up with rev. bbf1b49 of volume/driver.py.

5. Use the ABC metaclasses

Declare the existing StorPool volume driver functionality by
deriving from the appropriate driver.*VD classes.

6. Implement volume retyping and migrations

initialize_connection(): store the StorPool client ID in the connection
data to be used by the "StorPool" Brick connector.

validate_connector(): actually check the connector data for a valid
hostname defined in the StorPool configuration.

_storpool_client_id(): new method to get the numeric ID of a host in
the StorPool cluster from the /etc/storpool.conf file.

_attach_volume(), _detach_volume(): if the "remote" flag is set, pass
the request on to the default Cinder driver implementation; it knows
how to make remote volumes accessible.

_attach_volume(), _detach_volume(): support the case when these methods
are invoked from a method that is not overridden in the StorPool Cinder
driver - create a storpool.spopenstack.AttachDB attachment structure
and destroy it upon detaching.

ensure_export(): add a stub method, the actual work is handled by
the Nova volume attachment driver.

retype(): new method: handle a StorPool-to-StorPool retyping where
at most the volume's StorPool template or replication is changed.
For anything else, return False to indicate an unsupported request so
that a full volume migration is triggered.

update_migrated_volume(): rename the StorPool volume to correspond to
the real Cinder volume's name.

Add the StorPoolConfigurationMissing and StorPoolConfigurationInvalid
exceptions.

Flesh out the validate_connector() and initialize_connection() unit tests.

Implements: blueprint storpool-block-driver
Implements: blueprint abc-driver-update
Implements: blueprint volume-retype
Change-Id: I5c29cb5f679b08b8db664c9f20cf24cbcd7c6c60

the StorPool cluster from the /etc/storpool.conf file.

_attach_volume(), _detach_volume(): if the "remote" flag is set, pass
the request on to the default Cinder driver implementation; it knows
how to make remote volumes accessible.

_attach_volume(), _detach_volume(): support the case when these methods
are invoked from a method that is not overridden in the StorPool Cinder
driver - create a storpool.spopenstack.AttachDB attachment structure
and destroy it upon detaching.

ensure_export(): add a stub method, the actual work is handled by
the Nova volume attachment driver.

retype(): new method: handle a StorPool-to-StorPool retyping where
at most the volume's StorPool template or replication is changed.
For anything else, return False to indicate an unsupported request so
that a full volume migration is triggered.

update_migrated_volume(): rename the StorPool volume to correspond to
the real Cinder volume's name.

Add the StorPoolConfigurationMissing and StorPoolConfigurationInvalid
exceptions.

Flesh out the validate_connector() and initialize_connection() unit tests.

commit_message:
Re-add the StorPool distributed storage driver

Re-add the driver as it was removed, then make the following
six changes (bugfixes and updates):

1. Move the testcase to cinder/tests/unit/

2. Pass the H402 docstring check

Add a period at the end of a single-line docstring.

3. Fall back to the configured template

If the volume type does not specify a template, properly fall back to
the default template from the configuration instead of going with none.

4. Return volume object in _attach_volume()

Catch up with rev. bbf1b49 of volume/driver.py.

5. Use the ABC metaclasses

Declare the existing StorPool volume driver functionality by
deriving from the appropriate driver.*VD classes.

6. Implement volume retyping and migrations

initialize_connection(): store the StorPool client ID in the connection
data to be used by the "StorPool" Brick connector.

validate_connector(): actually check the connector data for a valid
hostname defined in the StorPool configuration.

_storpool_client_id(): new method to get the numeric ID of a host in
the StorPool cluster from the /etc/storpool.conf file.

_attach_volume(), _detach_volume(): if the "remote" flag is set, pass
the request on to the default Cinder driver implementation; it knows
how to make remote volumes accessible.

_attach_volume(), _detach_volume(): support the case when these methods
are invoked from a method that is not overridden in the StorPool Cinder
driver - create a storpool.spopenstack.AttachDB attachment structure
and destroy it upon detaching.

ensure_export(): add a stub method, the actual work is handled by
the Nova volume attachment driver.

retype(): new method: handle a StorPool-to-StorPool retyping where
at most the volume's StorPool template or replication is changed.
For anything else, return False to indicate an unsupported request so
that a full volume migration is triggered.

update_migrated_volume(): rename the StorPool volume to correspond to
the real Cinder volume's name.

Add the StorPoolConfigurationMissing and StorPoolConfigurationInvalid
exceptions.

Flesh out the validate_connector() and initialize_connection() unit tests.

Implements: blueprint storpool-block-driver
Implements: blueprint abc-driver-update
Implements: blueprint volume-retype
Change-Id: I5c29cb5f679b08b8db664c9f20cf24cbcd7c6c60

commit_message:
Revert "Remove unused map_nbd function"

This reverts commit ea4a823810c4b7794bf540bd26f2e3b1b8788fbb.

This function was actually still in use in lib/common-functions
and removing it causes the disk-image-get-kernel /bin
to fail entirely.

Change-Id: Icddb3ca369922a6ea915af8b1b62c434cb1bdf28
Closes-bug: 1464031

Searchlight is a new project being split out of Glance based on the
Glance Catalog Index Service, which was developed and released in
Kilo [1]. We received community and operator feedback that this
would be very useful for more than just Glance. At the Liberty
Summit it was  decided to broaden the scope and make it its own
project with a mission to provide advanced and scalable search across
multi-tenant cloud resources. This was presented and discussed
at both Glance and Horizon fishbowl sessions dedicated to this
topic where it was enthusiastically received.

A narrated screencast of the demo shown at the summit is
available at the project wiki [2].

The project is being launched based on a deep history of following
all of the principles of the OpenStack way:

While in Glance, 21 Engineers at 6 different companies contributed in
design sessions, code, or related reviews to the Catalog Index
Service. The concepts that directly led to it becoming a part of
Glance were first presented at the Juno summit, taking some
inspiration from search concepts previously discussed at the
IceHouse summit.

All code has been developed under an Apache license and all
library dependencies allow for unrestricted distribution and
deployment. It has been developed in Gerrit under the Glance project
with only this initial separation from Glance being copied to github.
No further work will be done on the codebase until the project is
back under the Gerrit system.

All previous IRC meetings have been held in the Glance IRC meetings,
but now have an approved IRC meeting [2] of its own in
started using #openstack-searchlight for open discussion.

The project will initially have a co-PTL with Travis Tripp and
Nikhil Komawar (current Glance PTL) to launch the project and regular
elections will be held to elect the PTL. The initial set of drivers
(currently 12) is based on shared interest and contribution to the
service while it was in Glance.

Searchlight is compatible with OpenStack APIs, and uses Keystone
middleware to integrate with OpenStack Identity. It also consumes
notifications from other OpenStack services and implements a plugin
mechanism for resource abstraction.

[1] http://specs.openstack.org/openstack/glance-specs

[2] https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Searchlight

[3] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/186060/

commit_message:
Add the Searchlight Project:

Searchlight is a new project being split out of Glance based on the
Glance Catalog Index Service, which was developed and released in
Kilo [1]. We received community and operator feedback that this
would be very useful for more than just Glance. At the Liberty
Summit it was  decided to broaden the scope and make it its own
project with a mission to provide advanced and scalable search across
multi-tenant cloud resources. This was presented and discussed
at both Glance and Horizon fishbowl sessions dedicated to this
topic where it was enthusiastically received.

A narrated screencast of the demo shown at the summit is
available at the project wiki [2].

The project is being launched based on a deep history of following
all of the principles of the OpenStack way:

While in Glance, 21 Engineers at 6 different companies contributed in
design sessions, code, or related reviews to the Catalog Index
Service. The concepts that directly led to it becoming a part of
Glance were first presented at the Juno summit, taking some
inspiration from search concepts previously discussed at the
IceHouse summit.

All code has been developed under an Apache license and all
library dependencies allow for unrestricted distribution and
deployment. It has been developed in Gerrit under the Glance project
with only this initial separation from Glance being copied to github.
No further work will be done on the codebase until the project is
back under the Gerrit system.

All previous IRC meetings have been held in the Glance IRC meetings,
but now have an approved IRC meeting [2] of its own in
started using #openstack-searchlight for open discussion.

The project will initially have a co-PTL with Travis Tripp and
Nikhil Komawar (current Glance PTL) to launch the project and regular
elections will be held to elect the PTL. The initial set of drivers
(currently 12) is based on shared interest and contribution to the
service while it was in Glance.

Searchlight is compatible with OpenStack APIs, and uses Keystone
middleware to integrate with OpenStack Identity. It also consumes
notifications from other OpenStack services and implements a plugin
mechanism for resource abstraction.

[1] http://specs.openstack.org/openstack/glance-specs
    /specs/kilo/catalog-index-service.htm

[2] https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Searchlight

[3] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/186060/

Change-Id: I8b44aac03585c651ef8d5e94624f64a0ed2d10b2

commit_message:
fix grenade phase check

The check for which phase grenade was working on was based on checking
the contents of a variable passed in to setup_localrc file. However,
this was changes from localrc_old to localrc_oldnew sometime during
the multinode work, but one call to it remained. That meant all
devstacks were told they were GRENADE_PHASE=target.

It didn't seem to be hurting anything, but we should fix this fact.

Change-Id: I1a4b888a493c0b99200b2574d279039e3d5f4ef3

commit_message:
Adding a revert_all option to retry controllers

When a retry controller is added to a nested flow, with the exception of
AlwaysRetryAll, existing retry controllers do not cause a revert of
predecessor tasks in the surrounding flow.  This is due to the fact that
these retry controllers always return RETRY.

The revert_all option, when set True, will result in the retry
controller returning REVERT_ALL rather than REVERT, which will cause
predecessor tasks in the surrounding flow to also be REVERTed.

Change-Id: I2d867b2d05e8559121ec48fd7249f15078450532

commit_message:
Replace ssh exec calls with paramiko lib

Nova already has a dependency on paramiko and therefore should
take advantage of it for generating key pairs.  This will reduce
the code complexity and remove calls to exec.

Change-Id: Ibb01f5227ded9b79816c064a06a1f6724f765e78

A couple of asides based on my observations which are not directly related to the patch set, but something I believe we should be eventually moving towards.

It's obvious the current configuration group implementation has been written around MySQL and it works. I actually like the design, but we are starting hitting some of those assumptions as we start implementing other datastores.

I think that:

- The configuration commands should be 'calls' not 'tasks'. They just update config file on the guestagent and possibly execute some client queries.

(assuming the current implementation with tasks)
- The task manager should not perform any operations on configuration values other than checking the validation rules. The configuration management should be left on the guestagent because it knows its configuration format and how to parse it.
An example of this in the current codebase would be how the taskmanager resolves 'K,M,G' suffixes into multiples of 1024. That may be OK for MySQL, but not for other datastores.

- The taskmanager should not make any additional assumptions about the Json objects other than validating them against the rules. The reason is again that it's only the guestagent who knows what to expect and how to work with it (an example could be lists, which are valid Json objects used by other datastores, but currently not supported as that data structure was not needed for MySQL).

- The configuration template should be resolved on the guestagent too because while the taskmanager has only the instance flavor the guestagent has access to more details including OS and again, it knows its configuration format.

- We should probably get rid of the config.override.template altogether. Although the template mechanism makes perfect sense in the context of the default configuration (e.g. resolving the amount of RAM) the user defined values should be passed down as given.

- apply_overrides and update_overrides interfaces take different objects. apply takes a dict with config values and update takes a resolved string (config.override.template).
I believe that all methods should accept the values in a dict form and apply their parsing strategies (implemented as codecs by this patch set).

- The update/remove overrides should be fixed. When overrides are removed the code currently really calls update with new overrides set to the defaults. This strategy may work for MySQL which just blasts it to the imported configuration file, but it does not work that well with datastores that do not support 'imports' of configuration files - i.e. they must have only a single configuration file containing all values. The taskmanager should just call remove on the guest and let it (it's configuration manager) handle it."}, {'account_id': 14576, 'date': '2015-06-11 20:38:59.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

To sum it up I believe we should be moving towards making the configuration commands 'calls'. Understanding that may be a significant issue we should at least decouple the configuration processing from the taskmanager and let the guestagent Configuration Manager handle it. The configuration templates and their resolution should also be moved to the guestagent.

Again. This is out of scope of this proposal, but sooner or later will have to be addressed."}, {'account_id': 10440, 'date': '2015-06-11 21:08:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review+1

I think that it makes sense to move as much down to the guest as possible -- clearly it has the most knowledge about itself. 

A great example of this is the rather unpleasant hack of the config templating system I had to do in order to get pgsql working on fedora/redhat: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/188912/

At some point, it would be good to have a cleaner way of solving the above problem.'}, {'account_id': 4240, 'date': '2015-06-12 03:43:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)

Make sure to address odd ball configs files.'}, {'account_id': 14576, 'date': '2015-06-12 05:19:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

When I first thought about how to make the config file I was thinking the easiest way was to make the guest agnostic of the config file format because all it should be doing it writing a file or "applying" the config variables to the datastore (e.g. mysql). Using a jinja template allowed us to create any format of a config file you need from a dictionary of items. So in the codec are you still using a jinja template to serialize the file? Are just moving that logic into the guest?'}, {'account_id': 9664, 'date': '2015-06-12 17:03:32.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)

I think there are still issues that need to be hashed out. The first is whether 2.6 support is required or not. If it is not required, that makes things easier.

I propose making it explicit that 2.6 support won't be available.

Then there's the issue of comments. What happens to them, do you retain them?

Also, I will reiterate my earlier comment (from patch set 1) and request a more concrete example of the use-case."}, {'account_id': 14576, 'date': '2015-06-12 17:50:16.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Ad comments: The comments are not preserved, but neither they are in the current implementation. I don't think there is much added value in preserving the comments on the guestagent which is mostly locked down anyway. The comments can be added to the base configuration template."}, {'account_id': 9664, 'date': '2015-06-12 18:04:02.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Code-Review+2

Thanks Petr, I'll follow up with cp16net re: 2.6."}, {'account_id': 14576, 'date': '2015-06-12 18:18:27.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

@Craig I really did not want to make any changes above the guestagent. The configuration manager works with Python/JSON dicts.
You give it a dict of values (possibly nested) and it uses a given codec to serialize it to a file written to the disk. Similarly, it uses the same codec to deserialize it back to a dict.

It turns out that all guestagents (including MySQL) need to make adjustments to the configuration values. They each end up implementing their own logic to do serialization/update/deserialization/file handling. I just abstracted this out into the configuration manager which sits in one of the guestagent classes (usually App). The methods then access the configuration via this manager. The can use its methods to update/rewrite/retrieve etc. values from the underlying configuration file using a common interface like:

self.configuration_manager = ConfigurationManager(<config_file>, <owner>, <group>, IniCodec())

# Updating the base configuration file (<config_file>):
self.configuration_manager.save_configuration({'section1': {'key1': 10, 'key2': False},
					       'section2': {'key1': 'bar'}}})
self.configuration_manager.get_value('section1')['key2'] # False
self.configuration_manager.update_configuration({'section1': {'key2': True}})
self.configuration_manager.get_value('section1')['key2'] # True

# Attaching/detaching overrides:
self.configuration_manager.set_override_strategy(RollingOverrideStrategy(<backup_dir>))
self.configuration_manager.apply_override({'section2': {'key1': 'foo'}})
self.configuration_manager.apply_override({'section1': {'key1': 20}}) # Exception - max. number of overrides exceeded.
self.configuration_manager.get_value('section2')['key1'] # foo
self.configuration_manager.remove_override()
self.configuration_manager.get_value('section2')['key1'] # bar
self.configuration_manager.remove_override() # Exception - no overrides to remove.

I added similar methods for handling serialized input.

BTW, as currently implemented the override strategies work with any number of overrides, so you can push (apply) them over each other and pop (remove) one-by-one. The strategies themselves are not supposed to enforce any limits, that's the manager's job. The limit is currently set to '1' to match the current Trove behavior which allows only one override at a time."}, {'account_id': 14576, 'date': '2015-06-12 18:23:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

I think that JINJA templates are good for the base config template in that they allow for values like 0.5 * {{AMOUNT_OF_RAM}}.

This patch set does not touch any of that. The guestagent just takes whatever it gets from the task manager and if needed deserializes->updates->serializes it (this is all done by its configuration manager instance).

I am not sure how much value JINJA templates provide for override templates that just take values from the user input.'}, {'account_id': 14576, 'date': '2015-06-12 18:58:37.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-06-12 19:10:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Verified+1

commit_message:
Ensure cloud.cfg.d is present when needed

Before this patch, set-cloud-init-sources errored out because the
parent directory did not exist if for example you were using a
virtualenv to install cloud-init.

Change-Id: Iafb4d523dc98fd2ff1984036993f4801ce7a7354

commit_message:
libvirt: Fix Race between imagebackend and imagecache

ImageCacheManager deletes the base images that
have not been used beyond the time setting.
Because there is some time until process of
deleting base images, there are possibilities that
base image is deleted by image cache process.

This patch fixes problem by updating the base image's
timestamp in process of creating instance from the base image.
That allows to check date of images will be removed
before cache process actually deletes.
We expect it to reduce the cache possibility of problems.

Change-Id: I7d08c9a7ff14bd12e6c37ded44447c196fca9a66
Closes-Bug: #1256838

The nova api here is confusing IMO.

GET/v2/?{tenant_id}?/os-hosts returns a list with "hosts" dict with host_name attribute

GET/v2/?{tenant_id}?/os-hosts/?{host_name}? returns a list with "host" dict and host attribute

I need to comb through this more to figure out what's correct'}, {'account_id': 4690, 'date': '2015-03-23 23:55:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

Finally got done testing some stuff with this, and I find the correct attribute for the __repr__ depends on what call we make.

For c.hosts.list(), host_name is right.

However, for c.hosts.get('hostname') the error is raised similarly:

>>> c.hosts.get('vagrant-ubuntu-trusty-64')
[Traceback (most recent call last):
  File "<stdin>", line 1, in <module>
  File "/usr/local/lib/python2.7/dist-packages/novaclient/v2/hosts.py", line 24, in __repr__
    return "<Host: %s>" % self.host_name
  File "/usr/local/lib/python2.7/dist-packages/novaclient/openstack/common/apiclient/base.py", line 480, in __getattr__
    raise AttributeError(k)
AttributeError: host_name'}, {'account_id': 4690, 'date': '2015-03-23 23:56:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

commit_message:
Fix hostname usage for Host resource.

Adding property to deal with different Nova API
calls, that use different attribute names to
avoid AttributeError

Change-Id: Ib14ce7570ab4f6101038f93d6ef15a823f8074e7
Closes-Bug: #1434167

commit_message:
Flavor created only when flavorid is an integer

Initially, when the "id" was set to non-integer
or non-UUID, the flavor was also created successfully.

Now, with this patch we are able to create a flavor
with "id" only.

Change-Id: I1a67b3c79f0be287c3d9946b6cd7e5cc91cbfad2
Closes-Bug: #1426806

commit_message:
Update quickstart to point to kubernetes 0.15 and v1beta3 manifest

The dev quickstart document needs to be updated to point to the
Kubernetes 0.15.0 release for cloning. The quickstart document also
needs to be updated to point to the v1beta3 manifest for the redis
pod-create example.

Change-Id: Ibf50e6a93ee0f57c82be4117aaf0aae48c339a85
Closes-Bug: #1464689

commit_message:
Display security group id in server details

This patch modifies the '_print_server' method in 'v2/shell.py'
file, to display security group id along with its name in server
details.

Co-Authored-By: Sai Kiran <saikiran@techpatron.co.in>
Closes-Bug: 1394462
Change-Id: I7bc73cbc6801ce44bd6b8a1e0cbff9bac5c62e04

commit_message:
Fix an obvious typo in cluster get_agent()

It doesn't make sense to use python built-in function 'id' here.
Fixes a bug in commit 58fc00a5a61745df88dd5ad7fed8e07712c73e63.

Change-Id: Id4067014b2fc42182e283be2619a233c98fde9ea

commit_message:
Enable all deprecation warnings for test runs

We would like to catch all deprecation warnings during test runs to be
notified in advance about potential problems with next library releases
we depend on.

Change-Id: I876d8c4de88618b01898ab537a44920789d8178e

commit_message:
Revert "Switch from MySQL-python to PyMySQL"

Test to address rally gate breakage

commit_message:
corrected the create volume from snapshot

While creating the volume from snapshot via horizon UI, the volume
is not created from snapshot. It is just creating a volume with
same size of the snapshot.

Fixed the condition used if snapshot_id should be passed when
creating volume. The volume_source_type field is empty string if
launched from Volume Snapshot panel.

Co-Authored-By: Lin Hua Cheng <os.lcheng@gmail.com>

Change-Id: I19ddd572d1a7a028e3ae4dae412ffc54e730e50c
Closes-Bug: #1447288

commit_message:
Install PyMySQL if used

Change Ic609ce136061b753ca692b37509a0b29c60bb8b5 switched to PyMySQL by
default but does not make sure it is installed. This is causing gate
failure in Gnocchi for example:

  http://logs.openstack.org/25/186025/3/check/gate-gnocchi-dsvm-functional-file-mysql/eebd773/logs/devstacklog.txt.gz

Change-Id: I23d313220607fcc8acb95ab43f55b7d9899b9b1f

commit_message:
Add role assignment in keystone wrapper for both v2 and v3

This patch is to adding role assignment (add/remove) in keystone wrapper 
to support both keystone v2 and v3.

Change-Id: I1e664bc0989120022b5d324943b91cf72982617e

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-04-30 08:05:30.000000000', 'message': "Add 'source-id' and 'source-name' support in VNX driver

Currently, VNX driver only supports 'id' as the id-type in manage/unmanage volume.
With release of new version python-cinderclient, 'source-id' and 'source-name' are
preferred id-type when using cinder manage.

This fix is to add 'source-id' and 'source-name' support
and obsolete the self-defined 'id' support.

Change-Id: Ia0619123ff56e44da98c4f12c554474c8fe6093c
closes-bug: 1450280

commit_message:
Add 'source-id' and 'source-name' support in VNX driver

Currently, VNX driver only supports 'id' as the id-type in manage/unmanage volume.
With release of new version python-cinderclient, 'source-id' and 'source-name' are
preferred id-type when using cinder manage.

This fix is to add 'source-id' and 'source-name' support
and obsolete the self-defined 'id' support.

Change-Id: Ia0619123ff56e44da98c4f12c554474c8fe6093c
closes-bug: 1450280

commit_message:
Reduce DEVSTACK_GATE_TIMEOUT for Rally

This gives more time to do cleanup and log relocation after a build
hits the devstack timeout, so that logs are not swallowed whole.

Change-Id: Ie7d95ee59f7695402ef14a041dbac3da3ae530cc
Partial-Bug: 1464363

[{'created': '2015-06-03 19:39:23.000000000', 'message': 'Fix connecting unnecessary iSCSI sessions issue

With "iscsi_use_multipath=true", attaching a multipath
iSCSI volume may create unnecessary iSCSI sessions.
The iscsiadm discovery command in connect_volume() returns all of
the targets in the Cinder node, not just the ones related to
the multipath volume which is specified by iqn. If the storage
has many targets, connecting to all these volumes will also
result in many unnecessary connections.

There are two types of iSCSI multipath devices.
One which shares the same iqn between multiple portals,
and the other which use different iqns on different portals.
connect_volume() needs to identify the type by checking iscsiadm
the output if the iqn is used by multiple portals.

This patch changes the behavior of attaching volume:

   1. Identify the type by checking the iscsiadm output.
   2. Connect to the correct targets by connect_to_iscsi_portal().

(Ported from I488ad0c09bf26a609e27d67b9ef60b65bb45e0ad)

commit_message:
Fix connecting unnecessary iSCSI sessions issue

With "iscsi_use_multipath=true", attaching a multipath
iSCSI volume may create unnecessary iSCSI sessions.
The iscsiadm discovery command in connect_volume() returns all of
the targets in the Cinder node, not just the ones related to
the multipath volume which is specified by iqn. If the storage
has many targets, connecting to all these volumes will also
result in many unnecessary connections.

There are two types of iSCSI multipath devices.
One which shares the same iqn between multiple portals,
and the other which use different iqns on different portals.
connect_volume() needs to identify the type by checking iscsiadm
the output if the iqn is used by multiple portals.

This patch changes the behavior of attaching volume:

   1. Identify the type by checking the iscsiadm output.
   2. Connect to the correct targets by connect_to_iscsi_portal().

(Ported from I488ad0c09bf26a609e27d67b9ef60b65bb45e0ad)

Co-Authored-By: Hiroyuki Eguchi <h-eguchi@az.jp.nec.com>
Related-Bug: #1382440
Change-Id: I4c9b173cfab387a55772709242eed69c10168c0f

commit_message:
collect grenade pluginrc if it exists

This collects the grenade pluginrc (used by external grenade plugins)
if it exists. Maybe be an important part of understanding failures.

Change-Id: I2fe62a2ab649ebad39fd9d9c25091798e7dc4ed3

commit_message:
Adding code to prevent vip port deletion from port api

When a lbaas port is deleted from the port delete command from
neutron it tries to delete the port but since it is being held
for the vip the database update fails and neutron throws a 500
error

This fix checks if the vip is associated to the port and allows
deletion of the port only if there is no vip associated with the
port

Change-Id: If9f123dedfe86225c52b6d26c76a64e3f5bee15c
Closes-Bug: #1430394

commit_message:
DO NOT MERGE: Increase ODL_BOOT_WAIT timeout to 1200 seconds

I suspect we're hitting a case in the gate where ODL isn't quite
ready to run yet. Lets crank this way up and verify this. I'm
really looking forward to nailing this one.

Change-Id: Ic8970d6864914ed15083375e3387293b473e3310
Signed-off-by: Kyle Mestery <mestery@mestery.com>

commit_message:
Add rabbitmq max_retries and retry_interval in cinder conf

Oslo.message using rabbit_max_retries and rabbit_retry_interval to
define reconnect rabbitmq server times and interval when can not
connect to rabbitmq server.

Change-Id: I449f7be68dd9c9adbad587a47cf9d9dcc3462369
Closes-bug: #1439968

commit_message:
Allow oslo rabbit heartbeat configuration

In order to allow components to better handle and respond to mq failures,
oslo has some heartbeat options that are useful.

Change-Id: Ib69e69e1ace08448d789f3eb28749d0d228ae00d
Partial-Bug: #1462438

commit_message:
Fix disconnecting necessary iSCSI sessions issue

With "iscsi_use_multipath=true", detaching a multipath iSCSI
volume kills all iSCSI volumes visible from the attached node.
When we use different targets(IQNs) associated with same portal
for each different multipath device, all of the targets will
be deleted via disconnect_volume().

This patch fixes the behavior of detaching volume:

  1. Extract the targets for the detached multipath device.
  2. Delete/disconnect the targets for the detached multipath
     device.

(Ported from I38eafdaee03d136282cfde1fd013e322a4256cc4)

Co-Authored-By: Hiroyuki Eguchi <h-eguchi@az.jp.nec.com>
Closes-Bug: #1382440
Change-Id: I5fdbb5765642bac7263ff616ae4b006d9504547a

commit_message:
Allow create_user to find existing user regardless of tenant

The current code was checking for existing user ONLY in the
requested tenant.  But if the user already existing with another
tenant, the create user call will fail. With this patch, it will
skip the create and succeed, and then the grant_role action can
be used to add a role for this user in the requested tenant.

Change-Id: I0a96ed6103e9a7da7f2e50624ddaff45d2ed9881
Closes-Bug: 1457533

commit_message:
Avoid conflicts with ceilometer.conf in dispatcher tests

This makes sure a critical configuration value
(filter_service_activity) used in the ceilometer dispatcher tests
is explicitly set in the setUp of the test. Otherwise a conflicting
value in /etc/ceilometer/ceilometer.conf can cause tests to fail.

Efforts to make a solution which just ignores
/etc/ceilometer/ceilometer.conf were confounded by too much "helpful"
magic in oslo_config. Given that this dispatcher will be leaving the
gnocchi repo soonish, a long trip down a rabbit hole was skipped.

Change-Id: I8f270183d6c38de0b4088166ddc2da687576a752
Closes-Bug: #1463889

Closes-bug: #1439968

commit_message:
Add rabbitmq max_retries and retry_interval attributes in keystone conf

Oslo.message using rabbit_max_retries and rabbit_retry_interval to
define reconnect rabbitmq server times and interval when can not
connect to rabbitmq server.

Change-Id: I54236d1d0243e73eb27dd8984cfb86f8bbf7a271
Closes-bug: #1439968

commit_message:
revert to eventlet based keystone upgrade for juno -> kilo

While both juno and kilo keystone in devstack support wsgi, they don't
support code only upgrade. This reverts back to the eventlet based
upgrade testing for this transition.

Change the testing variable from GRENADE_BASE_BRANCH to
GRENADE_NEW_BRANCH because it looks like BASE_BRANCH is not always
exported.

Change-Id: Ic9174f6f959f95eabf76ba8b8a19729898194a61

personally I don't care much about what you log and how you log it (within reason).  Ivan makes some valid points, if you don't want to follow them I guess some of that's ok.

The issue of "I have a BP to do cleanup after merge" however I find troubling.  The initial version hasn't even landed, and you have a BP up to fix things?  That's lame, why not just submit a 'good' driver from the start.

Honestly, we all think of "better" ways to do things and things we might want to optimize or cleanup as we go, and that's absolutely great.  BUT, please don't put up a blueprint for it, especially before you even merge the initial version.  We all know that things iterate.

As far as things like logging standards and such, as much of a pain as it's become and as seemingly ridiculous it might be, just fix things.

commit_message:
Add iSCSI protocol support for IBM FlashSystem

This change implements iSCSI protocol for Cinder driver.
It is inherited from driver.ISCSIDriver and flashsystem.py.
We will separate flashsystem.py into common and FC protocol.

iSCSI test result:
https://bugs.launchpad.net/cinder/+bug/1406442

Implements: blueprint ibm-flashsystem-driver-iscsi
Change-Id: Ie6cc2315e9d770302fcdfb63873da1b0dea12bda

commit_message:
Resize cisco_csr_identifier_map.ipsec_site_conn_id

Some database engines require exact match of sizes of foreign keys
and referenced fields. Foreign key ipsec_site_conn_id of table
cisco_csr_identifier_map is varchar(64) but it references field
id varchar(36) of table ipsec_site_connections. This gives error
while running migration scripts in such databases.

Change-Id: I384a9bbaba05ef94174b666bdcfb276eedc74134
Closes-Bug: #1463806

Revert "change the default to PyMYSQL"

The failure rate with neutron is too high to keep this
as the default.

This reverts commit b3798af474955368211a297ba85332fde5491993.

So, I'm having a tough time with the ideas in this spec. While I certainly think that the cells stuff should be aligned with the non-cells stuff in Nova, I think it would be a mistake to modify the regular nova-scheduler by simply adding cells calculations to the main FilterScheduler.

The current architecture of the nova-scheduler is entirely non-scalable. It's a centralized point of failure and bottleneck in that a single scheduler process is responsible for handling all of the placement requests for the entire deployment or cell. While you can have multiple scheduler daemons, and broadcast select_destinations() RPC API calls to the multiple schedulers, each scheduler has to keep the entire state of the system's resource pool in memory -- or continually re-read it from the database.

This is not a horizontally scalable architecture, and adding the cell placement functionality into it makes this worse than the tiered architecture we currently have. Under this plan, the scheduler processes would need to know about all the cell information in addition to all the system resource pool information.

I'm going to think on this more, but I have a bad feeling about this one...

Best,

-jay"}, {'account_id': 5441, 'date': '2015-04-02 13:21:10.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

Jay, I completely agree.  What I'm trying to focus on here is that from the Nova (outside the scheduler) point of view it should be possible to make one call to get a claim/placement.  I think that the scheduler should be tiered to handle that, or otherwise re-architected.  And in order to hide that from the rest of Nova we can have a scheduler client that makes requests to a cell scheduler and then a host scheduler, or we can hide that behind the scheduler API.  My preference is to hide that behind the scheduler API.  And the main point of this spec is to say that the scheduler should take certain input, currently unchanged, and provide certain output.

That being said what this spec is proposing may be getting too deep into details that fall within the scheduler.  I included them mainly because I want to document things that I think should inform the direction of the scheduler.  But there may be a better place for that."}, {'account_id': 5441, 'date': '2015-04-07 23:53:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

I should add that we should find a solution that allows us to schedule for cellsv2 in Lemming.'}, {'account_id': 7166, 'date': '2015-04-13 19:47:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

commit_message:
Proposal for cells v2 scheduling interaction

The scheduler should be called earlier in the build process so that an
instance can be created in the proper cell.

blueprint cells-scheduling-interaction

Change-Id: I9fbbb107cb148aee4404f6fa3f06021edf3fa5b4

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-04-30 13:52:13.000000000', 'message': "Wake-On-Lan Power interface

This patch implements a simple Wake-On-Lan power interface. For those
that does not have any fancy hardware just old PCs at home.

Wake-On-Lan is only capable of powering ON the machine, so it's
recommended to use the DIB ramdisk for testing the deployments with it
because it does a soft reboot on the machine at the end of the deployment.

After the machine is unprovisioned, you'll have to manually power it
off :-)

This patch also doesn't implement SecureON password feature for
Wake-On-Lan, I left a TODO in the code for those willing to implement it.

Change-Id: I6c0f98ef1cab1ebfb4a7e1d0aaae29672db1c5a4

commit_message:
Wake-On-Lan Power interface

This patch implements a simple Wake-On-Lan power interface. For those
that does not have any fancy hardware just old PCs at home.

Wake-On-Lan is only capable of powering ON the machine, so it's
recommended to use the DIB ramdisk for testing the deployments with it
because it does a soft reboot on the machine at the end of the deployment.

After the machine is unprovisioned, you'll have to manually power it
off :-)

This patch also doesn't implement SecureON password feature for
Wake-On-Lan, I left a TODO in the code for those willing to implement it.

Implements: blueprint wol-power-driver
Change-Id: I6c0f98ef1cab1ebfb4a7e1d0aaae29672db1c5a4

commit_message:
Add power_off command in standby extension

This commit adds a new command power_off to
standby extension which runs shutdown -h now
on the system. This commit also adds mappings
for /proc and /sys in cloud-config.yml for the
agent service spawned.

Partial-Bug: #1451310
Change-Id: I2a5f984af26bbbe03002bb8c367c8c6af8d91434

commit_message:

commit_message:
Purge soft deleted rows

Soft delete punts responsibility for database cleanup to operators. If
operators fail to manage this properly, the database fills up with
deleted rows and query performance degrades severely. This spec offers a
way to ask Nova to take care of this.

blueprint purge-soft-deleted-rows

Change-Id: I5dc3809c063e30a550e250e251dce52c546a4d85

commit_message:
Port basic installation guide

Convert RPC installation guide from DocBook to RST,
remove content specific to Rackspace, and create initial
OSAD installation guide.

Change-Id: I3eedadc8ba441b4d931720dd6e3f7f3489302a9c
Co-Authored-By: Matt Kassawara <mkassawara@gmail.com>
(cherry picked from commit f9f907732ef47e4301e808f863c3c56059b043db)

commit_message:
MongoDB single instance backup and restore

Uses the mongodump and mongorestore tools against a single
instance of mongodb.

Due to the poor support for streaming backups in MongoDB as
of version 3.0, a backup is done inside volume storage, then
compressed and streamed out to object storage. Restore operates
inversely.

Backup makes a best effort to determine if there is enough
available disk space before starting.

Change-Id: I679f49f4945ec42332e74db44b7739185de0eb83
Depends-On: I312a77edf8a59f5e21b9b69031dbd2b063862fe3
Implements: blueprint backups-single-instance-mongodb
Co-Authored-By: Ramashri Umale <rumale@ebaysf.com>

commit_message:
Use mongodb 3 instead of 2.4

Make redstack kick-start install mongodb 3.0 instead of 2.4.
This requires some extra work for apt to retrieve the packages.

Change-Id: I312a77edf8a59f5e21b9b69031dbd2b063862fe3

commit_message:
Move swift_allow_all_users to role defaults

We currently default swift_allow_all_users in
etc/openstack_deploy/user_variables.yml instead of
playbooks/roles/os_swift/defaults/main.yml.  If a deployer removes this
variable from etc/openstack_deploy/user_variables.yml, the swift
playbook will fail.  This commit moves the variable default to
playbooks/roles/os_swift/defaults/main.yml.

Change-Id: I9a73eda990327bf427f40a13965484fde00cbe21
Closes-Bug: #1424981

commit_message:
Pass Down the Instance Name to Ironic Driver

In order to access the display_name from the Ironic driver, it must be passed
to it by Nova. Nowadays it's not possible to retrieve this information.

Co-Authored-By: Alberto Barros <albertoffb@lsd.ufcg.edu.br>
Co-Authored-By: Caio Oliveira <caiobo@lsd.ufcg.edu.br>

Co-Authored-By: Sinval Vieira <sinval@lsd.ufcg.edu.br>
Co-Authored-By: Thiago Paiva <thiagop@lsd.ufcg.edu.br>

Change-Id: I52973bd84a0f213d9b180a8a4e1e12899952b2de

tests the _hard_reboot method). The existing test case included a
single assertion that checked the return value of _get_guest_xml;
this functionality is extracted into the new test_get_guest_xml
method. The remainder of test_power_on is cleaned up by removing
unnecessary variables, mocks, etc. to reflect what was actually being
tested.

commit_message:
libvirt: Remove unit tests for _hard_reboot

This commit removes the test_power_on test case, which actually
tested the _hard_reboot method. The only assertion in the test case
checked the return value of _get_guest_xml, which is covered by
other unit tests.

Change-Id: I16d1f3a407660a148d13737240f3982c3d701590

- gate-nova-specs-python27 http://logs.openstack.org/27/127827/1/check/gate-nova-specs-python27/3b0f6a7 : SUCCESS in 1m 26s'}, {'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2014-10-15 16:59:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

I am weary of adding support for yet another thing. We already support so many different backends (virt, db, mq, networking etc.). I am concerned about the maintenance impact on adding another kernel. Do other projects need code changes to support FreeBSD? If so I would like to see a broader discussion on adding FreeBSD support to all of OpenStack (what work needs to be done, what are the pros and cons etc.).'}, {'account_id': 6509, 'date': '2014-10-15 17:19:54.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

If we're talking about minimal setup, such as nova (including nova-network) + glance + keystone, then only nova requires changes. Last time I checked, glance and keystone worked fine (the only problem I found with glance was usage of some GNU specific flags for 'du' that was fixed already).

Taking about Nova, it needs few modifications other than networking, specifically:

- provide a version of nova.virt.disk.mount that uses FreeBSD's mdconfig(8) instead of Linux's losetup,
- libvirt driver itself most likely will need minor changes to support bhyve (I think that would be the last thing to do in Nova, because it'd be reasonable to start with running libvirt/qemu on FreeBSD first).

If we add Cinder to the mix, it'll require some volume driver that's available on FreeBSD, e.g. ZFS (IIRC I've seen an implementation floating around) and, quite likely, some minor portability fixes."}, {'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2014-10-15 17:23:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

We should include cinder in the mix. I think support for FreeBSD in OpenStack warrants a ML thread since this will require changes to at least two projects (cinder and nova).'}, {'account_id': 6509, 'date': '2014-10-16 12:15:13.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

By the way, the was a thread on this topic back in March: http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2014-March/031431.html. Do I get it right that I need to start a new thread on the maillist with an overview of what's need to be done to add FreeBSD host support to OpenStack?"}, {'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2014-10-16 17:31:03.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

If this has the same limitations as the previous thread: http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2014-March/031431.html, this is a no-go.  If this doesn't have those limitations then yes I think a new thread is in order."}, {'account_id': 1779, 'date': '2014-10-20 08:15:39.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2

I don't think it is a productive use of time to try and analyse every openstack project upfront to identify all places that need FreeBSD porting. Suggesting that be a pre-requisite is effectively an attempt to kill the FreeBSD port under a mountain of paperwork before it has even begun. Even if there were a document outlining everything that needed changing across every project I'd be very sceptical that it were accurate or complete since with this kind of porting effort is damn hard to identify problems by mere code inspection. You need to actually try running the functionality and/or testing it to identify the problems. It is much more practical to take an iterative approach, tackling the porting problem in small easily digestible chunks as they are identified. 

The existing Nova network setup code is a real big tangled web of horror. This proposal for unravelling the mess is worthwhile effort even if we were not intending todo a BSD port. 

So I'm happy to see this work done and don't think we need to identify every piece of BSD porting work upfront"}, {'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2014-10-20 17:38:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Workflow-1

commit_message:
libvirt/linux_net refactor to work on FreeBSD

A proposal to implement freebsd_net and refactor libvirt.vif
module not use use only linux_net, but allow to choose
what network driver to use.

Change-Id: Icf6f1358abe21f1414507cd7a4dd4b05bce7afc5

Overall, I'm for this idea, but not necessarily for the reasons listed (specifically, making commenting/documenting the file easier).

I think that doing this will help logically group configuration options, and provide specific locations for end users to look, and serve as a model for any projects extending os-ansible-deployment.

Like I state in my in-line comment, I think providing a 'big picture' document would probably be better done outside of a configuration file. The comments, at least to me, should serve to describe the setting/variable's place in the overall structure."}, {'account_id': 9515, 'date': '2015-05-14 16:37:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

I'm overall +1. One thing concerns me though. If we aren't careful when we implement this, we could end up creating a list of files that can override each other. In other words, if we load hosts.yml and then networking.yml and merge the two resulting dictionaries, the order in which we merge them will override settings from the first one. I think this means that we'll be providing a footgun to the user which we shouldn't do.

In that case, a follow-up proposal should be made that starts using something to make sure items aren't defined in those files that shouldn't be. Specifically, I'm thinking of something like https://github.com/sigmavirus24/schema-validator. We could make the schemas very light to begin with and add more validation as we find it necessary. Whether this is run by the user out of band, or as a pre-requisite for running the playbooks, this will be something to further improve the user experience. Instead of accidentally overriding something incorrectly, they'll get feedback."}, {'account_id': 7217, 'date': '2015-06-04 12:32:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

I agree with Ian that the potential for defining the same thing twice is a problem. Having commented out examples of each config option in the appropriate file would probably help users to specify them in the right places.


Validation would be quite tricky as we want to allow unknown keys so that role defaults can be overridden, but we would want to disallow keys that are specified in another config file. So we would have to list all the keys of every other config file in the schema? That seems like a maintenance headache. Maybe the schema for each file could be generated from some master list of keys? 


Maybe config schema should be its own spec.'}, {'account_id': 7353, 'date': '2015-06-10 19:00:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review+2'}, {'account_id': 7414, 'date': '2015-06-12 14:54:52.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Code-Review+2 Workflow+1

This looks good to me, I agree with the concerns of Ian and Hugh so we'll have to be very careful and consistent when this is implemented, but overall I very much support the idea of modularization."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-06-12 14:54:57.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: -Verified

commit_message:
libvirt: convert imagebackend to support nova.virt.image.model classes

Add a new 'get_model' method to nova.virt.libvirt.imagebackend.Image
class that returns an instance of nova.virt.image.model.Image. This
allows us to break the assumption that we only inject files into
plain file based images, enabling support for RBD too.

Closes-Bug: #1257674
Change-Id: I4effa2d4d7b4d8da6a703451857e17bcbdb0b5c3

commit_message:
Add a script for building courtesy ping list for PTLs

The cross-project meeting starts with a courtesy ping for each PTL. Now
that we are adding more projects, it is useful to have a tool to build
the list instead of keeping a static copy somewhere.

Change-Id: If23bf302e912557fbb44b5e68747956308bccf64

I'm still +1 to this. Ramesh and I have talked about it a couple times and I think it's a good idea. 

One thing I want to point out is that when implementing, we should make this available to cleaning as well (which it looks like it will, but good to keep in mind). If I hand a tenant a box, when they're done with it, I probably want to reset it to the original RAID level. So I'm envisioning when deploying a new node, use the RAID interface to add the expected config to the node, then when moving from MANAGEABLE -> AVAILABLE, during that cleaning, it can configure my RAID (if enabled, definitely not the default). Then every time a tenant is done, the RAID can be reset."}, {'account_id': 6804, 'date': '2015-05-07 00:23:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 8106, 'date': '2015-05-07 07:53:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

commit_message:
Add Quota support for Barbican resources

This spec aims at implementing quota support for the Barbican resources
"secrets", "orders", "containers" and "transport keys".  Moving the
spec from Kilo to Liberty directory.

Also: fixed some typos, updated assignee, and updated implementation
details based on current status of oslo.common.quotas.

Change-Id: Iff773fb4ab0814096156f58b1c9f7bb3fc43e681

commit_message:
virt: convert disk API over to use nova.virt.image.model

Convert the nova.virt.disk.api methods over to use the
nova.virt.image.model classes instead of taking a file
path and use_cow boolean as parameters.

Related-Bug: #1257674
Change-Id: I34e2f29e1f068636036226a7745d88640f724d93

@Dave - This patch is an incremental improvement on the handling of mongodb loss/restart scenarios for some tolerance of high availability of the data store. 

The other patch adds in the ability to use the MongoReplicaSetClient which is aware of the various nodes within the mongo cluster and allows failing over to the other nodes and introduces the handling of the AutoReconnect exception raised on loss of the primary. This patch builds upon that and adjusts the behavior to wrap the Cursor object to handle more a broader range of queries.

Hopefully that clears up the relation between the two patches a bit.'}, {'account_id': 13273, 'date': '2014-12-16 13:14:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 10721, 'date': '2015-01-07 08:42:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 4491, 'date': '2015-01-08 06:44:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 12927, 'date': '2015-01-16 07:23:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-12-09 04:05:14.000000000', 'message': 'Retry to connect database when DB2 or mongodb is restarted

The patch https://review.openstack.org/#/c/122387 works fine
with operations with get, record and update functions.
But exception would still occured with the operation of
db.collection.find() function.

This patch can give some benefit to tolerate DB restart
with find() function.

commit_message:
Retry to connect database when DB2 or mongodb is restarted

The patch https://review.openstack.org/#/c/122387 works fine
with operations with get, record and update functions.
But exception would still occured with the operation of
db.collection.find() function.

This patch can give some benefit to tolerate DB restart
with find() function.
This patch also removes "test_mongo_find" test case since
it doesn't raise AutoReconnect exception at all.

Closes-Bug: #1389985
Change-Id: Ia0474726960ce2b4b611fda0a1c304bb8ad96922
(cherry-picked from commit 8c6841d3c00931204eaba0e9058707629120c1da)

commit_message:
[MongoDB] Fix bug with reconnection to new master node

Fixes bug with raising AutoReconnect exception when MongoDB ReplicaSet
loses connection to primary node.

Closes-Bug: #1309555

Conflicts:
	ceilometer/event/storage/impl_db2.py
	ceilometer/event/storage/impl_mongodb.py
	ceilometer/storage/__init__.py
	ceilometer/storage/mongo/utils.py
        ceilometer/tests/storage/test_pymongo_base.py

Conflicts are due to refactoring of the storage drivers and this patch
has been modified to account for the refactor. The test case within the
file test_pymongo_base.py was removed since equivalent test coverage
was included in the cherry picked commit in the test_storage_scenarios.py
file.

Change-Id: Id0e81ba60b28d09adff6a10d04b412f25257d8ce
(cherry-picked from commit 21d882c96cbbaeb8b78ff91e06e3615be97bff07)

commit_message:
Reserve Redis VIP from Neutron instead of hardcoding

Also adds GenericPort for controllers, because the network on which we
want to create the Redis VIP is defined by ServiceNetMap, so we don't
know that statically and cannot hardcode it into the template to be on
some specific network.

Change-Id: I9284153b47bb9c13148264a49b9e66f3a2261d21
Co-Authored-By: Giulio Fidente <gfidente@redhat.com>

commit_message:
Don't specify a nova region by default

The nova region config option isn't required and doesn't need
to be set when using one region. Remove the default of 'RegionOne'
and don't specify the option at all by default.

Change-Id: Ie17187fcb74d11465cf08d57a85c30766760d7f2
Closes-bug: #1452092

commit_message:
Fix skipped image create attribute location attr

Image create action accepts attribute called location,
in method body is list of allowed attributes, which contain
localtion, what is typo and this attribute was not passed to
glance. Fixed.

Change-Id: I357b06b63b8aa97f7a5f587ef3fcee7a4b360ed1
Closes-Bug: #1445460

[{'created': '2015-04-23 13:07:18.000000000', 'message': 'Enable rabbit_heartbeats for all MOS services

W/o this fix rabbit_heartbeats use inoptimal defaults
and are enabled not for all OpenStack services. This is
an issue as it may lead to unstable failover procedure for
open AMQP conversations.

The solution is to enable heartbeats both server and client sided,
for example for nova-conductor and nova-compute, for neutron-server
and all of its agents, and follow recommendations from the scale lab
testing team to set rabbit_heartbeat to 520 as this parameter should
be lower then 580, which is a default timeout of the rabbitmq-server.

Note, that rabbit_heartbeats option is
avaiable only in MOS Juno and later it could be replaced to upstream
implementation in Kilo as well.

Closes-bug: #1447559

Change-Id: I1f477f27ba5bb11b3cf6150c51f8da4e1e7fb963
Signed-off-by: Bogdan Dobrelya <bdobrelia@mirantis.com>
'}, {'created': '2015-05-15 14:35:02.000000000', 'message': 'Enable rabbit_heartbeats for all MOS services but Neutron

W/o this fix AMQP heartbeats are disabled and may lead
to broken state of some Openstack services, for example like
it was described here https://bugs.launchpad.net/fuel/+bug/1289200

This is an issue as it may lead to unstable failover procedure for
open AMQP conversations.

The solution is to enable heartbeats both server and client sided,
for example for nova-conductor and nova-compute, and follow
recommendations from the scale lab testing team to set
rabbit_heartbeat to 520 as this parameter should be lower then 580,
which is a default timeout of the rabbitmq-server.

Note, that rabbit_heartbeats option is
avaiable only in MOS Juno and later it must be replaced to upstream
implementation in Kilo as well.
Note, Neutron should not use rabbit_heartbeat option as it may not
work as expected for Neutron server and agents. For Neutron, we will
switch to upstream Heartbeats in Kilo as well as for other related
Openstack services.

Closes-bug: #1447559

Change-Id: I1f477f27ba5bb11b3cf6150c51f8da4e1e7fb963
Signed-off-by: Bogdan Dobrelya <bdobrelia@mirantis.com>

commit_message:
Enable rabbit_heartbeats for all MOS services

W/o this fix AMQP heartbeats defaults are implicit and may lead
to broken state of some Openstack services, for example like
it was described here https://bugs.launchpad.net/fuel/+bug/1289200
This is an issue as it may lead to unstable failover procedure for
open AMQP conversations.

The solution is to enable explicit values for heartbeats both server
and client sided, for example for nova-conductor and nova-compute,
neutron-server and its agents, and follow recommendations from the
scale lab testing team to set rabbit_heartbeat to 520 as this
parameter should be lower then 580, which is a default timeout of
the rabbitmq-server.

Note, that rabbit_heartbeats option is
avaiable only in MOS Juno and later it must be replaced to upstream
implementation in Kilo as well.

Closes-bug: #1447559

Change-Id: I1f477f27ba5bb11b3cf6150c51f8da4e1e7fb963
Signed-off-by: Bogdan Dobrelya <bdobrelia@mirantis.com>

I have some documentation/process questions wrt this patch.

You're adding a new method for vendor passthru. I don't think we require a spec for it, but I would have thought a bug would be useful (even though it isn't a bug, it is a feature).

Even without a bug, at the very least, it seems like the commit should be explicit about what the new passthru is - the method name, etc.

I believe that we have an endpoint that can be used to discover what passthru methods exist but I still think it would be useful to know what changed during the release cycle.

Does this need a microversion bump?"}, {'account_id': 9315, 'date': '2015-06-11 03:42:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Workflow-1

Oh no - no microversion bump up please :)  

In my opinion, microversion bump up is not required because we are not adding any new API endpoint and the feature added is discoverable with the existing framework.

commit_message:
Add vendor-passthru to attach and boot an ISO

This commit adds a new vendor-passthru 'boot_into_iso' 
in iscsi_ilo driver to attach and boot from an ISO
located in Glance or an HTTP(s) URL.  This vendor passthru
can be invoked only when the node is in manage state or
in maintenance mode.  This vendor-passthru can help in
debugging issues with bare metal node.

Partial-Bug: 1464168
Change-Id: I75c5363b1df13b12c8f025a4b45de02367229f8f

commit_message:
power grab

The current core reviewers hierarchy didn't have a place for the
parts of ML2 that weren't related to agent communication. For now
we can put all of ML2 under the built-in control-plane until we
decide it needs to be put somewhere else.

Change-Id: Ic4924e0041c4cbb955d8fac0f96ec56406d6466e

commit_message:
Replace types.NameType with name

* Replace types.BooleanType with bool
* Replace types.DictionaryType with dict
* Replace types.ListType with list
* Replace types.StringTypes with six.string_types

This change makes the code compatible with Python 3, because all these
types attributes are gone in Python 3.

Change-Id: If3ff794e3b50047ae39c8d2b30c3eda737bfc361

commit_message:
Use keystonemiddleware auth credentials

We support oslo.config, so use Use keystonemiddleware auth credentials
instead of auth options ourselves.
Notes:
Below items will be used to get ironic client forever, not DEPRECATED,
but, in the case of keystone authentication, they are DEPRECATED.
Use [keystone_authtoken]'s items instead of them.
[ironic]
* os_auth_url
* os_username
* os_password
* os_tenant_name
And also this patch set drop default value of os_auth_url and identity_url,
so that this change will break people relying on ether/both of them.

Change-Id: Ib0774b6027bb60910dd4b5c2bc8acea0069ba0a1
Closes-Bug: #1435882

commit_message:
Fixed hashmap migrations for postgresql

Fixed constraint names being duplicated.
Fixed an enum not being removed on downgrade, causing fail on the next
upgrade.
House keeping in migration scripts.

commit_message:
Change pip install method and add six to requirements

Minor changes to make Bifrost's test/installation sequence more
compatible with Centos7.  Attempt easy_install based install
for pip if it is missing and install six from pypi as it
is required by Ansible.

Change-Id: Ia583bcaa15239753b7f50afbae001aff0904efd3
Partial-Bug: 1463871

commit_message:
Correct CSV processing in inventory

Late changes due to suggestions partially broke CSV processing such
that values were not properly evaluated thus resulting in values
not being included in output.

Change-Id: I90a29741149d7718175fceb0f77071e4ce13ef03

gordc redirected me here from https://review.openstack.org/#/c/180929/

Where I said:

-=-=-
I don't think this is the best way to solve this problem. It is insufficiently generic, overly complex and quite brittle. Better to have the version url set from config. This way the service can behind a variety of proxies, load balancers, miscellaneous systems of all sorts, and always know it publishes the right URL because it has been made explicit.

See the glance fix: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/130311/
-=-=-

Generally speaking a modern web app needs to know its base_url from configuration because the path by which a request gets to a WSGI can be tortured and involve not just changes in the url scheme but also the host, port and base path. Consider, for example, someone who wants to front all the various service endpoints under a single host and port and use path redirection to land at the right wsgi app?

It's easier to just declare that the tool which is going to cook a visible, external, fully-qualified URL looks up the base in config (and that config receives a reasonable default)."}, {'account_id': 8124, 'date': '2015-05-11 19:32:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

@Chris: host and port? They are provided by clients in Host header[1] and is mandatory in http/1.1:

  curl http://localhost:8000 -v
 * Rebuilt URL to: http://localhost:8000/
 * Connected to localhost (127.0.0.1) port 8000 (#0)
 > GET / HTTP/1.1
 > User-Agent: curl/7.35.0
 > Host: localhost:8000
 > Accept: */*

Common proxies can forward client provided Host header.

webob supportsHost header and supports base-url in Host header through the pattern: 

  $host[:$port][/$base-url]


[1] http://www.w3.org/Protocols/rfc2616/rfc2616-sec14.html'}, {'account_id': 4190, 'date': '2015-06-03 01:38:16.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

@Cedric, some folk still issue HTTP/0.9 requests: yes 1.0,1.1 and 2 all added more things, but unless we state 'will only work with X', we can't guarantee they are there. 

Secondly, and more importantly, I agree with Chris - this really is something that should be set in the application, because any absolute URLs generated by the app (like Ironic does) need to be correct - and we don't want the middleware to have to sniff-and-rewrite the body of the response.

That said, if this is already in use elsewhere, I am fine with it being added, but it should come with warnings and explanations on what better approaches exist."}, {'account_id': 4190, 'date': '2015-06-03 01:44:07.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)

There's one actual code issue today, see inline.

A further note on the basic approach though - while a config setting does preclude running one instance on many locations at once, this is actually very rare, and entirely unneeded for stateless services : you can just run another instance of the stateless server configured for the Nth location you want it visible at.

There is a hypothetical case where the number of locations is high and the load per-location low, but AFAIK none of the OpenStack services match this scenario today, nor are any planned that would."}, {'account_id': 8124, 'date': '2015-06-09 11:49:43.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 5.'}, {'account_id': 8124, 'date': '2015-06-09 11:49:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

commit_message:
Add middleware to support ssl termination proxies

This change defines SSLMiddleware middleware which enables OpenStack
services behind SSL termination proxies to return urls with original
protocol scheme.

SSLMiddleware is based on heat SSLMiddleware class.

Change-Id: I72f8da160ced6ac80fdac743c00ea3f7ffb1f57c
Closes-Bug: #1444490

commit_message:
Remove old logs when resetting environment

If logs are left, they cause failing of logratate since
there are hanging symlinks left.
It was fixed for removing nodes and fix for resetting must be added.

Change-Id: I047bf4161cf1f76b30bf7a0f5b6d13207d314019
Closes-Bug: #1428150
(cherry picked from commit f39b95b6dc993ba1224ddfab3d1e8ea0848f87d7)

commit_message:
Fix condition in CheckSizeArgForCreate parser action

CheckSizeArgForCreate checks that size is specified when snapshot
or source volume aren't. But when size is 0, CheckSizeArgForCreate
action works wrong and generates error: 'Size is a required
parameter if snapshot or source volume is not specified', meanwhile
user expected to see: 'Volume size '0' must be greater than 0'.

Change-Id: I164970a600d6e86bd7076dd485f676a703f5e487
Closes-Bug: #1454276

commit_message:
Add extended support for Manila project

Add support for following features of Manila:
- Create/delete/list share networks
- Create/delete security services
- Add security service to share network
- List share servers

Change-Id: I045512e4a6967ad3b39170af411ff0222ce35ea8

commit_message:
Provide better detection of failures during message send

This change causes the message sender to block until the messaging
infrastructure (e.g. the broker) assumes ownership of the message (or
fails to accept it).  If the message is accepted, then the sender will
either pend for a response (in the case of RPC), or simply return (in
the case of notification).  If the message is rejected by the
messaging infrastructure a MessagingException will be raised at the
sender.

Change-Id: I3f4a1ed1c17e18f6d629f16e6b5c99de45b083d6
Closes-Bug: #1377228

commit_message:
EMC ScaleIO Cinder Driver

This patch adds a Cinder volume driver for EMC ScaleIO product.
The ScaleIO driver supports the following Cinder features:
* Create/delete volume
* Create/delete snapshot
* Create volume from snapshot
* Create cloned volume
* Extend volume

implements blueprint scaleio-cinder-volume-driver

Change-Id: I7007e4ec36586d98cbf53e4f322ab25aa9b414c6

commit_message:
Allow providing customized event + condition classes/factories

When a green thread pool executor (and eventlet) is used and
the threading module is *not* patched it is required to avoid
using the native threading condition and event classes to ensure
that the eventlet loop is context-switched into.

To make it possible for this periodic worker to work in those
such usages allow for providing the condition and event class
that will be used internally (which should be green equivalents
when eventlet is used).

Change-Id: I82e10e4318936745e84db3418af619523d1cb0c3

commit_message:
Allow providing a executor to be able to run in parallel

Instead of just running one callable at a time it can be
quite useful to run multiple callables that the schedule
says to run in parallel so that it is easily possible to
avoid blocking up the schedule queue.

To make this possible, allow for providing a executor
factory function that can create a executor that will be used
to run callables in parallel (by default it uses the sync
executor, which does *not* run things in parallel to retain
the existing behavior).

Change-Id: I85deacd3ab838beb20ba0a9d014c87e7fd54b806

commit_message:
Hyper-V: Add Fibre Channel support

At the moment, the Hyper-V driver supports attaching volumes only
via iSCSI or SMB. In many cases, using FC based topologies might
be desired.

This blueprint proposes adding Fibre Channel support for the
Hyper-V driver.

blueprint bp/hyperv-fibre-channel

Change-Id: I9b3b58a2dada0f318b5b78b3d3568328f990dae5

commit_message:
change the default to PyMYSQL

As discussed in the Liberty Design Summit "Moving apps to Python 3"
cross-project workshop, the way forward in the near future is to
switch to the pure-python PyMySQL library as a default.

    https://etherpad.openstack.org/p/liberty-cross-project-python3

Change-Id: Ic609ce136061b753ca692b37509a0b29c60bb8b5

commit_message:
Remove old logs when resetting environment

If logs are left, they cause failing of logratate since
there are hanging symlinks left.
It was fixed for removing nodes and fix for resetting must be added.

Change-Id: I047bf4161cf1f76b30bf7a0f5b6d13207d314019
Closes-Bug: #1428150

Hi Ramesh, looks good. A few minor things inline.'}, {'account_id': 6618, 'date': '2015-04-29 15:34:40.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

Hi Ramesh, sorry to be a pain about this. I know we discussed where to store the RAID config from the user; you had initially put it in driver_internal_info, which I disagreed with since that is for internal info, not info from the user, so we agreed on the target_raid_config.

Would you please explain again why it couldn't go in the node's driver_info?

I'm asking because I am somewhat concerned about our model. If the RAID config doesn't belong in driver_info or instance_info, does it make sense to create a third <something>_info? And if so, what would that <something> be? My concern is that another feature FX will show up that also won't fit into our driver/instance_info model and we'd end up special casing that too.

Eg, GET /drivers/<driver>/raid/logical_disk_properties could be covered by 'GET /v1/drivers/properties' if it was in driver_info."}, {'account_id': 9315, 'date': '2015-04-30 07:06:35.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

(2 comments)

Ruby, thanks for the thorough reviews.  I guess it's becoming increasingly complex now.

The root cause of this is because 

* This spec proposes new APIs for RAID configuration and preferably validate the information before it is accepted.
* After the information is validated, the information shouldn't be editable.  Or only validated information is stored.

This is different from a general convention in Ironic that we accept the information through one API and then validate it through another API.

I agree both has it's own pros and cons, but the latter might have more re-usable components with it - as we separate the input acceptance part from input validation part.

I think we could take either of these two approaches:

* Store the input in driver_info (that means no need of a new API) and validate it through our validate API.  Now we could get rid of the PUT API proposed and keep only the GET ones (we can debate on whether we need to keep this as well).

* Store the input in a new field (node.raid_config) or a new-generalized field (node.<something>_info).  This would mean we would have a new API for accepting the input - as the input accepting API will do that validation as well. New APIs would be available for GETTing information as well.

Now, we can decide whether we are seeing a new pattern of things coming in like raid OR we should stick around to our old pattern.  

Now after all this conversation with yours, I have ended up in two minds.  Having a different way of dealing with an interface is kind of confusing to the end user (some interfaces first store the information and then validate [deploy], whereas some others first validate and then store the information [proposed raid]).

May be now we should have only one kind of things.  I am kind of getting into that thought now.  We should keep accepting input through an API and then validate with another.  If everyone thinks so, I could remove the APIs proposed (or keep GET ones) and then use validate() to validate it.

What do you think ?"}, {'account_id': 6618, 'date': '2015-04-30 13:57:19.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

@Ramesh, thanks for the detailed comment! My preference is to use what we have, unless that doesn't make sense. And if it doesn't, then come up with something that is generalizable :-)

Specifically, IF you (and others) think that using driver_info and the existing mechanism makes sense -- user sets raid config in driver_info, validate() validates it, and we'd still want the conductor to validate() all interfaces that are involved with zapping before starting zapping, then that's my preference.

I haven't thought much about the GET APIs you proposed. Some of them may still be useful for the user. (I don't want to think too much on this until after you've thought it through but ahh, where is the information about logical disks and physical disks stored internally, or is it stored?)"}, {'account_id': 9315, 'date': '2015-05-05 16:04:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

Ruby, thanks for the comments.  I think I also agree with that workflow:

1. Operator adds raid configuration to driver_info using node-update. (not a PUT /nodes/<>/raid API)
  ironic node-update add driver_info/target_raid_config=<>
2. A validate() method is available in the raid interface. This will read the information from node.driver_info and will validate the input.
3. Zapping calls node.raid.validate() to validate again.
4. After raid configuration is done results are written to node.properties.raid_config.  

Now we can debate if we need a separate cli to get/set raid configuration.  I think it will be useful.

  ironic node-get-raid-config <node-uuid>
  ironic node-set-raid-config <node-uuid>
  ironic node-get-raid-physical-disks <node-uuid>
  ironic node-get-raid-logical-disk-properties <node-uuid>

What do you think ?'}, {'account_id': 9315, 'date': '2015-05-06 14:40:37.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 6.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-05-06 15:02:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Verified+1

commit_message:
Add generic RAID configuration spec for liberty

This commit moves the spec for generic RAID
configuration interface from kilo to liberty.
It also changes location of the current and target
RAID configuration in the DB to their own respective
fields.

Change-Id: Id7b64ccaaf327b9e1c6e6702ba79c9b86a982c19

commit_message:
Metadata Definition service should include OS::Cinder::VolumeType

Extending metadata definition service to include
OS::Cinder::VolumeType as default resource type.

Modification is necessary for upcoming Horizon widget for updating
extra specs on Cinder Volume Types.

Change-Id: I4f4dbde4e7071520627d33ba32f979f5e6c23033
Closes-Bug: 1369115

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-02-14 15:42:35.000000000', 'message': 'Cleanup scrubber must read all images

The cleanup scrubber would never list more than one
batch of images from the registry if the registry were
to truncate the number of images returned to its max limit.
Update the code to call the registry with a marker to
get the rest of the images in a loop.
Currently the cleanup scrubber has no tests, adding one.

This is not sufficient for fully working cleanup scrubber -
it does NOT fix bug #1193424 (when metadata is encrypted),
or bug #1190643 (lack of locations).

Change-Id: Ia1c4a1c9906aee0785cdfe697239d1937ae4da05
