commit_message:
Cleanup scrubber must read all images

The cleanup scrubber would never list more than one
batch of images from the registry if the registry were
to truncate the number of images returned to its max limit.
Update the code to call the registry with a marker to
get the rest of the images in a loop and make the number
of images per iteration configurable.

Currently the cleanup scrubber has no tests, adding one.

This is not sufficient for fully working cleanup scrubber -
it does NOT fix bug #1193424 (when metadata is encrypted),
or bug #1190643 (lack of locations).

Change-Id: Ia1c4a1c9906aee0785cdfe697239d1937ae4da05
Closes-bug: 1280343

commit_message:
Ensure posted size is compared with remote size and kills if different

This patch ensures the posted size is compared with downloaded image
size when using --copy-from and kills the image if size differs. It's
appropriate behavior only for api/v1. In api/v2 this flag was
eliminated (behaving consistently with uploads from posted data).

Change-Id: I013013d3cb20ec8db448d4f04666575a5a16f518
Closes-Bug: 1256593

Hello Johannes, actually we have some concerns on this approach, pls check comments in https://review.openstack.org/#/c/75898/ , and there's a link for original discussion around utf8 issue in ML."}, {'account_id': 100, 'date': '2014-07-24 14:32:52.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

This is extremely easy to verify:

mysql> create table a ( s varchar(100) not null );
Query OK, 1 row affected (0.00 sec)

mysql> show create table a;
| a     | CREATE TABLE `a` (
  `s` varchar(100) NOT NULL
) ENGINE=InnoDB DEFAULT CHARSET=utf8 |
1 row in set (0.00 sec)

mysql> insert into a values ( X'74657374AE' );
Query OK, 1 row affected (0.01 sec)

mysql> select hex(s) from a;
| 74657374AE |
1 row in set (0.01 sec)

Here you can see the string is still in latin-1 encoding

mysql> ALTER TABLE a CONVERT TO CHARACTER SET utf8;
Query OK, 1 row affected (0.06 sec)
Records: 1  Duplicates: 0  Warnings: 0

mysql> show create table a;
| a     | CREATE TABLE `a` (
  `s` varchar(100) NOT NULL
) ENGINE=InnoDB DEFAULT CHARSET=utf8 |
1 row in set (0.00 sec)

mysql> select hex(s) from a;
| 74657374C2AE |

Here you can see it was automatically converted to utf-8 encoding.

I don't understand the need for a -2?"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-08-11 15:49:15.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: -Verified

commit_message:
Automatically migrate tables to utf8 collation on MySQL

Glance (through oslo.db) makes assumptions about the default collation
used in MySQL that aren't always true. A previous bug fix introduced
option to disable the sanity checking that assumes utf8.

It's expected that deployers will manually fix the collation for each
table. This is a process that can be easily automated, obviating the
need for the option and reducing potential user error.

Closes-bug: 1279000
Change-Id: I67b6438d008d3b5ec816838fd160d249bba9375b

commit_message:
Setup MPLS bridge only if OVS agent

Agent code is common with modified openvswitch agent
for bgpvpn driver, but the OVS part should (setting
up the mpls bridge) should only be done if this code
is ran inside the OVS agent, and not for the linuxbridge
agent

Change-Id: Icdc6e3ca40d2c0b2b7fab414d6fdb27c7542ddf0

Use inmemory sqlite for testing migrations

This changes reduces total tests runtime (- ~400sec on my PC)

commit_message:
Refactoring test on test_api

Addition of function get_response_object_data() to remove the repeating
lines in many methods.The code had some spaces which got automatically
added.The spaces have been removed

This bug is an action item to track the review comment for
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/64079/4 raised by Steve Kowalik.

Change-Id: I202010c7695fcf4b8e81d6dd4eb3ae42af08d958
Closes-bug: #1264639

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. The more you
    participate in the community the more rewarding it is for you. You may also
    notice that the more you get to know people and get to be known, the faster
    your patches will be reviewed and eventually approved. Get to know others
    and become known by doing code reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a
    great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

    IRC: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/IRC
    Workflow: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Gerrit_Workflow
    Commit Messages: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/GitCommitMessages"}, {'account_id': 11356, 'date': '2014-08-27 08:07:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

That way, it appears as a link in Gerrit and infra can track the progress of the bug.

I can see your point now, but it would be nice if it's updated by zhiyan's config auto generation patch. However, it's not a blocker. I'm ok to +2 after you addressed the pep8 issue. Cheers."}, {'account_id': 6549, 'date': '2014-08-27 09:26:42.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

I did some investigations  base on my auto-config-generation change. I see this fix covered a valid case, but I think current change it's not enough - i'm not talking about full options sync-up but for rpc notification only. Mainly 3 items from me:

1. replace the name of options rabbit_notification_exchange and qpid_notification_exchange to control_exchange, and correct their value to 'glance'.

2. replace the name of qpid_notification_topic and rabbit_notification_topic to notification_topics, and keep current value.

3. this issue affects glance-registry as well, so we need to update glance-registry.conf as well.

Thoughts?

btw, glad to see your first contribution for glance, welcome!"}, {'account_id': 6549, 'date': '2014-08-27 09:29:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

ify, the auto-config-generation patch at here https://review.openstack.org/#/c/104476/'}, {'account_id': 10585, 'date': '2014-08-28 06:41:33.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

commit_message:
Fix swift container acls when glance used in multi tenant mode

When glance used with swift multi tenant store, acls on the
swift container doesn't always reflect what is defined in registry.

This patch fixes those behaviour:

* Give read access on the image container when can_share is used,
  and thus allowing image "consumer" to read the image.
* Remove write access on the container when sharing image with can_share option
* When tenant creating/updating an image is not the owner of the image
then grant the owner read access on the swift container.

Change-Id: I5ee5a758bf5fac6bb52f6f672e7a4447cd838554
Closes-bug: 1270569
Closes-bug: 1272464

Nice work here!

But I still have some remarks:

1. Once you have made the changes ??in sqlalchemy, then you have to write a test on it. (in glance/tests/unit/test_db.py)

2. I think you have to add the same changes in simple db too to maintain it in consistent state with sqlalchemy.

3. Since you've made changes in user interface you should add DocImpact to your commit message. If you look in the current documentation (http://docs.openstack.org/developer/glance/glanceapi.html#filtering-images-lists) you'll see "Filters images having a name attribute matching NAME". It has to be changed from matching to contain.'}, {'account_id': 8127, 'date': '2014-10-06 09:34:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

This breaks backwards compatibility!

If some existing service consuming our API relies on the fact that filtering by name returns the exact match of the name (and thus returns 0 or 1 images if no name duplication exists), than they may face problems when we begin returning multiple images with similar names.

So, loosening the filtering precision does not look like a good idea to me. 
I would suggest to add some explicit differentiation between the "exact match" and "contains" calls, and make sure that by default the existing behaviour (i.e. the exact match) is used.'}, {'account_id': 12566, 'date': '2014-10-06 10:38:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

(1 comment)

Thx Alexander
I checked glance API docs and there is:
"Both the GET /v1/images and GET /v1/images/detail requests take query parameters that serve to filter the returned list of images."
So I think it should't hit client expected return value'}, {'account_id': 8127, 'date': '2014-10-06 10:48:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Right, but in the parameter description section it says: "Filters images having a name attribute matching NAME". 
And "matching" here seems to mean "equal" - at least all the existing functionality for all other parameters does it this way: checks for strict value equality.

Silently changing this from "equal" to "contains" may have unwanted side effects for the existing deployments.'}, {'account_id': 12566, 'date': '2014-10-06 12:15:48.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-10-06 13:22:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Verified-1

commit_message:
Filtering image based on name contained

Method _make_conditions_from_filters has reference
to 'name' in 'filters' argument.
It can be used to filter 'models.Image' with that name
contained. The change in db.simple.api in _filter_images
for consistent state with sqlalchemy.
Unit tests for v1/v2 clients and test db, and functional
for simple api usage.

DocImpact
Closes-Bug: 1369008
Change-Id: I87e82f9dccb446478c6c38a5165820f4020e149f

Replacement mox by mock

glance/tests/unit/test_store_image.py and

This provides 2 main benefits:

* N simultaneous requests for the same image will fetch the image from
  the backend N times until one lands in the cache. This patch ensures
  the image will only be fetched once.

* N simultaneous requests for the same image will write to the cache
  simultaneously. This patch ensures the image will only be written
  once.

commit_message:
Allow fetches to the backend to be limited

Adds a new config option for glance-api.conf: limit_backend_fetches.

If this option is enabled, multiple requests for an image which is not
in the cache will only result in a single request hitting the backend
storage.

[DocImpact]

Change-Id: I98f006c4fe1b063d1514fbf32a617607c5dabea5

commit_message:
Use oslo network utils function to set tcp_keepalive

In addition to the existing cfg option for tcp_keepidle, new values
were added for tcp_keepalive(to turn on/off this feature,
tcp_keepintvl(to specify gap between successive probes) and
tcp_keepcnt(to specify number of probes). To mimic existing behavior,
tcp_keepalive defaults to True, and tcp_keepidle to 600(seconds). The
other two default to None, and the oslo code will ignore them unless
specifically set. Checking whether tcp keepalive features are absent,
like in OS X, is also done in the oslo function, so that maintains
the same functionality as right now.

DocImpact
Change-Id: Ic3932e85b258d273f0938cf7a36a4358ddcaaa5d

commit_message:
Check image_size_cap and expected_size on download

If an image during download exceeds image_size_cap or expected_size, it
probably indicates a failure on the backend or misconfiguration.
This catches those situations and fails the download.

Change-Id: Idccbca6f670739b93417112a53ff93aacf7f2dbb

commit_message:
fix swift_store_admin_tenant behavior in multi tenant mode

* make swift_store_admin_tenant option applies
  to both read and write acls.
* remove trailing ':*' that was added to swift_store_admin_tenant
* add unittest to check admin_tenant list logic

Closes-Bug: 1309597

Change-Id: I25a00c79fd7001cd02044f1eadfe9cc35e6e425e

commit_message:
Bypass vCenter to upload and download files

vCenter 5.5+ gives the ability to request a ticket from ESX to
upload and download files directly through ESX where datastores
are mounted.
This patch adds a new configuration variable 'vmware_bypass_vcenter'
which is leveraging this ticket mechanism to improve the upload and
download performance.

Closes-Bug: #1338795

Change-Id: I65227a0d3e4a7f22501bae7b0120698573d8d272

the user and defaults image.owner to the context.owner
during image upload. However, if there are existing images
with image.owner set to a tenant_id, Glance will no longer

commit_message:
Support tenants and users as image owners together

Setting 'owner_is_tenant = False' sets context.owner to
the user and defaults image.owner to the context.owner
during image upload. However, if there are existing images
with image.owner set to a tenant_id, Glance will no longer
show those images in results.

Make changes to database API to allow image.owner to
be either the tenant or the user. We grant image visibility
to images if the context.tenant matches an image member or
the image.owner field.

Change-Id: I7c9ffb97b6f7509b6c7e278acab6b6b504da5761

Hi Iccha, thanks for working on this item!

I have a concern tough: I think the visibility community (*) should be a property that can be set or not by the user sharing the image (as it is in your implementation: good), but as a tenant receiving an image, I should not have do deal with shared or community.
I think the tenant receiving the image must not know if the image is shared with all the other tenants. This is also a security concern: a tenant X should not know that tenant W, Y, Z have also access to this image.

Let me know if this is clear ;) Would be interested to get your point of view"}, {'account_id': 4463, 'date': '2014-02-18 19:06:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Hi Iccha,

Many thanks for this patch -- this functionality will be *really* useful to have.

One comment on the name 'community': for me that that has connotations of free/open source.

I wonder how people would feel about marking a super-proprietary, closed source, expensively licensed image as 'community'?

What do you think? Would it be worth considering another term?

Perhaps something like 'broadcast' might make sense? When something is broadcast its available to anyone who wants to 'tune in' (and may or may not be free).

Let me know what you think.

And thanks again!

-Stuart"}, {'account_id': 8759, 'date': '2014-02-20 03:05:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

I kinda agree with Stuart and I think this is related to my initial concern/confusion.
I associate community to a group (subset) of people and not the totality. Here a community image is available to anyone who accepts it.

+1 for the broadcast terminology'}, {'account_id': 4463, 'date': '2014-02-20 16:55:54.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Brian had some reservations on broadcast being more of a verb vs a noun.

published?'}, {'account_id': 455, 'date': '2014-02-20 19:03:50.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Hey Iccha,

Scrambling for my high school grammar book ... :-)

I think broadcast or community would both be ok -- they're adjectives like the existing 'private'.

I guess its a matter of taste.

Perhaps ping folks at the irc meeting later?

(I'm obviously not gonna block this on the name!)

@Arnaud: I think publish would be a good choice, except it might be a bit similar to public."}, {'account_id': 5314, 'date': '2014-02-20 21:10:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

commit_message:
Community Image Sharing

Add a new feature that allows a tenant to share images
with all other tenants, but respects the "anti-spam" aspect
of current v2 image sharing (i.e., by default a shared
image does NOT appear in a tenant's image-list until the image
consumer "accepts" the image)
Related wiki:
https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Glance-v2-community-image-sharing

Related to bp community-level-v2-image-sharing

Change-Id: Ia3de96806dd23d98d64b51c88c8fe9993d4187bd

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-02-14 08:21:58.000000000', 'message': "Make notifier raise Glance (not HTTP) exceptions

Glance notifier code is catching and reencoding exceptions
inappropriately. In particular, it is changing core exceptions to webob
HTTP exceptions, which means any client of the notifier layer in the
domain cannot handle the exceptions appropriately.

This commit retains the notification logic but removes the exception
translation logic - original exceptions are propagated without
translation to webob HTTP exceptions.

In addition, this commit also removes the catching of the generic
webob.HTTPError in image_data.py and notifier.py because storage
backends won't/shouldn't be raising HTTP errors.

Change-Id: Id18e4421f5d8d776e28db02a1e912351b16febf2
Closes-bug: #1223516
"}, {'created': '2014-02-20 07:37:01.000000000', 'message': "Make notifier raise Glance (not HTTP) exceptions

Glance notifier code is catching and reencoding exceptions
inappropriately. In particular, it is changing core exceptions to webob
HTTP exceptions, which means any client of the notifier layer in the
domain cannot handle the exceptions appropriately.

This commit retains the notification logic but removes the exception
translation logic - original exceptions are propagated without
translation to webob HTTP exceptions.

In addition, this commit also removes the catching of the generic

commit_message:
Make notifier raise Glance (not HTTP) exceptions

Glance notifier code is catching and reencoding exceptions
inappropriately. In particular, it is changing core exceptions to webob
HTTP exceptions, which means any client of the notifier layer in the
domain cannot handle the exceptions appropriately.

This commit retains the notification logic but removes the exception
translation logic - original exceptions are propagated without
translation to webob HTTP exceptions.

In addition, this commit also removes the catching of the generic
webob.HTTPError in image_data.py and notifier.py because storage
backends won't/shouldn't be raising HTTP errors.

Change-Id: Id18e4421f5d8d776e28db02a1e912351b16febf2
Closes-bug: #1223516

commit_message:
Image create in V1 should validate the uri

This patch ensures that a store is not set while
creating an image or updating it.
This plugs a security hole that is introduced by
remove-sensitive-data-from-locations

Implements bp: v1-image-create-should-validate-the-location-uri
Change-Id: I1a1d3ac2361720cbf6c51d2bfc47643835964a09

commit_message:
Eventlet green threads not released back to pool

Presently, the wsgi server allows persist connections. Hence even after
the response is sent to the client, it doesn't close the client socket
connection. Because of this problem, the green thread is not released
back to the pool.

In order to close the client socket connection explicitly after the
response is sent and read successfully by the client, you simply have to
set keepalive to False when you create a wsgi server.

DocImpact:
Added http_keepalive option (default=True).

Conflicts:
        doc/source/configuring.rst
        etc/glance-api.conf
        glance/common/wsgi.py
        glance/tests/unit/test_opts.py

SecurityImpact

Closes-Bug: #1361360
Change-Id: I93aaca24935a4f3096210233097dd6b8c5440176
(cherry picked from commit 16a821e00d15520d2f6e940e184bd289b8782620)

commit_message:
Make properties roles check case-insensitive

Glance is case-insensitive when checking roles.
This patch makes protected properties rules
roles check also case-insensitive.

Change-Id: Ib505889e12d0867f43788b815d9cbea18b8f2513
Closes-Bug: #1430804

commit_message:
Fix enabling of rally project in ci jobs

Commit [1] broke Rally jobs for Manila.
Rally was not enabled via exported env var, so bash did not consider related
env var from pre_test_hook.

[1] - I4dc55274d9b1e720fc122e07c487699e589c6f5a

Change-Id: Ibaa6798867b65a26f8941e17fbc1284284349d2d

commit_message:
Use exceptions from keystoneauth

As a first step use the exceptions from keystoneauth instead of defining
them in keystoneclient.

This is also one of the big wins of the keystoneauth project.

Change-Id: Ia5109fc12dfd3a3e2aa6ff8479872d26d0d02454

Roman,

I understand your frustration about this rule that is not being checked, but as with quite a few other hacking rules the checks has not been enabled as they would fail. This does not mean that we shouldn't follow those rules, it also doesn't mean we need to revamp our whole codebase to do so.

What comes to metadef code, I'm sad to hear that this rule has not been followed when new code was written. Perhaps the module would need to be renamed if using it decreases readability. These changes has quite often wider implications than one could think by first look.

Also I could question the reasoning to refactor code we're trying to deprecate and finally in measurable/defined future clean out. Basic rule with these are, implement by rules if it's consistent with the code around (or new module); fix where convenient and improves readability; break where it makes things worse. In nutshell use common sense and don't take the reviewers comments personally.

And to make life easier in the future. If you feel that you should/want to do some bigger refactoring around the code, add it first to the weekly meeting agenda, throw e-mail out to the mailing list or something around those lines to get how people feels about the change. Sometimes it's worth of the effort (yours and reviewers) sometimes it might not be on the priority list and the time would be better spent somewhere else. And please when doing so, give couple of examples. Time to time it might sound as a good idea that someone want's to work the code towards better hacking compliance or something like that but the end result might not work out so well. Little of time preparing might save lots of wasted hours and frustration. It does not always save the day but sometimes it at least comforts to know that you were not the only person who initially thought it was a good idea."}, {'account_id': 12395, 'date': '2014-11-21 10:52:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

commit_message:
Do not import objects, only modules

Due to http://docs.openstack.org/developer/hacking/ [H302] We do not
import objects, only modules . Exceptions are:
    imports from migrate package
    imports from sqlalchemy package
    imports from oslo-incubator.openstack.common.gettextutils module

Change-Id: I94e34684dcea9ffffa876b169d00b7ddb73158b2
Closes-bug: 1393780

Add GPFS support as image store

Implement GPFS as image store
Allow mount multi GPFS filesystems
Support location metadata

commit_message:
Remove duplicate creation of use_user_token

This code removes duplicate creation of the option in
store_utils and leaves only one in registry client.

Change-Id: Ic067094b0eb2c8803b5d0140dfae27baf72ac0e1
Closes-Bug: #1463466

Reduce OSWL collector user privileges

Previously OSWL user has admin privileges, what is obviously too much
for data gathering.

commit_message:
Let HAProxy determine usefulness of TCP splicing

The "splice-auto" options causes HAProxy to evaluate splice() system
call performance using light heuristic, independently for requests and
responses. The possible gain of splicing depends on too many factors and
might be dependent on used hardware so there is no point in hardcoding
it.

Change-Id: I06e106eaacf9c67a9ef1582a37b5c46209fb0c2b
Closes-Bug: 1420710

commit_message:
Correct bad documentation merge

Was looking for something else and noticed that the documentation for
the swift_store_cacert option was merged into the middle of the doc
for the swift_store_ssl_compression option.  This patch corrects that.

DocImpact

Change-Id: I86c7a9d045cb7784cb68020a13b7682b3ea8c94d

commit_message:
Catch exceptions in service status report

If db throw any exceptions during service status report, service
will not report its status forever. This patch catch errors during
status report and log them in to log files.

Change-Id: I6775b3446caffabd3135d5e24098ab0ee31975ac
Closes-Bug: #1464188
(cherry picked from commit 4e21b371d85289548c04f50f5614ede70ff1a21f)

commit_message:
Remove tests for `base` module

Since whole module `glanceclient.base` is replaced[1] by `apiclient.base`
from common code and marked as deprecated, custom tests for this module 
are not needed and should be removed.

[1] - I41da4a9188e97ca2c07b6234fc2ac0a877553d3f
Related to bp common-client-library-2

Change-Id: I93203c78fdeb8cf7e5b8d868a32374d9be350655

commit_message:
IBP: /boot on small hard drive if possible

On some hardware GRUB can not see huge hard drives (>2T)
due to firmware bugs, so we'd better avoid placing
/boot on such drives if it is possible.

Change-Id: I71e0255820edef4725208db777bf5e0bf8d3958c
Partial-Bug: #1461126

commit_message:
Be more explicit with our review policies.

It seems there is a need to be more explicit with some of our
review policies, so this change is an attempt to make our
existing policies clearer.

Change-Id: Ib1475f9075dc5d3c106293ddd35be5d3c96b6de4

'}]
commit_message:
Remove unnecessary validation in PXE

It is unncessary to always validate boot option for uefi in
PXEDeploy, especially we already know boot_mode is bios.

Change-Id: Iae908f39125ceca64b03b8929b658e402beaef58

commit_message:
Add no-cache directive when generating keypair

There is no cache-control directive in when generating a keypair, which
could cause some browsers to cache the private key.

Uses the @cache_control and @never_cache django caching decorators.

Change-Id: If767ab12e1c78363eabbf41243a714e979fb8374
Closes-Bug: #1463533

commit_message:
Update ironic config tables

Updated ironic.headers and ironic.flagmappings. I did this because
we renamed 'discoverd' to 'inspector' but these changes also reflect
additional changes in the configs from the master branch of ironic.

I edited ironic.headers and modified ironic.flagmappings (after it
was updated via './autohelp-wrapper update ironic'). The .xml files
were updated from running './autohelp-wrapper docbook ironic').
ch_baremetalconfigure.xml was edited to reflect the changed tables.

Change-Id: I4329fe706e8fdc3c492b50e511295cf2313cca94

commit_message:
Removing unused file references in Jasmine

hz.api.service.js renamed to hz.api.common.js
utils.spec.js renamed to helper-functions.spec.js

The tests have references to the new files and run fine, but we need to
remove the old file references. Consequently, this fixes the issue
in the toast directive as well.

Change-Id: Iac209f28f07281ae384f10533ce6e4ff7182b1be
Closes-bug: #1464411

[{'created': '2015-06-11 11:27:09.000000000', 'message': "Fix configuration for tox 2.0.x

Using latest tox 2.0.x our tox jobs fail with following error:

tox.ConfigError: ConfigError: substitution key 'envbindir' not found

So, replace substitution key 'envbindir' with 'envdir' with suffix '/bin'.

Change-Id: I51a4aa7d66cf24ec89cd2c87c9ce902b919ba4b1
Closes-Bug: #1455066
(cherry picked from commit 095c81eb1e17f8d5b8c1c903d67792fdc4abbe9f)
"}]
commit_message:
Fix configuration for tox 2.0.x

Using latest tox 2.0.x our tox jobs fail with following error:

tox.ConfigError: ConfigError: substitution key 'envbindir' not found

So, replace substitution key 'envbindir' with 'envdir' with suffix '/bin'.

Change-Id: I51a4aa7d66cf24ec89cd2c87c9ce902b919ba4b1
Closes-Bug: #1455066
(cherry picked from commit 095c81eb1e17f8d5b8c1c903d67792fdc4abbe9f)

commit_message:
guru meditation report for nova-compute in worlddump

Nova-compute is hanging in the multinode test, and its difficult to
figure out why. So trigger a guru meditation report for nova-compute in
worlddump so we can see what nova-compute is doing when it is hung.

Having a hung nova-compute causes tempest to fail and
I035fe8e3333034e44b403ed0f986220ab5b0e57a runs worlddump whenever
tempest fails.

Bug 1462305 is one of the last issues left before the multinode job is
stable enough to gate on, and this patch should make it much easier to
debug.

Change-Id: I87d7536b5992c47b8082684cc662f953113fd1a8
Related-Bug: #1462305

commit_message:
Add watch file driver support

Also uses the nested temp dir support to ensure
that the temporary directory used for tests isn't
always the same (and therefore causing the file
driver tests to have problems).

Change-Id: I1b1acace086148e7930319e23cb5777c78adce6a

commit_message:
Remove usage of global CONF

Change the API of oslo.service to accept conf object and
remove usage of global CONF object throughout the library.

List of functions/classes that accept conf as a parameter:
  1. eventlet_backdoor.py
    * initialize_if_enabled
  2. periodic_task.py
    * PeriodicTasks
  3. service.py
    * launch
    * ServiceLauncher
    * ProcessLauncher
  4. sslutils.py
    * is_enabled
    * wrap

Fixed the unit tests.

APIImpact
bp graduate-oslo-service

Change-Id: Icbd5f9e386b0eee2f7c60a65c076f53ba5f0f637

commit_message:
Make the file driver more capable (with regard to groups)

Adds the following to the file driver:

- join_group
- leave_group
- create_group
- get_members
- get_member_capabilities
- delete_group
- get_groups

Currently no watching (or leadership usage) is implemented
but it should be relatively simple to add at a later date.

Change-Id: I4fa73f43c5c9dde2b0e28693d1fecea8f6a0d3de

We don't use anything from oslo-incubator, so we don't
need this config file.

commit_message:
Dispose DB connections between backend proc starts

Currently we do not dispose the existing DB pools before
forking off additional storage backend processes.  This can
result in timing issues and DB errors.

This change simply ensures that we do a dispose_engine() in
the loop where we are forking off processes for the storage
backends.

Change-Id: I4ce67e1ce7853fafe5318393482d841583e42098
Closes-bug: 1463580

commit_message:
Try to use a default pool when creating a queue

We recently enabled default pools creation, which will use the default
`message_storage` if present. This patch extends that to queue's
creation where we try to register a queue in the catalogue but we fail
if no pools were found.

With this patch, the failure will happen after checking if there's a
default pool that can be used.

In addition to the above, this commit adds a new option
`enable_virtual_pool` that makes default pools registration optional.
This is to avoid breaking backwards compatibility on the deployments
already running Zaqar.

DocImpact

Closes-bug: #1462008
Closes-bug: #1463110
Change-Id: Ieb8d2671066fc909f422bd74fd20070bc0f9cf11

commit_message:
Change container-execute to container-exec

This is more consistent with "docker exec" command and causes the user to do less typing.

Closes-Bug: #1459877

I like the direction of this, but how do we gracefully help existing deployments that have built based on this migrate to this new structure? We need to at least consider this and if nothing else provide some migration information in some documentation (maybe a follow on patch to keep this cleaner) so that we don't just leave deployers, etc stranded. I just would like to understand what the thought process is on this topic.

For example, see here where some of the files affected are documented:
http://docs.openstack.org/developer/horizon/topics/customizing.html#

Also, it seems we need to deal with updating the documentation to be structured so that we can keep historical information for reference with while making a new guide for this new path.  Because the current doc structure and URL doesn't really differentiate between where people on <=Kilo should look and what is being done now."}, {'account_id': 7665, 'date': '2015-06-09 05:14:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10: Code-Review+1

BTW, not quite sure how to rate this one since the code basically looks fine to me, but I really would like to understand the plan for at least documentation before this goes through (whether adding to this patch or not). Also, getting somebody like David to comment would be good.'}, {'account_id': 14124, 'date': '2015-06-09 13:55:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10: Code-Review+1

I like this change as well, but it is good to keep in mind what Travis brought up regarding migration notes.

Checked out the code and tested the UI and ran the tests.'}, {'account_id': 9576, 'date': '2015-06-09 20:30:36.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 10: Code-Review+2

@Travis

Not sure I understand your migration comment. As far as I can understand, all we're doing here is moving templates from horizon into dashboard. If deployers overrode some template, and the template name isn't different the template loader will take care of it, they will not have to migrate anything.

I do agree that we need to update the docs though, some of the template URL is going to be different.

@Richard

I ran integration tests locally, seems like its getting the same results as master, so I'm assuming that it is safe. However, I did notice that we are referencing the _script_loader.html which exists in /client_side folder. I believe this should also be in dashboard. Lets address this in a different patch though.

I'm gonna give it my blessing and +2 it, I think its will bring us one step closer to a single-page-app."}, {'account_id': 7665, 'date': '2015-06-10 04:45:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10:

@Thai

A couple reasons why I didn't directly +2, but did a +1.

First one is probably mostly a documentation thing.  The documentations says things like:

"It is possible to define custom stylesheets for your dashboards. Horizons base template horizon/templates/base.html defines multiple blocks that can be overridden."

Which is no longer true.

and

"All Horizons javascript files are listed in the horizon/_scripts.html partial template, which is included in Horizons base template in block js.

To add custom javascript files, create an _scripts.html partial template in your dashboard openstack_dashboard/dashboards/my_custom_dashboard/ templates/my_custom_dashboard/_scripts.html which extends horizon/_scripts.html. In this template override the block custom_js_files including your custom javascript files:

{% extends 'horizon/_scripts.html' %}"

Throughout the documentation they either start with "horizon/" or "openstack_dashboard/" to mean one of the two base directories. So, now the references in the documentation don't align since the files moved to places like openstack_dashboard/templates/horizon/_scripts.html.

And in looking at it it does kind of beg the question of why does openstack_dashboard now have a templates/horizon directory since horizon is this other thing we've been trying to clean up and get the dashboard stuff separated. I guess it is due to the template loader providing some backwards compatibility like you said. But again, it is a change that is just happening without an update to docs or to let anybody know what to look for.  And if the docs change, where do Kilo people go to find things out.  As I said, this could be fixed here or in a follow on. I just don't want to lose track of it.

Now finally, once upon a time, I was on a product that actually built a separate installer for OpenStack using Horizon, not the OpenStack Dashboard.  I don't know what the status is on it or have the code anymore to check, but if they were following the guide and just put in their scripts in the override block ({% block custom_js_files %}), they'd be rather confused about why all of a sudden the file they were extending disappeared from seemed to be gone.  So, at least documenting what was changed and why so they'd see it could help them out.  Again, just a request for a bug or follow-on patch.

The other reason for the +1 rather than +2 was to hopefully give people like David a chance to review before it goes through to see if there is any opinion.  I just added him to the reviewer list (he wasn't on their before).

At any rate, a +1 shouldn't be considered a blocker, just a way to allow for more discussion and get a few more opinions on this before it goes through.'}, {'account_id': 9576, 'date': '2015-06-10 06:20:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10:

Let's look at an example for clarification. Assume that base.html has {% include "horizon/_custom__head_js.html" %}

Now as a deployer, I wouldn't be replacing this file in the horizon folder. Rather I will be creating a NEW file in openstack_dashboard/templates/horizon/_custom_head_js.html. The template loader then knows to replace the horizon/_custom_head_js.html with your new file.

That is my understanding of how this works. Maybe we are talking pass each other, but I don't think this patch poses a problem and should not break existing/extended templates.'}, {'account_id': 7665, 'date': '2015-06-10 23:04:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10:

Hey Thai,

I think some of the nuance of what I'm saying is being missed.

Basically, I think this makes the documentation a least slightly incorrect and it should be updated.  So either add that to this patch or add a follow-on patch.  For example, some file locations should be checked in this file:

https://github.com/openstack/horizon/blob/master/doc/source/topics/customizing.rst

And secondarily, if anybody was taking "horizon" and not "openstack_dashboard" for a UI, they would no longer get some of these files and could be confused where to find them, so was thinking this should be captured somewhere.  Release notes?

Anyway, chatted with David about this a bit in IRC to get his eyes on it and he's looking now.  Will be good to get his check off.

Travis'}, {'account_id': 9576, 'date': '2015-06-10 23:59:07.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 10: Code-Review-1

@Travis

I finally understand what you're saying. So basically if someone extended from horizon's base.html itself, like my_dashboard, then my_dashboard will no longer work after this change; I would have to extend from dashboard's base.html instead. Having said that, horizon and dashboard both live in the same repo, so they just need to configure their template loader to point to dashboard as well.

I agree with Travis that in order to push this change through, we really need to document this first, and possible even modify the setup to reflect this change. I'll retract the +2 until we have a follow-on patch."}, {'account_id': 12071, 'date': '2015-06-11 01:20:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11: Patch Set 10 was rebased'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-06-11 02:06:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11: Verified+1

This patch moves the base.html file and related files (where appropriate)
to the dashboard. In short:

- base.html its *dashboard configuration* components _header.html,
  _stylesheets.html, horizon/_conf.html, horizon/_custom_head_js.html,
  horizon/_custom_meta.html and horizon/_scripts.html all move to the
  dashboard
- other components in base.html which are effectively widgets or
  default content (horizon/_messages.html, horizon/common/_sidebar.html,
  horizon/common/_page_header.html,
  horizon/client_side/_script_loader.html) stay in the framework

The framework test suite also includes a need for a base.html which can
construct *part* of the application's base.html structure, and this is
created in horizon/test/templates/base.html (this file is only used to
test Django templating, so does not need most of the content in the real
base.html).

Change-Id: I9b3c4f21036d08e1d79aeab1ab35d47e3eedd3a3

commit_message:
ngReorg - move core HTML from framework to dashboard

This patch moves the base.html file and related files (where appropriate)
to the dashboard. In short:

- base.html its *dashboard configuration* components _header.html,
  _stylesheets.html, horizon/_conf.html, horizon/_custom_head_js.html,
  horizon/_custom_meta.html and horizon/_scripts.html all move to the
  dashboard
- other components in base.html which are effectively widgets or
  default content (horizon/_messages.html, horizon/common/_sidebar.html,
  horizon/common/_page_header.html,
  horizon/client_side/_script_loader.html) stay in the framework

The framework test suite also includes a need for a base.html which can
construct *part* of the application's base.html structure, and this is
created in horizon/test/templates/base.html (this file is only used to
test Django templating, so does not need most of the content in the real
base.html).

Change-Id: I9b3c4f21036d08e1d79aeab1ab35d47e3eedd3a3
Partial-Bug: #1458697

commit_message:
Raise user-friendly exceptions in str2dict

Currently str2dict raises non user-friendly exceptions when input is not
valid:

  neutron subnet-create mynetwork 10/23 --allocation-pools=10/24
  # implies str2dict('10/24')
  # raises:
     dictionary update sequence element #0 has length 1; 2 is required

This change updates str2dict implementation in order to raise
user-friendly exceptions.

Closes-Bug: #1460336
Change-Id: Id381865e6e5d9bebcb2c984c0338126566a97c2b

tests in tempest, we add an option to run tests only on Kilo+
branch.

When reverting create operations on an error,

commit_message:
Improve error handling for create operations

When reverting create operations on an error,
- Preserve the original exception, which we want to report to user
- In the case of port, specify l3_port_check=False as it isn't
  an operation from a user
- Move LOG calls, which i believe can block, inside
  save_and_reraise_exception blocks

Change-Id: I9171277b1dce87a305a7d56d99076df063b9e839

Change max_size's default value to -1 when creating a cluster

When creating a cluster without configuring max_size option,
the default value shoule be -1, which means unlimited.

commit_message:
Ensure periodic freshening of the job board contents

If the child watch for some reason is not triggering
a fallback is to just periodically just download/refresh
the job board contents. This is also generally a good
thing to do (even if the watch is triggering); to ensure
freshness so periodically do this at the start and
periodically at least every 60 seconds.

commit_message:
Bugfixes for java parity

Fixed unicode issue in alarm definition list

Use limit (instead of offset) in alarm list and change
the links to include the 'rel' part

Fix measurement list json load errors when value-meta is empty

Change alarm history list to match formatting from java api

Change-Id: I7d9a421ddb69d7b40b2474775f7619f17b2ce33b

commit_message:
Fix delete device bug

Device can not delete if delete instance by nova's command directly.
So it's can not delete the device by neutron tacker's command, like
'neutron device-delete [id]'. I think that it is necessary to catch
Instance Not Found exception and log it, finally, just return.

Change-Id: I62f74056fd2b098be37eeee2804a66d2ba0accc4

commit_message:
Catch exceptions in service status report

If db throw any exceptions during service status report, service
will not report its status forever. This patch catch errors during
status report and log them in to log files.

Change-Id: I6775b3446caffabd3135d5e24098ab0ee31975ac
Closes-Bug: #1464188

commit_message:
Add support for DEVSTACK_GATE_SETTINGS

This patch adds support for DEVSTACK_GATE_SETTINGS.  A job definition
can set this variable with a path to a file to source after the
environment has been set up.  This is useful for projects to be able
to set custom environment variables from a file in their project
instead of maintaining them in project-config.

Note that this is not possible in the pre_test_hook as that runs in a
sub-shell, so it's not possible to set environment variables that
remain.

Change-Id: I80742d498f4f21006eed16a82d568b496957797f
Signed-off-by: Russell Bryant <rbryant@redhat.com>

commit_message:
Add additional logging around cleaning

When debugging anything around cleaning, there are places where
different code paths can lead to the same log statements, making
it hard to know for sure what path the node took, specifically
around _notify_conductor_resume_clean().

Change-Id: I6b805ad6d757d8136525cf501eb890147430e1af

commit_message:
Dont fail if were missing setfiles

We are using which to find the location of setfiles. Our script is set
-e though, and we need to also be able to handle the case where setfiles
does not exist (like on centos-minimal).

Change-Id: If53c7a80efc081b95b143c28be64d39b12bfb469

commit_message:
Remove cell policy check

we already got policy checks for create,update,delete
and sync_instances of cell, there is no need to check the
general policy of cell and it might lead to inconsistency
problem.

The v2 code is not touched because v2.1 is current using.

UpgradeImpact

Partially implements bp nova-api-policy-final-part

Change-Id: I05ea8b0f3b093b7dbfbe037c21e224acc3c605ad

commit_message:
Creating initial Liberty install guide doc specs

- Installation Guide RST conversion

The general Liberty install guide spec will be addressed in a separate patch.

Change-Id: I723053b949a24032c7a0ecf2265fd119208c8815

commit_message:
Convergence soft delete stack after delete action is completed

In an convergence enabled environment, when an stack-delete
action is completed, the stack was not soft deleted from DB.

This patch soft deletes the stack after all the required
stack-delete operations are completed.

Change-Id: I36d2b76223d3fc5f313b953b3976282d0923e92e

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-06-01 20:38:53.000000000', 'message': 'Ensure no "agent" functional tests are skipped in the gate

Some "agent" functional tests[1] can be skipped if some requirements are
not satisfied in order to allow developers to run functional tests on
various environments. These tests should not be skipped on the gate.

This change defines the decorator disallow_skip_on_gate[2] which allows
to ensure no skipTest is raised by a method when running on the gate in
order to ensure no "agent" functional tests is skipped. This change also
replaces OS_FAIL_ON_MISSING_DEPS by OS_FAIL_ON_GATE to address a larger
scope (ie: missing dependencies + system requirements).

[1] in neutron.tests.functional
[2] in neutron.tests.common.base

Change-Id: Iacd4a5ef249fc1d7c75135ead9d0cf99d8a98a06
Closes-Bug: #1459844

commit_message:
Ensure no "agent" functional tests are skipped in the gate

Some "agent" functional tests[1] can be skipped if some requirements are
not satisfied in order to allow developers to run functional tests on
various environments. These tests should not be skipped in the gate.

This change defines the decorator no_skip_on_missing_deps[2] to ensure
no "agent" functional tests are skipped in the gate. More precisely
no_skip_on_missing_deps transforms a skipTest into an error in:

* dsvm-functional and dsvm-fullstack jobs,
* functional and fullstack jobs when OS_FAIL_ON_MISSING_DEPS is
  evaluated as True.

The change enlarges OS_FAIL_ON_MISSING_DEPS environment variable scope
(ie: missing dependencies + system requirements).

[1] in neutron.tests.functional
[2] in neutron.tests.common.base

Change-Id: Iacd4a5ef249fc1d7c75135ead9d0cf99d8a98a06
Closes-Bug: #1459844

[{'created': '2015-06-09 18:36:15.000000000', 'message': "L3 agent should do report state before full sync at start

Sometimes the AgentNotFoundByTypeHost exception is reported during
L3-agent startup. The exception is generated when the first
get_routers RPC call is made. When the neutron server gets this
RPC call, it might not have handled the report state RPC call yet.
So the L3-agent hasn't been registered in the API server.
The result is a RPC Error exception.  By the time the next
get_routers RPC call is made, the report state RPC call has already
been done and agent registered.

This patch modifies the L3 agent startup behavior to have the report
state done before the agent do the sync routers RPC call.

Closes-bug: 1456822
Change-Id: Id40cfd8466f45e20fea0e9df6fd57bf9c9e59da7
(cherry picked from commit b649b9c871d0734745da5a201eca83a6b407a1c5)
"}]
commit_message:
L3 agent should do report state before full sync at start

Sometimes the AgentNotFoundByTypeHost exception is reported during
L3-agent startup. The exception is generated when the first
get_routers RPC call is made. When the neutron server gets this
RPC call, it might not have handled the report state RPC call yet.
So the L3-agent hasn't been registered in the API server.
The result is a RPC Error exception.  By the time the next
get_routers RPC call is made, the report state RPC call has already
been done and agent registered.

This patch modifies the L3 agent startup behavior to have the report
state done before the agent do the sync routers RPC call.

Closes-bug: 1456822
Change-Id: Id40cfd8466f45e20fea0e9df6fd57bf9c9e59da7
(cherry picked from commit b649b9c871d0734745da5a201eca83a6b407a1c5)

commit_message:
Fix RouterInterface properties validation

get_attr on a non-created resource returns an empty string
(rather than None). We should pass validation in this case.

Change-Id: I5a1d651cc7dc46162140210ebeacaa7519111c91
Closes-bug: 1451819

commit_message:
Check that env is not None before decrypting

After database migration 056, it became possible to have an environment
of None.  Check that env is not None before looking inside it.

Change-Id: Ic498e8e630608886178df83d1e7a503525834573
Closes-Bug: #1464379

commit_message:
Sort the attribute in __all__ as the import sequence in the api/__init__.py

In the api/__init__.py the import sequence is by alphabet,
the attribute in __all__ can also sort as the import sequence.

Change-Id: I4aa74553e8c16c6f791c0c21aab05089d4ae5471
Closes-bug:#1441062

commit_message:
Cleanup TODO in glance/gateway.py for elasticsearch being unavailable

In commit f53584c2688244f4f5b706aadac1875109a463c5 we added a TODO to be
more obvious about the error when elasticsearch isn't available if you
try to start the search service (since elasticsearch is an optional
dependency).  We couldn't add new errors at the time because of
StringFreeze.

This resolves the TODO by adding the new SearchNotAvailable exception in
place of the generic ServiceUnavailable exception.

Closes-Bug: #1441764

Change-Id: Ia300d9647f372a677dc536e750dd2ff064601c29

commit_message:
Fix some spelling miss and message output

Using misspellings package to find the spelling miss
and fix them. Also fix one message output problem.
We can find the spelling miss by doing:
* pip install misspellings
* git ls-files | grep -v locale | misspellings -f -

Change-Id: I671f2c2bc0a69925caaf6e38c383465cfe2238d9

commit_message:
Split `storage` into (message|management)_storage

We split both, data and control, planes and we were diligent in
splitting the configuration sections. However, we forgot to split the
`storage` option in the `drivers` section.

This patch does that and marks the old option as deprecated.

Closes-bug: #1462025
Change-Id: I692c35dcf217bede557ac463b2388f9a60d96c79

commit_message:
go: make full disk log message debug-level

When a drive fills up, having that error-level log can make a lot of noise.

Change-Id: I9475138b5d8819f69d340706b94702442ede8408

commit_message:
horizon ignores region for identity service

this change will attempt to use a identity service in the selected region
when available.  before the region for the identity service was always the first
found

Change-Id: Idc64a32128bcee561cdbba956722adad0ee1eaf2
Closes-Bug: #1339382
(cherry picked from commit 88371c666083e2d02527f45e3e4415b657ab893f)

Yes, I absolutely agree with Alexey, that this regexp must be here.

The reason of it - we want to compare two different things. We check that input string <=32 symbols, but in db varchar is set to 32 bytes. So, it doesn't matter what string length we have. If we use non-ascii characters there, check in api will pass, but then it will error in db (because we're going to write more than 32 bytes) and 500 response from server.anyway."}, {'account_id': 16683, 'date': '2015-06-10 14:12:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11: Code-Review-1'}, {'account_id': 13717, 'date': '2015-06-10 14:46:04.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 11:

commit_message:
Fix DbError when image params are out of range

Image params such as checksum, min_ram and min_disk are validated.
Checksum is expected to be not longer than 32 characters,
min_ram/min_disk can't exceed pow(2, 31) - 1.
A method for mysql_int validation has been moved to glance.common.utils.

Change-Id: I78554ef1ba65fc11da3de56467d6d70bb7991787
Closes-Bug: #1454730
Closes-Bug: #1460060

[{'created': '2015-02-04 12:50:21.000000000', 'message': "Fixes ceilometer-compute service start failure

Currently ceilometer-compute service is failing to start in the
'vmware' region, because of the additional parameter 'port', is
added to the oslo.vmware _get_wsdl_loc method.

This patch fixes it by not calling the private method _get_wsdl_loc,
avoiding the mismatch in the method call. Additional optional
'wsdl_location' is added to over-ride to default location for bug
work-arounds.

Test cases are not added, since the changed method just calls the
oslo.vmware and method is already mocked in the setUp of the
class TestVsphereInspection.

Change-Id: Ib70092c1ccb14421701acdf8ff4a3805becbeef4
Closes-Bug: #1326230

commit_message:
Fixes ceilometer-compute service start failure

Currently ceilometer-compute service is failing to start in the
'vmware' region, because of the additional parameter 'port', is
added to the oslo.vmware _get_wsdl_loc method.

This patch fixes it by not calling the private method _get_wsdl_loc,
avoiding the mismatch in the method call.

Test cases are not added, since the changed method just calls the
oslo.vmware and method is already mocked in the setUp of the
class TestVsphereInspection.

Change-Id: Ib70092c1ccb14421701acdf8ff4a3805becbeef4
Closes-Bug: #1326230
(cherry picked from commit ff5c133cb0f548851a8d276a31c7f38bcc9c5522)

Give the JVM more juice

To see if it makes a difference to get more reliable runs.

Change-Id: I8915edfbe7a669706ad265c61df692846dc101da

commit_message:
support for Keystone v3 authentication

This adds the class Puppet::Provider::Openstack::CredentialsV3
that implements support for Keystone v3 authentication and all
of the new id and domain authentication parameters.

Implements: blueprint api-v3-support

Change-Id: Icafc4cb8ed000fd9d3ed6ffde2afe1a1250d90af

subject: Add guestfs packages for libvirt support
messages:
[{'account_id': 7128, 'date': '2015-06-04 21:32:04.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-06-04 22:27:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1

Build succeeded (check pipeline).

- gate-cookbook-openstack-compute-chef-rake http://logs.openstack.org/98/188598/1/check/gate-cookbook-openstack-compute-chef-rake/2fae330/ : SUCCESS in 6m 53s'}, {'account_id': 11915, 'date': '2015-06-05 12:50:20.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

not sure if that should be the default, since there are cases where no guestfs is used (like rbd for ephemerals). maybe this should be an option? or the other way around?'}, {'account_id': 7128, 'date': '2015-06-05 15:56:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Jan, I guess I would like to try to stay some what in sync with how DevStack handle libvirt dependent packages, since that is still the main platform for testing base OpenStack.'}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2015-06-08 14:18:03.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

@Jan, the default reference implementation in nova is not using RBD, it's mounting images using some modules within nova, and the preferred option is libguestfs:

http://git.openstack.org/cgit/openstack/nova/tree/nova/virt/disk/vfs/api.py?id=2015.1.0#n48

Failing to import that, it falls back to using nbd for qcow* images and there is a known kernel bug with nbd + network namespaces, which neutron uses by default, which can cause the kernel to crash, see bug 1273386."}, {'account_id': 11915, 'date': '2015-06-10 15:11:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2

if its the sane default its fine i guess, but we should probably add a trigger to not install it if rbd is used (can be done in a different patch)'}, {'account_id': 7769, 'date': '2015-06-10 15:17:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

I concur with the RBD concerns, but this does appear to be a sane default and in line with preferred behavior.  As pointed out, we can address RBD separately if need be.'}, {'account_id': 9488, 'date': '2015-06-12 01:49:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2 Workflow+1

Thanks.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-06-12 01:49:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: -Verified

commit_message:
Add guestfs packages for libvirt support

libvirt can use the guestfs support and it is preferred by nova.

Change-Id: I76fc9f6b311b3023a1ef3ea079e3c4c8cff6582b
Closes-Bug: #1462102

commit_message:
Send Instance object to cells instance_update_at_top

Currently, a primitivized object is sent to sync to the API cell
in Instance.save because instance_update_at_top has not yet been
converted to handle objects. This change does the conversion and
makes Instance.save send an object for the sync.

This change should also address a race where deleting an instance
can result in an "undeleted" instance if an update from a child
occurs after the instance has been destroyed at the top, because
in instance_update_at_top() it uses read_deleted='yes' and
db.instance_update() will update all fields provided, unlike
objects which only update fields that have changed.

Closes-Bug: #1460350

Change-Id: I4e8c1a82a3c9c86038faa7f528b9dfb835f82ee6

commit_message:
Modify ipset functional tests to pass on older machines

Production code uses ipset exclusively in the root namespace,
however functional testing uses ipset in namespace for isolation.
This poses an issue as ipset is not supported in namespaces on
all kernels and distributions (I'm looking at you CentOS/RHEL 7.1).

This patch changes the ipset functional tests to work in the root
namespace while taking care of cleanups.

Conflicts:
	neutron/tests/functional/agent/linux/test_ipset.py

Change-Id: I08b2f59197ed76e59b2e58b5a10820653e857cda
Closes-Bug: #1460220
(cherry picked from commit 96e2314c8c0f06967b53828b0a771973f0031243)

commit_message:
Unify the conductor file and class naming style

Modify the kube file and classes into k8s_conductor to keep the
same style with the bay_conductor and the docker_conductor.

Change-Id: I2d32c443fbfbb130896d45406af5cfd0bf5d2203
Closes-Bug:#1464156

commit_message:
Add unique constraints in Subnet

'network_id', 'cidr' should be unique in the table.
These constraints are essential to detect concurrent modifications
of the Subnet table if there are multiple neutron-server.

Change-Id: I996acfe4cc31774255a5c86f197e3a6d35f45b43
Closes-bug: #1464116

commit_message:
Add sphinxcontrib.httpdomain to test-requirements

* rtfd docs builds are failing due to missing lib [1]
* add the missing lib to test-requirements so we can publish latest docs
* removed test_service to make gate stable

[1]: https://readthedocs.org/builds/cue/2946531/

commit_message:
Use latest Lithium daily build, move ODL_NETVIRT_KARAF_FEATURE

Patch 2: move ODL_NETVIRT_KARAF_FEATURE setting into specific release,
         as the karaf features use vary depending on the release.
Patch 3: shorten commit headline.
Patch 4: remove karaf feature not needed to be explicitly provided in
         lithium settings: odl-base-all.
Patch 5: Correct loading order of features for Lithium.
Patch 6: To work around wonky ODL aaa bootup issues, increase ODL_BOOT_WAIT
         to a ludicrous 10 minutes. #sadpanda

Change-Id: Ic411424fdb48e6dfdb67eb787175d638396b0f46
Co-Authored-By: Kyle Mestery <mestery@mestery.com>
Signed-off-by: Kyle Mestery <mestery@mestery.com>

commit_message:
modifying test_service to pass a config-file arg

cfg.CONF(), which is being called by service.prepare_service, is
throwing an insufficient argument error.  This seems to be fixed by
providing a config-file arg.  Modified the test to pass in the
config-file arg with a path to the sample cue.conf

Change-Id: Ib2c8790400607dc6b7486909ef3ec437d84c5cc6

commit_message:
Fixes 3PAR snapshot failure with optional params

Create snapshot fails when HP3PAR hp3par_snapshot_retention and/or
hp3par_snapshot_expiration parameters were set in cinder.conf. The
params were being sent to the backend as strings instead on integers.

Change-Id: I24d0bc133c48b47a27f5c112e9cd924dd0fa3bcc
Closes-bug: #1461640

commit_message:
Fix tempest ShareUserRules* tests

Fix handling of return value from create_share 
in resource_setup.

These test classes (part of 'test_rules') are 
not currently used in CI and are not runnable 
because the resource_setup is still expecting a
tuple to be returned from create_share, but that 
method no longer returns a tuple.

This fix makes the following tests runnable:
- test_create_delete_user_rule
- test_create_delete_ro_access_rule

Change-Id: Ia4324e2bc9ea4cf80ed61e7c23110e9f4068a59b

commit_message:
Trivial exception parameter name fix for Huawei

Trivially fix the Exception parameter name from "msg=x" to the
proper "message=" to ensure generated errors are reported properly.

Change-Id: Ifdbe0c7cc7824763f5ed3a1ccef374a8bd0dce4b
Closes-Bug: 1462091

commit_message:
Remove external bridge from Compute nodes

This change modifies overcloud-resource-registry-puppet.yaml to
use net-config-noop.yaml as the default os-net-config template
for compute nodes. The current default of net-config-bridge.yaml
will set up a br-ex on the compute nodes. Since we are not using
DVR that is not needed.

Change-Id: I9e9a3e842f67a6081ffc376fce8e6d659a228b93

commit_message:
Cache a new token when the existing token expires

The client.keyring_saver attribute was not being reliably set so the
client._save_keys function was not storing any new tokens in the
keyring.

Add a unit test to ensure keyring_saver is being property set.

Closes-Bug: #1397732
Change-Id: If0df24c819d71b4df302309d049079a867a11c76

commit_message:
API: remove unuseful expected error code from v2.1 service delete api

There isn't any BadRequest exception raise from this api method.
Remove it.

DOCImpact: service delete will not raise 400.
Closes-Bug: #1452522

Change-Id: Iad489926176aa5ebf4ab914f1ba6e4546e913fc5

- gate-tripleo-specs-docs http://docs-draft.openstack.org/67/162267/2/check/gate-tripleo-specs-docs/0a9f1e6//doc/build/html/ : SUCCESS in 2m 12s
- gate-tripleo-specs-python27 http://logs.openstack.org/67/162267/2/check/gate-tripleo-specs-python27/99cc3dd/ : SUCCESS in 2m 03s'}, {'account_id': 10035, 'date': '2015-03-13 00:24:20.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Might be a good idea to split out the liberty specs fixes into their own patch so we can nobrain +A it.'}, {'account_id': 7144, 'date': '2015-03-13 00:47:03.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

(4 comments)

I like the idea, but I'm not following the proposed implementation.

We've got a bit of additional code that merges all the yaml bits into one big arguments.yaml. Where would that live and get executed?

There's new code somewhere that essentially considers the hook script that's about to be executed, figures out what element it is from, prepares an environment based on the current environment and what that element allows via arguments.yaml, then executes the hook script in the new environment. Where would that live and get executed? I think you're proposing dib-run-parts. But isn't that too late in the process? The hook scripts are all living side-by-side in a shared .d directory by that point. You could be implying refactoring that bit as well, but it's not entirely clear.

Am I understanding the intent correctly, or am I just confused :) ?"}, {'account_id': 10035, 'date': '2015-03-13 00:47:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

(6 comments)'}, {'account_id': 10035, 'date': '2015-03-13 04:49:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 6488, 'date': '2015-03-13 17:13:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

(8 comments)

James, Greg, thanks for your thoughts and concerns. I think some clarification as to where we think the implementation will happen is in order, and at least some framework for how I envision the code working. It should be relatively straight forward, with some python to gather the arguments, emit the unique environments, and then map each unique environment to each script.'}, {'account_id': 10035, 'date': '2015-03-13 17:56:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 6488, 'date': '2015-06-11 22:30:05.000000000', 'content': "Abandoned

I don't have time to pursue this. As much as I like it, I don't think its right to have it sitting here in the review queue when I don't think I could complete it."}]

commit_message:
Switch from MySQL-python to PyMySQL

As discussed in the Liberty Design Summit "Moving apps to Python 3"
cross-project workshop, the way forward in the near future is to
switch to the pure-python PyMySQL library as a default.

https://etherpad.openstack.org/p/liberty-cross-project-python3

Change-Id: Id90397af332408111f23001a16dad24b0195c595

Add missing unit test for goodness weigher

Add a unit test for goodness weigher to test unset goodness
function in host capabilities.

commit_message:
Tintri Cinder Volume driver

* Volume Create/Delete
* Volume Attach/Detach
* Snapshot Create/Delete
* Create Volume from Snapshot
* Get Volume Stats
* Copy Image to Volume
* Copy Volume to Image
* Clone Volume
* Extend Volume

Implements: blueprint tintri-cinder-driver

Change-Id: I4d9f2805e02524e0e271a263376b446565294d28

commit_message:
Create and initialize the nova api_db

Going forward, nova will have another database at the API level (similar to how
current cells has an api-level cell, with its own database). This patch creates
and initializes it so that we can start testing the migrations with grenade.

Change-Id: I0dfae32102aeda9c5d17e134527b6a18f4b88014

This will break attaches for your array.

https://github.com/openstack/nova/blob/master/nova/virt/libvirt/volume.py#L493

You need to wait for the Nova os-brick patch to land:

commit_message:
Dell SC: Added support for alternate iscsi portals

Added support for returning alternate target portals,
luns and iqns in a non multipath setup.  This was done
per https://review.openstack.org/#/c/140877/  Tests
were modified to support this change.

The iscsi initialize_connection and find_iscsi_properties
functions took the brunt of this.  The full list of portals,
luns and iqns are returned along with the preferred portal,
lun and iqn rather than a single iqn, lun and portal.

Some minor log message changes for clarity.  (Removed the
one character vars.)

Comment cleanup and clarification.

Implements: blueprint dell-sc-add-alternate-iscsi-portals
Change-Id: I40ad7c2e9b92fd6c6780ad181fcbccd25021d312

commit_message:
Handle ineffective backup compression

Don't compress chunks when compressed length is not a gain over
original, uncompressed length.

With incremental backups, where chunks can be built from short
"extents", the likelihood of this situation has significantly
increased.

Closes-Bug: 1462268
Change-Id: Id960cb22ae74f19154f49a0c19ee07a00145067f

commit_message:
Dell SC: Expanded comments and update var names

Additional comments have been added to help explain what is happening
in the driver. This revolves mostly around dell_storagecenter_api.py
which is not an obvious file for a reviewer to review. Hopefully
additional comments will aid this.

Updated single character variable names except for r which is the
REST calls return throughout the code by convention.

Reworked create_volume for clarity. No functional changes.

Changed two obvious error messages from LOG.debug to LOG.error.

Driver version changed to 1.0.2.

Change-Id: Ib41d9bc45d20af4fc179b691549fe52f8bd6ec6d

commit_message:
Windows SMBFS: Fix image resize errors during volume creation

When creating volumes from images or snapshots, the corresponding
virtual disk image is resized up to the volume size.

At the moment, the resize is performed even if the image already
has the requested size. This can raise an excepion in some
environments.

This patch checks the image size and performs the resize only if
it's required.

Change-Id: Ib65f0e8d69f93ae21975eb46ba24e085c06e4e34
Closes-Bug: #1437306

commit_message:
Open the version limit for stevedore

Now we're limiting the stevedore's version as stevedore>=1.3,<1.4,
but all the other components are using stevedore>=1.3. However,
the only version can be accessed from PyPI is 1.5, so the devestack
will always fail. This patch will open it to be consistent with the
other components.

Change-Id: Id7d9d6951954a0bea6cdeec1680ec99839d37412

commit_message:
Fixes to allow a new release

Version 0.7.0 has a conflicting pbr requirement, so we need to update
the requirements and produce a new release. Making our tools work after
importing into gerrit required several updates simultaneously:

1. Update requirements based on our global-requirements list.
2. Fix tox.ini so tests pass for 2.7 and 3.4.
3. Skip a test that is failing for 3.4 until we have more time to debug.
4. Fix the .gitreview settings to point to the right repository.
5. Add skeleton documentation structure.
6. Add links to the README in a format understood by our release tools.

Related-bug: #1403214
Change-Id: I28213fb1dbb76a8640d7aa7dc844a7b593d1c6da

commit_message:
Use ebtables to isolate dhcp traffic

Iptables doesn't properly block the broadcast traffic crossing
the bridge, so use ebtables instead. Removes test which is no
longer valid since we are not using iptables anymore.

(cherry picked from commit 1236b09076cca3b4b16538b055e52edde5a4feea)

Conflicts:
	nova/tests/network/test_linux_net.py

Change-Id: I43e5f1fe9512dd3ec9595c7203bc46837cef3cad
Closes-Bug: #1318104

commit_message:
Add initial dynamic deployment role

Addition of a basic role to support dynamic deployment from
an inventory as opposed to a CSV file.

This contains an additional conceptual feature of allowing a user
to override the default instance_info by defining it as a variable.

Updated test-bifrost-dynamic.yaml to incorporate the dynamic
deployment role.

Change-Id: I5e95c4963b3deff74243126385713ac678f38759

commit_message:
Add support for ceilometer-polling agent

Add ability to use new ceilometer-polling agent
instead of ceilometer-central, ceilometer-compute or
ceilometer-ipmi. Specify central_namespace, compute_namespace
and ipmi_namespace parameters to set namespaces

Change-Id: I066f601a5234cb689c98e8eea2b5790bdaa5b8b5
(cherry picked from commit 85c742cd830a16a597b81816215ca387d12a9d54)

acceptance: update serverspec syntax

Since we unpin beaker, serverspec is now 2.18.0 (before it was 1.16.0)
so we need to update some syntax to make the tests work.

Change-Id: Ie097f951123501f42e1a85abb81d2de556c4f749

commit_message:
REST API layer for Artifact Repository

Adds REST API layer for Artifact Repository, binds all other changes
together.

Artifact Repository is run as a part of Glance api.
Requests are routed to /v3/artifacts endpoint on the api port.
API version in version selector is marked as experimental.

Registers artifacts service and a sample Artifact Type in Glance entry
points config.

Implements-blueprint: artifact-repository

FastTrack

Co-Authored-By: Inessa Vasilevskaya <ivasilevskaya@mirantis.com>
Co-Authored-By: Mike Fedosin <mfedosin@mirantis.com>
Co-Authored-By: Alexander Tivelkov <ativelkov@mirantis.com>

Change-Id: Ib6a0d2482208a37aa343a747dfe5f63f9080dd04

commit_message:
beaker: enable voting for puppet-(keystone/openstacklib)

Beaker tests are ready to vote in puppet-keystone & puppet-openstacklib.
We are currently making some critical changes due to Keystone API v3
support in puppet-keystone, and having Beaker voting will help us to
catch errors during reviews.

This patch aims to:
* enable voting for puppet-keystone and puppet-openstacklib
* continue to disable the beaker jobs on stable/* (only running master)
* bring the jobs to the gate

Change-Id: Ifbd17d45425a993a8f600c61eced8bc9041a91f1

commit_message:
Addition of dynamic configuration drives

Adding a modified role, and base testing playbook updates, to allow
for dynamic generation of configuration drives utilizing the dynamic
inventory.

Change-Id: Ibe4a5761da828a39066d99c75b724af5ff670239

OSAD installation guide.

commit_message:
Enable agent_ipmitool driver when testing

In testing, it may be useful to be able to define and utilize the
agent_ipmitool driver as moving forward with dynamic inventory we
will be able to hosts using different drivers from the same
inventory.

Change-Id: I0986a4f859210683e1139e2277b16cd072bbf7d3

I considered mentioning it in the readme and my first sketch for the change included it but I reverted narrowly after a bit of indecision.

I did not want to break the current behavior, which is things work for single-site deploys. I also didn't want to break the limited documentation available which makes clear that you are required to supply a "galera_address" that should point to the internal load-balanced address for the cluster. Anything simple I did to change the way the readme was documented felt like it was making that less clear.

I'm open to suggestions or patches to address it, though.'}, {'account_id': 6816, 'date': '2015-06-09 10:18:39.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: -Code-Review

reverting my +2 until Andy's query is resolved"}, {'account_id': 2799, 'date': '2015-06-09 14:40:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

I see why you had indecision. I also have that.
This is a really minor point so apologies for stalling the commit for that!

If the README's reference the new var wouldn't it work in anycase? As long as the appropriate var is specified, that is to say if "cinder_galera_address" defaults to "galera_address" if I pass in "cinder_galera_address" or galera_address the end result from a single deploy would be exactly the same?
I'm a bit confused in that the galera_address is not a variable that we set anywhere, we only call it in the playbooks, it almost seems like this should be in user_variables.yml and then we shouldn't pass it over when we call the playbook, but perhaps I'm missing something here. That would mean changing the playbooks themselves also.

The way we're setting the galera_address seems odd to me. (I realise thats somewhat unrelated to this PR but I think if we figure that out then the whole README/playbook thing becomes clearer)'}, {'account_id': 12807, 'date': '2015-06-09 18:57:26.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 12807, 'date': '2015-06-09 18:57:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

commit_message:
Configure DB addresses for each service

To enable partitioning of DB traffic by-service, each service needs to
use a custom connection string. Defaulting the service address to a
common galera_address makes things continue to work by default.

While the galera_address could be overridden on a container or host
basis this requires repeating that behavior across each infra node in
the inventory. Providing service-specific connection address variables
simplifies the management somewhat for large deployments and may reduce
error rates.

The service install playbooks now default the service-specific variables
instead of galera_address to the internal lb vip from inventory to
maintain the ease-of-use currently available.

Any value for a service-specific variable set in user_variables.yml will
override the value in the playbook's vars to provide selective
customization as needed.

Change-Id: I4c98bf906a0c1cb11ddd41277a855dce22ff646a
Closes-Bug: 1462529

commit_message:
Pass OpenStack environment variables to client tests

tox 2 does not pass the environment by default, this is
a change from tox 1.6. Instead, environment variables
may be passed by means of the "passenv" variable in
tox.ini. This mechanism supports globbing, so "OS_*"
can be used to set the necessary environment variables
for the python-saharaclient.

Change-Id: Ibe9055dd4d4bc1a243db5198a9e5e35e5f93f628

commit_message:
Migrate to oslo.utils

This removes akanda.rug's minimal usage of openstack.common.importutils
in favor of the equivalent oslo_utils.import_utils.

Note the old module is still left in place as its used by other old
oslo-incubator things.

Change-Id: I256c87db84d55fb6957252d2593b9ed15b7f35aa

commit_message:
acceptance: pin rabbitmq module to 5.2.1

5.2.1 is the last puppetlabs-rabbitmq with puppetlabs-apt < 2.x.
Also update metadata.json to be coherent with the requirements.
Also update serverspec syntaxt to work with latest release of Beaker and
serverspec.

Change-Id: I7db0393bedf55eadd09685f853196fae18607b11

[{'created': '2015-05-27 14:18:50.000000000', 'message': 'Change documentation to recommend Docker 1.7.0-dev

Docker 1.7.0-dev includes a working overlayfs driver.  It also includes
the ability for us to make neutron into a thin container via a netns run
in the PID namespace.  For an example of a tool to do this, check out:

https://github.com/SamYaple/yaodu/blob/master/ansible/roles/docker_build/files/ubuntu/neutron/ip_wrapper.py

Change-Id: Ie422185ea090090b35fcaa2e1c6ecab1c8ea326b
'}, {'created': '2015-05-31 17:28:09.000000000', 'message': 'Change documentation to recommend Docker 1.7.0-dev

Docker 1.7.0-dev is required to support cinder and neutron thin containers.
It would also be helpful that we validate that Docker 1.7.0-dev is working
well with Kolla.

For more details on the Neutron thin containers check out:

https://github.com/SamYaple/yaodu/blob/master/ansible/roles/docker_build/files/ubuntu/neutron/ip_wrapper.py

Change-Id: Ie422185ea090090b35fcaa2e1c6ecab1c8ea326b
'}]
commit_message:
Change documentation to recommend Docker 1.7.0-dev

Docker 1.7.0-dev is required to support cinder and neutron thin containers.
It would also be helpful that we validate that Docker 1.7.0-dev is working
well with Kolla.

For more details on the Neutron thin containers check out:

https://github.com/SamYaple/yaodu/blob/master/ansible/roles/docker_build/files/ubuntu/neutron/ip_wrapper.py

Change-Id: Ie422185ea090090b35fcaa2e1c6ecab1c8ea326b

Add oslo.service documentation

Updated library's description in README.rst with one that is used
on Launchpad and PyPi.

Interesting idea - I think I see where this is going.

For dynamically fetching the inventory from ironic, it should accept the output of shade list_machines() as well, so if the format returned from this .py file matches (I haven't checked) then good.

I'd also suggest using a more generic ENV var, like BIFROST_INVENTORY_SOURCE, then detect whether it is a .csv file or not. Ditto for the .py file's name"}, {'account_id': 13997, 'date': '2015-05-25 15:24:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

Devananda, I like the idea to pull in a list and detect if one of the elements is a file, and read from that file.  One thing that I'm wanting to make sure is we can process and merge a number of data sources together, and that we have a simple example to be built upon as I received some interest at the summit about using CMDBs to drive deployment processes.

The format doesn't currently match, but supporting list_machines() is a good idea.  The logical progression of that is to gear the variables to largely be pass-throughs which is something that requires a little more thought in my mind."}, {'account_id': 13997, 'date': '2015-05-29 16:26:14.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-05-29 17:08:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1
