commit_message:
Initial inventory module

An initial module to facilitate the conversion of Bifrost to
leverage an inventory instead of a CSV file and an updated
requirements.txt file to meet the package requirements to
run the inventory.

Change-Id: I2eb1c8d674e0d6e298b22a7c3d9fd425658a5cc2

commit_message:
Check for 'removed' in port_info before reference

scan_ports can return early on no changes, in which case
'removed' won't be present in the dict. The deleted_ports
logic wasn't setup to handle that.

This patch checks for the key before trying to reference it.

Change-Id: I0e2c6d76515ad8e2a2addc8d40451ac003a150f7
Closes-Bug: #1461325

This reverts commit 6185ef643963c05d064429b59d9935f078a798f7.

running before devstack-gate runs to check out the source.  We should

commit_message:
Revert "networking-ovn: Allow setting devstack-gate env vars"

This reverts commit 6185ef643963c05d064429b59d9935f078a798f7.

This isn't harming anything, but it turns out to be useless as this is
running before devstack-gate runs to check out the source.  We should
remove it so it doesn't serve as a bad example to try to follow.

Change-Id: I7118952ecf34d827b6e78d59cc094602229430ab
Signed-off-by: Russell Bryant <rbryant@redhat.com>

After main deploy part we mark all nodes as 'ready'. If we
run stop deployment in this case, Nailgun will send to Astute
empty nodes list to stop. Before this change we fail to
run mcollective on empty nodes list.

Change-Id: Ib5b8298eb761f8f6123efc0dedce538c4f63b68d
Closes-Bug: #1463881
(cherry picked from commit d4f2bd1129f1b7579d1cdcca14cff27502a51fdc)
"}]
commit_message:
Prevent stop deployment fail in case of post-deployments hooks

After main deploy part we mark all nodes as 'ready'. If we
run stop deployment in this case, Nailgun will send to Astute
empty nodes list to stop. Before this change we fail to
run mcollective on empty nodes list.

Change-Id: Ib5b8298eb761f8f6123efc0dedce538c4f63b68d
Closes-Bug: #1463881
(cherry picked from commit d4f2bd1129f1b7579d1cdcca14cff27502a51fdc)

commit_message:
Add support for Fernet Tokens

This adds support for Fernet token creation during the installation and
config options for Fernet tokens.

Change-Id: I43657e9ba46f07c316a9e67a134e30aa3a44a867

commit_message:
Prevent stop deployment fail in case of post-deployments hooks

After main deploy part we mark all nodes as 'ready'. If we
run stop deployment in this case, Nailgun will send to Astute
empty nodes list to stop. Before this change we fail to
run mcollective on empty nodes list.

Change-Id: Ib5b8298eb761f8f6123efc0dedce538c4f63b68d
Closes-Bug: #1463881

commit_message:
Allow setting reseller_prefix for keystone filter

When using keystone, it's possible to modify the behaviour to
use a different prefix instead of the default AUTH_.

This patch allows you to be able to set that option when
declaring your class definition.

Change-Id: I11ff23d118e0f3d1792b43e1dc7a2c82c6826427
(cherry picked from commit 2a845da2944cb0a33e2f411c22be12f866b60a4f)

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-06-05 22:10:30.000000000', 'message': "Fix ipv6 support

One shold never parse uri with split(':') as it was in types
ring_account_device, ring_container_device and ring_object_device.
This is fixed by using uri and just setting variables from that.
Also swift_ring_builder didn't add brackets to ipv6 address before
adding port information to it.

Change-Id: I55b7032143c8446abeed4f6c266c0fff0cb6b3b3
(cherry picked from commit b6ba9f09b291252a196d69c3e30b188fe77c2c4a)
"}]
commit_message:
Fix ipv6 support

One shold never parse uri with split(':') as it was in types
ring_account_device, ring_container_device and ring_object_device.
This is fixed by using uri and just setting variables from that.
Also swift_ring_builder didn't add brackets to ipv6 address before
adding port information to it.

Change-Id: I55b7032143c8446abeed4f6c266c0fff0cb6b3b3
(cherry picked from commit b6ba9f09b291252a196d69c3e30b188fe77c2c4a)

commit_message:
ConsistencyGroup: Return 400 instead of 500 for invalid body

If invalid request body is passed to the delete
consistencygroups api, then it returns 500 error.

Validated request body using 'is_valid_body()' method
and also added validation to check 'force' is of bool type.

APIImpact

Closes-Bug: #1458868
Change-Id: Iaaa4409233bfed6ae3e67be5df8cc5ada28e054f

commit_message:
Update LH CLIQ cinder driver with deprecation warn

This patch adds a deprecation message to the HPLeftHandISCSIDriver CLIQ
driver docs with the plan of removing the driver in the 2016.1 release.
The HPLeftHandISCSIDriver REST based driver should be used instead.

See warning message patch in the cinder driver:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/187799

Change-Id: I8e924aa688c0868f37757323569567994c14a856

commit_message:
Adds Hyper-V imagecache cleanup

At the moment the Hyper-V driver's imagecache only deals with caching
the images in _base.

This blueprint will deal with implementing imagecache management that will
allow the aging and deletion of cached images that are no longer in use.

This is a driver feature parity blueprint.

Implements: blueprint hyper-v-imagecache-cleanup

Change-Id: I9d787095e91c2366683d060c0eaf21aeedf58fbb

[{'created': '2015-06-11 16:05:59.000000000', 'message': 'Fix config option fallback if "include" missing

Currently, if an "include" stanza is missing from the config
file and recursive checking is requested, a nasty error is
experienced.

When the included config option is used, it is supposed to
sanely fall back to the default of "*.py", but rather than
being set as a list (as is expected) a coding error sets it
to be a string.

This change resolves this issue by returning a list of one
item ['*.py'], rather than a string.

Change-Id: Ieb631032d1cc2d6e1864ca3d26b2155219fbd13e
Closes-bug: #1434281
Signed-off-by: Dave Walker (Daviey) <email@daviey.com>
'}]
commit_message:
Fix config option fallback if "include" missing

Currently, if an "include" stanza is missing from the config
file and recursive checking is requested, a nasty error is
experienced.

When the included config option is used, it is supposed to
sanely fall back to the default of "*.py", but rather than
being set as a list (as is expected) a coding error sets it
to be a string.

This change resolves this issue by returning a list of one
item ['*.py'], rather than a string.

Change-Id: Ieb631032d1cc2d6e1864ca3d26b2155219fbd13e
Closes-bug: #1434281
Signed-off-by: Dave Walker (Daviey) <email@daviey.com>

commit_message:
Add Neutron PTL Office Hours

To ensure a weekly oppurtunity to sync between the PTL and the
Lieutenants, officially setup Neutron PTL Office Hours.

Depends-On: Ia5c8090e90939097104cb95c0aa3b883f7b4dd9b
Change-Id: Iab3c21764937ebb3a1d0553b3a3d42b5c44bf3cc
Signed-off-by: Kyle Mestery <mestery@mestery.com>

commit_message:
Add manila client to heat requirements

The requirements for manila client has been added (the version is
the same as global-requirements version). Also the manilaclient version
is introduced when creating a client.

Change-Id: Id487c94477e82addbb98e5402ae50f0151c87669

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. The more you
    participate in the community the more rewarding it is for you. You may also
    notice that the more you get to know people and get to be known, the faster
    your patches will be reviewed and eventually approved. Get to know others
    and become known by doing code reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a
    great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

    IRC: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/IRC
    Workflow: http://docs.openstack.org/infra/manual/developers.html

commit_message:
Add error catching to the cleanup method for Heat tests

If the test fails on some step it calls cleanup method that tries
to delete the created stack, but in case if there is some problem
in it user won't see errors in FUEL web, that's why error catching
was added.

Closes-Bug: #1463339

Change-Id: I93b72d24e54dde31c9dd608c98be857aa9a65657

commit_message:
Add error catching to the cleanup method for Heat tests

If the test fails on some step it calls cleanup method that tries
to delete the created stack, but in case if there is some problem
in it user won't see errors in FUEL web, that's why error catching
was added.

Closes-Bug: #1463339

Change-Id: I93b72d24e54dde31c9dd608c98be857aa9a65657

As for "default", a default has been a hard thing to change or specify in my experience. Most of the other clients have Session handling and the current advice is people should use that instead of passing usernames and passwords. I don't know how they plan to handle the deprecation though.

commit_message:
Make glanceclient accept a session object

To make this work we create a different HTTPClient that extends the
basic keystoneclient Adapter. The Adapter is a standard set of
parameters that all clients should know how to use like region_name and
user_agent. We extend this with the glance specific response
manipulation like loading and sending iterables.

Implements: bp session-objects
Change-Id: Ie8eb4bbf7d1a037099a6d4b272cab70525fbfc85

commit_message:
Merge tag '2015.1.0'

This is a null-merge of the 2015.1.0 release tag back into the master
branch so that the 2015.1.0 tag will appear in the git commit history of
the master branch. It contains no actual changes to the master branch,
regardless of how our code review system's UI represents it. Please
ask in #openstack-infra if you have any questions, and otherwise try
to merge this as quickly as possible to avoid later conflicts on the
master branch.

Change-Id: I76a736bd12372cff6c7fb3936b0eeb520a96ba08

commit_message:
Merge tag '2014.2'

This is a null-merge of the 2014.2 release tag back into the
master branch. It contains no actual changes to the master branch,
regardless of how our code review system's UI represents it. Please
ask in #openstack-infra if you have any questions, and otherwise try
to merge this as quickly as possible to avoid later conflicts on the
master branch.

Change-Id: I16744c997f71f3680b2e12aaee8631f0e6b6b3d5

commit_message:
Do not run mongo checks for old releases

In Fuel releases before 6.1 we didn't have 'external mongo' feature,
and therefore running mongo checks is invalid operation.

Closes-Bug: #1463880

Change-Id: I58dd0ebd6de610448bf297d0bd97c6a334f6abc0
Signed-off-by: Igor Kalnitsky <igor@kalnitsky.org>

commit_message:
Pin upper bound of python-cinderclient version

python-cinderclient > 1.2.1 require python-keystoneclinet 1.6 when we install
1.4 due to fix problem with pbr version caused by keystonemiddleware
We could require higher versiona of keystonemiddleware (>=1.5) but it
would be much higher than the version we have in repos (1.2) for 6.1

Change-Id: I449d23cf5e563b9de386beb249437bbf98db47f3
Closes-Bug: #1464132
(cherry picked from commit 9f6004fac838a42cab281094e2a574bb5dfe5295)

commit_message:
Pin upper bound of python-cinderclient version

python-cinderclient > 1.2.1 require python-keystoneclinet 1.6 when we install
1.4 due to fix problem with pbr version caused by keystonemiddleware
We could require higher versiona of keystonemiddleware (>=1.5) but it
would be much higher than the version we have in repos (1.2) for 6.1

Change-Id: I449d23cf5e563b9de386beb249437bbf98db47f3
Closes-Bug: #1464132

commit_message:
install_venv_common no longer in oslo-incubator

Remove reference to the file as it is no longer in the oslo-incubator
repo. Note that the file still exists in keystone, but just advertising
the fact that a future sync will not refresh the file as it is no longer
present in oslo-incubator and imply keystone owns the file now.

Change-Id: Ic7591accee78637bef2413def75dbe6a9888495d

commit_message:
Do not run mongo checks for old releases

In Fuel releases before 6.1 we didn't have 'external mongo' feature,
and therefore running mongo checks is invalid operation.

Closes-Bug: #1463880

Change-Id: I58dd0ebd6de610448bf297d0bd97c6a334f6abc0
Signed-off-by: Igor Kalnitsky <igor@kalnitsky.org>

commit_message:
Rework processing hook interface for 2.0.0

This is a backward incompatible change of hooks interfaces.
The goal is to make these interfaces easier extensible, and to give
hooks access to NodeInfo instance.

Change-Id: I5b00a71e86a5a57111c25b0e16c662107074c21f
Implements: blueprint plugin-interface-v2

Cloud driver is not needed

At this time, we have a cloud driver for nova, but it isn't used by anywhere.

Change-Id: I23a12caa8651d5ae076b78d899905c96f3f8d61e
Closes-Bug: #1464109

commit_message:
Add help message for secgroup-add/del-default-rule

Add help message about only work with the nova-network backend, not neutron
for 'secgroup-add-default-rule' and 'secgroup-delete-default-rule'.

Change-Id: Ia88b022d86505c2d7baa920fafbbfbaee04e4e58
Closes-Bug: #1419739

commit_message:
IBP: /boot on small hard drive if possible

On some hardware GRUB can not see huge hard drives (>2T)
due to firmware bugs, so we'd better avoid placing
/boot on such drives if it is possible.

Change-Id: I71e0255820edef4725208db777bf5e0bf8d3958c
Partial-Bug: #1461126

commit_message:
virt: convert VFS API to use nova.virt.image.model

Convert the nova.virt.disk.vfs classes to use the
nova.virt.image.model classes instead of manually
passing a filename and image format as parameters.
This enables the libguestfs impl to now support the
configuration of RBD images.

Related-Bug: #1257674
Change-Id: I41d6af52ffed924d35ac255625488f40f7989a0a

commit_message:
Document ideas for supporting provider networks

We do not currently have a way to support Neutorn provider networks in
OVN.  I'd like to propose a way forward so I started writing up a
proposal.  I'm putting this up for review here to get initial feedback
from other Neutorn developers that this seems to make sense.  Once
the proposal seems baked enough, I'll post it to the ovs-dev mailing
list for discussion there.

Change-Id: I3771140880cb6eaafea2606268813effa3d4004a
Signed-off-by: Russell Bryant <rbryant@redhat.com>

I'm concerned this is not available in RH/Suse."}, {'account_id': 7448, 'date': '2014-12-16 17:56:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Mark, I share your concern.  I guess I was hoping that making it an optional feature would make it okay.  Maybe that is wishful thinking.

The bigger problem is that RAWSNAT and RAWDNAT have been removed from xtables-addons altogether [1] due to lack of maintenance.  That makes me sad.  Even if we were to find a maintainer and get it back in, the damage has been done.  The targets are not available in trusty and probably other recent releases.

So, Is the only hope to go with the tc based implementation (which I know little about)?

 [1] http://sourceforge.net/p/xtables-addons/xtables-addons/ci/9414a5df343bf30ba13e76dbd7181c55683b11cb/'}, {'account_id': 105, 'date': '2014-12-17 16:48:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review-2

I think this needs to be deferred to post kilo given all the concerns discussed here as well as in channel.'}, {'account_id': 7448, 'date': '2015-01-05 18:14:06.000000000', 'content': "Abandoned

I'm hoping that after the L3 agent refactor, it will be easier to add this capability without being too intrusive."}, {'account_id': 7448, 'date': '2015-04-01 18:58:10.000000000', 'content': 'Restored'}, {'account_id': 7448, 'date': '2015-04-01 18:58:38.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 5.'}, {'account_id': 7448, 'date': '2015-04-01 19:02:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Workflow-1

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 13734, 'date': '2015-04-21 09:14:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Code-Review+1

This continues to look good to me. I had a couple of queries, but they're both minor and probably don't justify any change to the spec.

- Firstly, I assume this NAT processing occurs at the same places as for current stateful NAT; and I think that means on the network node(s) for pre-DVR setups, and on compute nodes for DVR. Is that all correct? 

- Secondly, I wonder if anyone ever deploys a hybrid platform cloud? I.e. where it might be possible for one compute/network node to have the xtables add-on, but another not. In that case I guess the global flag would be interpreted as "do stateless NAT if possible, otherwise stateful".

Thanks - Neil'}, {'account_id': 7448, 'date': '2015-04-27 22:20:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

@Neil.  Your first assumption is correct about where NAT will occur.

We are in the process of writing this BP without xtables-addons.  We found that the stateless NAT capability was deprecated and removed from it so it can no longer be used.  tc is the only alternative left.'}, {'account_id': 13734, 'date': '2015-04-28 11:45:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

Thanks Carl.  Sorry to hear that the RAW settings are being removed - they seemed ideal for this work.'}, {'account_id': 8124, 'date': '2015-04-29 22:21:17.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 6.'}, {'account_id': 8124, 'date': '2015-04-29 22:23:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

PS6: use tc to perform stateless nat as xtables-addons RAWSNAT/RAWDNAT have been removed.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-04-29 22:27:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Verified+1

I like not needing exotic iptables modules.

(I'm disappointed we still need a disable option and can't remove the old code.  Floating-ips has crazy semantics - can't we just replace it with either some more generic LBaaS DNAT, or hand out the floating-ip address as the only interface address via DHCP?  Not a serious question.)"}, {'account_id': 7448, 'date': '2015-04-30 20:32:34.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6: Code-Review+1

I'm a little concerned with the data model.

If I have 20 instances across 10 cells, does a `nova list` require 10 backend calls? How does it behave if one of those 10 cells control plane is unavailable? 

I don't see a good way around this issue with out some form of top level caching/storing of those attributes."}, {'account_id': 5441, 'date': '2015-06-09 17:45:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

Andy: Yes, it would require 10 database calls to get info for those 20 instances.  There are plans and some work being done so that those database calls could be parallel operations so the performance impact should be alleviated somewhat.  Longer term we may need to add a cache at the api level that can handle list requests.  For now the idea is to get this working for a single cell, and then a caching layer like that would be discussed before scaling out to multiple cells.'}, {'account_id': 5441, 'date': '2015-06-09 18:43:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

I forgot to mention http://git.openstack.org/cgit/openstack/nova/tree/doc/source/cells.rst#n63.  The potential for some data to be unavailable is acknowledged.'}, {'account_id': 782, 'date': '2015-06-11 11:55:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8: Code-Review+2

Given the scope for liberty:
http://specs.openstack.org/openstack/nova-specs/priorities/liberty-priorities.html#cells-v2

I think we are good with this. We know about the 10 API call issue, and there is a plan to have an explicit caching layer than can be used for deployments where N is considered large, once we work out what large means in this context.'}, {'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2015-06-11 13:06:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8: Code-Review+2 Workflow+1

looks good, this is what we have been talking about for some time now.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-06-11 13:15:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8: -Verified

commit_message:
Install fence agents on the controller image

Installs fence-agents-all, and also fence-virt package to provide
fence_xvm.

Change-Id: I8b7adff6f05f864115071c51810b41efad887584

commit_message:
Fix support for auth_uri setting in neutron provider

Neutron provider still uses auth_port and auth_host config
options even though those are now deprecated and won't be set
if someone chooses to use auth_uri. This commit adds support
for auth_uri and keeps the provider backwards compatible.


Change-Id: I4824c09e6af4a800b5ac0c22bf5daea99452bd7e

commit_message:
Revert "Revert "only force off KEYSTONE_USE_WSGI up until kilo""

This reverts commit ccbfaa83ac82f14a9d7d9cc658d2899d41fc9dda.

This was never the correct fix, it just masked the root problem. This
correctly was setting the variables but there was a bug in grenade that
made this not do the right thing on stable/kilo because of a missing 
source include.

That's where it should have been fixed.

Related-Bug: #1456835

Change-Id: I557e9d7d35239b9336b6d90f037f14cdf2585f76

commit_message:
Set value for 'pool_maxsize' in keystone

 Set  new parameter 'pool_maxsize' for memcache.
 Default value was set to 100 to fix an issue with
 getting token from keystone after 10 sec timeout.

 Closes-Bug:#1455099

Change-Id: I0dd9b572d3b78c3d30cbfb4e000a457fd69d5e3a

commit_message:
Fixed issue with keystone memcache

With the default value for the 'dead_timeout' recovery
of keystone memcache service can take more than 3 minutes.
This parameter allows to reduce this timeout to 20-30 seconds.

Change-Id: Iac5076532e25295f6d9abbb9e9c1b4213931d1da
Closes-Bug: #1461036

commit_message:
Fixed issue with keystone memcache

With the default value for the 'dead_timeout' recovery
of keystone memcache service can take more than 3 minutes.
This parameter allows to reduce this timeout to 20-30 seconds.

Change-Id: Iac5076532e25295f6d9abbb9e9c1b4213931d1da
Closes-Bug: #1461036

commit_message:
Fix L3AgentSchedulerTestJSON failure for dvr routers

In L3AgentSchedulerTestJSON test class, the resource
setup method has special handling for the dvr routers,
since DVR Routers require a valid subnet with port for
the routers to be scheduled.

But in the case of Non-DVR Routers this was not required.

The resource cleanup method was missing in this test class.
But the Super class resource cleanup method was not aware
about the DVR Router and existence of the router owned ports
and hence was trying to delete the port before it removed
the router.

This patch fixes the problem by creaing a resource cleanup
method in L3AgentSchedulerTestJSON and cleans up the
interface and subnet added for the DVR Router.

Change-Id: I0fbc02a2bc8badbb1792870c34495b913572af0a
Closes-Bug: #1462150

commit_message:
Get only VM's with the full name matching

get-vm-mac would grep for a VM for example with the name 'instack'
and also VM's named 'instack.old' or 'backup-instack' would match.
This patch ensures only fully matching names are matched.

Change-Id: Ia5c59e3867bb1df9efee8288e4b78e96c5554246

commit_message:
Remove oslo-incubator copy of middleware

We have moved away from openstack/common/middleware modules
to the oslo_middlware library. Let's cleanup the remaining files,
left here to not breaking grenade in the gate.

Change-Id: I303a8f7e5c2113103de4658f0c5137a7e060fe83

commit_message:
Support BP:ipv6-router in Neutron HA Router

blueprint ipv6-router (ChangeID:Iaefa95f788053ded9fc9c7ff6845c3030c6fd6df),
supports an IPv6 Router where the router gateway port has no subnet.

The BP implements the following. If an external network (without any subnet)
is attached to the Neutron router, it reads the ipv6_gateway config parameter
(LLA of upstream router) from l3_agent.ini file and adds a default route that
points to this LLA.  If the ipv6_gateway config value is not configured, it
would configure the gateway interface to accept router advts from upstream
router to build the default route. For an HA router, we would have to
configure keepalived to perform this operation. 

This patch is a bug fix for the broken feature in kilo.

Conflicts:
        neutron/agent/l3/ha_router.py
        neutron/tests/unit/agent/l3/test_agent.py

Implements: blueprint ipv6-router
Change-Id: I26dc5ce9e46c74423358aa8a9559bc6c7cbdf85e
(cherry picked from commit 89489d2720c80c3465e36dad566aa835215fb92e)

Extends .jscsrc to ignore 3rd party files

Adds a few files that should be skipped to the .jscsrc, since they are
beyond our control (external libs, generated coverage reports etc.)

This also reduces the error count to around 2k

commit_message:
Merge tag '2015.1.0'

This is a null-merge of the 2015.1.0 release tag back into the master
branch so that the 2015.1.0 tag will appear in the git commit history of
the master branch. It contains no actual changes to the master branch,
regardless of how our code review system's UI represents it. Please
ask in #openstack-infra if you have any questions, and otherwise try
to merge this as quickly as possible to avoid later conflicts on the
master branch.

Change-Id: Ic5b95fdfa8949e85ca8601d39137cc4e4dcbb4cd

SELECT..FOR UPDATE is not compatible with Galera under normal multi-master use.  See http://www.joinfu.com/2015/01/understanding-reservations-concurrency-locking-in-nova/.   We'd prefer to use a compare and swap approach as detailed there; also see https://review.openstack.org/#/c/146228/ for the oslo.db feature that is now merged + released to support this pattern.

I'm leaving my review at +0 because I don't want to hold this back if it is needed right now, however I'd recommend against this approach."}, {'account_id': 8124, 'date': '2015-05-05 14:48:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

@mike: The aim of the methods is to choose and create a subnet cidr (ex: 10.0.0.0/24) in a pool (ex: 10.0.0.0/8) and ensures the cidr doesn't overlap with an existent/concurrently-created cidr from the pool. The workflow is:

 1) get all allocated subnet cidrs in the pool (sql query),
 2) choose a subnet cidr not overlapping with allocated subnet cidrs (python code),
 3) create the subnet with the chosen cidr (sql query).

We must ensure 1) to 3) is "atomic" per subnetpool otherwise we can create concurrently 2 subnet cidrs with overlapping cidrs


It's currently done using: 

 0) lock allocated subnet cidrs in the pool (can be empty)

But it only ensures the created cidr does not overlap existent cidrs at step 1) not at step 3), so the change proposes to use:

 0) lock subnetpool associated row to disallow concurrent allocation per subnetpool


I don't see how we can use update-on-match as we don't update the row we lock and afaik no db constraints can be used to ensure subnet cidrs in a pool don't overlap.'}, {'account_id': 14258, 'date': '2015-05-05 16:28:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

I'm not sure this change actually will serialize modifications on a per-subnetpool basis in a Galera cluster.  The "select for update" is made against the subnetpool, but because we don't modify the subnetpool record and don't use "select for update" in the subnets table we won't get any feedback from the DB about concurrent modifications to the subnets table.  Because we "select for update" on the subnetpool but don't modify it, my understanding is that Galera will happily allow concurrent transactions to be interleaved against the subnets table without any feedback.  I don't think this patch would actually fix the problem it's trying to solve in a Galera environment. As such, the bug we're trying to resolve would be fixed when running against a standalone DB, but would still exist when running against a Galera cluster? @Mike I'm not the expert in this stuff, am I way off base?'}, {'account_id': 8124, 'date': '2015-05-05 19:07:52.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

IMO, there are 3 troubles:

 * subnetpool not working with postgresql
 * non-overlapping cidrs not ensured without galera
 * non-overlapping cidrs not ensured with galera

The 2 first bullets can be solved quickly with current change.

The last bullet seems to require more work: 

  # _allocate_any_subnet
  1) get allocated cidrs
  2) choose subnet cidr
  3) create subnet
  4) get allocated cidrs
  5) recheck subnet cidr not overlapping other subnet cidrs
  6) recheck success ==> done
  7) delete subnet
  8) retry? 
  # retry requires at least to lower isolation level from REPEATABLE READ to READ COMMITTED[1]
  # for the root transaction!

  # something similar for _allocate_specific_subnet


IMO, the last bullet should be addressed in a follow-up change as neutron seems not galera-compliant (ie: uses lockmode)

in particular, you don't need to "delete" anything, retrying an operation makes use of transactions which will roll back the current work, then you can try again.  it's the basic case of optimistic vs. pessimistic concurrency control.  optimistic is generally preferable.'}, {'account_id': 8124, 'date': '2015-05-08 22:11:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

#3 (ensure non-overlapping subnets with galera) solution will replace #1/#2 solution as it addresses a larger scope.

I would really like what we merge #1/#2 solution to "unbreak" subnetpool with postgres in master and even more in stable/kilo.

For #3, READ COMMITTED isolation level is required otherwise 4) will return 1) result even if a subnet is inserted between 1) and 4)


Reminder:

  1) get allocated cidrs

  4) get allocated cidrs

  7) delete subnet
  8) retry?'}, {'account_id': 11816, 'date': '2015-05-09 00:22:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

yes, with enginefacade we are moving to be able to have specific isolation levels in use for specific methods.   In Nova there are many areas where we will need to ensure READ COMMITTED for a particular series of retryable methods.    

i know the "read committed" + "optimistic retry" thing is tedious, but the fact is Openstack is very heavy on Galera, and there are tons of cases like this that need to work identically on Galera as anywhere else.  We might as well handle them all in the same consistent way.  This is a key focus of my enginefacade work.'}, {'account_id': 8124, 'date': '2015-05-09 19:09:30.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4: Commit message was updated.'}, {'account_id': 14323, 'date': '2015-05-09 19:44:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

[{'created': '2015-05-04 21:59:05.000000000', 'message': "Ensure non-overlapping cidrs in subnetpools

_get_allocated_cidrs[1] locks only allocated subnets in a subnetpool
(with mysql/postgresql at least). It ensures we don't allocate a cidr
overlapping with existent cidrs but nothing disallows a concurrent
subnet allocation to create a subnet in the same subnetpool.

This change replaces the lock on subnetpool subnets by a lock on the
subnetpool itself. It disallows to allocate concurrently 2 subnets in
the same subnetpool and ensure non-overlapping cidrs in the same
subnetpool.

Moreover this change solves a trouble with postgresql which disallows
to lock an empty select with an outer join: it happens on first subnet
allocation in a subnetpool when no specific cidr is provided. Moving
the lock ensures the lock is done on a non-empty select.

[1] in neutron.ipam.subnet_alloc.SubnetAllocator

Change-Id: I73854f9863f44621ae0d89c5dc4893ccc16d07e4
Close-Bug: #1451576
Close-Bug: #1451558

commit_message:
Ensure non-overlapping cidrs in subnetpools without galera

_get_allocated_cidrs[1] locks only allocated subnets in a subnetpool
(with mysql/postgresql at least). It ensures we don't allocate a cidr
overlapping with existent cidrs but nothing disallows a concurrent
subnet allocation to create a subnet in the same subnetpool.

This change replaces the lock on subnetpool subnets by a lock on the
subnetpool itself. It disallows to allocate concurrently 2 subnets in
the same subnetpool and ensure non-overlapping cidrs in the same
subnetpool.

Moreover this change solves a trouble with postgresql which disallows
to lock an empty select with an outer join: it happens on first subnet
allocation in a subnetpool when no specific cidr is provided. Moving
the lock ensures the lock is done on a non-empty select.

But this change does not ensure non-overlapping cidrs in subnetpools
with galera because galera doesn't support SELECT FOR UPDATE locks. A
follow-up change will (try to?) remove locks from subnet allocation[1]
in order to ensure non-overlapping cidrs in subnetpools also with galera.

[1] in neutron.ipam.subnet_alloc.SubnetAllocator

Closes-Bug: #1451558
Partial-Bug: #1451576
Change-Id: I73854f9863f44621ae0d89c5dc4893ccc16d07e4

Adds rtfd post-hooks to all akanda projects

post-merge doc builds.

commit_message:
oslo.vmware non-voting bandit job

This adds a non-voting bandit job for oslo.vmware.  The oslo.vmware
project already has a tox environment for bandit, just need the
infra to run this job as part of the gate of the master branch.

Change-Id: I7913794de51bf7a862dbb835d4368fc6ab5cde5b

changed the direction of the bug. Specifically:

"This section applied to installation of horizon
on some server other than the controller node,

node that already includes the requirements."

I could mark the #1426451 bug as invalid, checkout a new bug that targets the install requirement changes, and then add that bug to this patch? Otherwise I can address the comments and repost.'}, {'account_id': 6547, 'date': '2015-06-07 14:26:32.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Once both together is fine, I'll happily remove my -2.

Btw. how did you create this patch at all?

We switched to python 2.7 (and not 2.69 already in September 2014:
commit b2227bfdd594626f6731c9f4039b45224f4b2fdf
Author: Tom Fifield <tom@openstack.org>
Date:   Fri Sep 26 13:09:01 2014 +0800

    Python 2.6 is end-of-life
    
    Python 2.6 is end-of-life, and we should be recommending Python 2.7.
    
    This patch updates two of the three places Python 2.6 was referred to
    in the documentation, removing the reference to 2.6 but keeping the
    2.7 reference. The final place is in the debian packages section of
    the install guide, which notes several issues with Python 2.7 that
    could now be solved. If this is the case, this entire section should
    probably be removed.

[{'created': '2015-06-03 03:22:56.000000000', 'message': 'Update system requirements in install guide for Debian 7

Updating information on where the dashboard service is installed,
and adding additional information to clarify system requirements -
python versions and sending ip addresses to users.

Change-Id: I653c12c3e895111d08ecf8fef017e82fca2f909d
backport: none
Closes-Bug: #1426451
'}, {'created': '2015-06-03 06:09:18.000000000', 'message': 'Update Dashboard system requirements in install guide for Debian 7

Removing the system requirements section, and moving any
important information into the introduction and concluding paragraps
of the Horizon chapter.

Change-Id: I653c12c3e895111d08ecf8fef017e82fca2f909d
backport: none
Partial-Bug: #1426451
'}, {'created': '2015-06-09 04:15:39.000000000', 'message': 'Dashboard system requirements for Debian 7 install

Because horizon is deployed on the controller node from Juno onwards, this
patch removes the system requirements section, which has documentation
for deploying horizon on a server other than the controller node.

It moves any important information from the system requirements chapter to the
introduction and concluding paragraphs of the Horizon chapter, and specifies
that these are Debian requirements.

Change-Id: I653c12c3e895111d08ecf8fef017e82fca2f909d
backport: juno kilo
Closes-Bug: #1426451

commit_message:
Dashboard system requirements for the install guide

Because horizon is deployed on the controller node from Juno and Kilo onwards, this
patch removes the system requirements section, which has documentation
for deploying horizon on a server other than the controller node.

It moves any important information from the system requirements chapter to the
introduction and concluding paragraphs of the Horizon chapter.

Change-Id: I653c12c3e895111d08ecf8fef017e82fca2f909d
backport: juno kilo
Closes-Bug: #1426451

On the matter of increased risk of backporting conflicts I believe it's the other way around, since without this patch the next 2 won't go in as cleanly. One is not clear that will go in [1], but the other is a good candidate [2] and will need redoing without this and [1].

commit_message:
Follow i18n guidelines in LIO target

In LIO target some logging instances do not follow i18n guidelines
related to delayed string interpolation.

Change-Id: Ie184725ea9d83d676612ec82ea56013c0f15eed4
(cherry picked from commit 948d6d87e8f09bbc3696cb0efec00f235b6cf799)

commit_message:
Log command failure details before raising ISCSITargetDetachFailed

In the case that there is some useful information in the
ProcessExecutionError (like stderr) when trying to terminate the
connection in the lio target, also log the error.

Related-Bug: #1450658

Change-Id: Id28968735eca27c4c4e5892e14d06aece02b06f5
(cherry picked from commit b9f3967c1d048674e5ea53e8a9f539030ff043ef)

The unit tests for iser inherit from the tgtAdm, it means that any
time run tests for iser, tgtAdm tests run too. This chache add
TargetFixture to tests, it allows to decouple tests and delete
duplicated code.

Other changes:
 -  deleted  __init__ in test's classes; __init__ may work as a
replacement for setUp, but  setUp should be used instead because
it is part of the protocol for writing tests. It also has a
counterpart, tearDown, which __init__ does no;
 - replaced stubs to mock.

Change-Id: I8aa9f756efb0b4fc4a3a0ea960c6f2d8e20ec18a
Closes-Bug: #1420009

commit_message:
Targets test refactoring

The unit tests for iser inherit from the tgtAdm, it means that any
time run tests for iser, tgtAdm tests run too. This chache add
TargetFixture to tests, it allows to decouple tests and delete
duplicated code.

Other changes:
 -  deleted  __init__ in test's classes; __init__ may work as a
replacement for setUp, but  setUp should be used instead because
it is part of the protocol for writing tests. It also has a
counterpart, tearDown, which __init__ does no;
 - replaced stubs to mock.

Change-Id: I8aa9f756efb0b4fc4a3a0ea960c6f2d8e20ec18a
Closes-Bug: #1420009
(cherry picked from commit bdd0ff6c685855a47034cdfa0cdfa50a4d153a1d)

commit_message:
Move unit tests into dedicated directory

This patch moves all of the existing cinder/tests into
cinder unit tests.  This is being done to make way for
the addition of cinder/tests/functional.

Yes, this is going to cause significant pain with
any changes that haven't merged behind it in terms
of rebase, but there's no real alternative.  We have
to rip the band-aid off at some point, and early in L
seems like a great time to do it.

Conflicts:
	cinder/tests/unit/api/contrib/test_qos_specs_manage.py

Change-Id: I63b0f89474b3c139bdb89589abd85319d2aa61ec
(cherry picked from commit cbcbc90cf64d91a33b7bcfb826c59d4b69697486)

subject: Include missing source so keystone can shut down in kilo
revisions:
[{'created': '2015-06-11 10:59:59.000000000', 'message': "Include missing source so keystone can shut down in kilo

Keystone couldn't shut down in WSGI mode because we were missing a
source of the lib/apache file. That was preventing kilo backports from
landing, this should fix that issue.

Change-Id: I4b2542e6ff2bc11a51c1fa15f1cf8836872ea089
Closes-Bug: #1456835

commit_message:
Include missing source so keystone can shut down in kilo

Keystone couldn't shut down in WSGI mode because we were missing a
source of the lib/apache file. That was preventing kilo backports from
landing, this should fix that issue.

Depends-On: I557e9d7d35239b9336b6d90f037f14cdf2585f76
(devstack-gate change to revert to old correct behavior)

Change-Id: I4b2542e6ff2bc11a51c1fa15f1cf8836872ea089
Closes-Bug: #1456835

commit_message:
Moving out the cisco n1kv section to stackforge

Since most of the n1kv plugin code resides in stackforge/networking-cisco
repo, it's best to move the n1kv section there

Change-Id: Ic1388980dea0d27dfa5e84869f1f20cc9bff78e5
Closes-Bug: #1441400

commit_message:
Fix configuration for tox 2.0.x

Using latest tox 2.0.x our tox jobs fail with following error:

tox.ConfigError: ConfigError: substitution key 'envbindir' not found

So, replace substitution key 'envbindir' with 'envdir' with suffix '/bin'.

Change-Id: I51a4aa7d66cf24ec89cd2c87c9ce902b919ba4b1
Closes-Bug: #1455066

commit_message:
Add libjerasure dev packages on workers

Without libjerasure-dev and its declared dependency, libjerasure2,
pyeclib doesn't build extensions needed to support Swift's Python
2.7 unit test jobs. Update the bindep fallback if the corresponding
change is merged to the openstack_project Puppet manifest.

Change-Id: I28ba0cb0a064e1a08b47578ead9ec1a2e2768ca3
Depends-On: Ia8ea54a8dc3350d17abc4ff33fe03fd937e0a068

commit_message:
Provides a sample resourcefile for Javelin

Introducing a sample file in etc/ similar to the existing ones for
tempest.conf or accounts.yaml. This file can be used as a concrete
example of how to use Javelin.

Currently some resources are missing from the file (like volumes,
routers, and more importantly servers) and could be added in a later
commit.

Change-Id: I3e0d06c7654ad30c42e435a19106c6633144c9b5

commit_message:
Add keystone v2.0 and v3 api discovery checks

Keystone documentation is quite strict about
field media-types and status, therefore they
must be validated. Remaining fields are
checked only for their presence in response.

Change-Id: I76f50bc1cf5581b35adca410bb7f5d4ec9aecbf4

commit_message:
Add base benchmark for Manila list shares operation

List of changes:
- Added general support of Manila project.
- Added support of 'list' operation for shares.
- Added benchmark for listing of shares.
- Added two different manila jobs scripts that will be used for two
different Manila installtions. Current benchmark is used without changes in
both installations.

Change-Id: I95d5a00c9e423ff38bcf3ed0497d9a2bdbfc22b0

commit_message:
Add validity check of 'expires_at' in trust creation

It is meaningless that creating a trust with expiration older than now.
This change add the validity check of "expires_at" when creating a trust.

Change-Id: Iebdfe86721204a550a74a00c46d661d903a4a141
Closes-Bug: 1456069

commit_message:
Import mox3 library

The mox3 library was a fork of mox created by the community, and left a
bit stagnant. It is now causing some issues with dependencies, and so we
would like to bring it into the Oslo program to clean it up and create
another release.

commit_message:
Clean-up openstack.common

* Unused module was removed
* Existing modules were updated
* Readme file was added
* Exceptions classes, used from unsupported exceptions from
  oslo-incubator are moved to murano.common
* Orginize imports to the correct order in files, where the order were modified

Next patch will remove all locations of openstack.common.log usage

Change-Id: I4382215df1bcf81aea60e29039de548bcfe5a356

commit_message:
Moving out the cisco n1kv section to stackforge

Since most of the n1kv plugin code resides in stackforge/networking-cisco
repo, it's best to move the n1kv section there

commit_message:
API design for configuration via data store

this patch adds in API two new requests:

GET /v2/meta/pipelines
    Return all pipeline configuration items
    Parameters: q - Filter rules for items to be returned
    Return type: configuration

PUT /v2/meta/pipelines
    Create a new pipeline configuration item with a user-defined id
    Parameters: data(configuration) - a configuration within the
    request body

APIImpact:
DocImpact:

Change-Id: Ic0ce45d957ed969f771469c4a4c4faf2f91406e8
Partially-Implements: blueprint ceilometer-configuration-via-data-store

commit_message:
[Murano Docs] Add importing an app package HowTo

This patch adds a HowTo instruction on importing an application package:
- from a zip file
- from murano applications repository
- from bundles of applications
Also adds a "figures" folder with necessary for this HowTo screenshots
 inside.
Removes the "From a local bundle of applications" section as it refers
 to CLI.
Change-Id: Ic6fb75a0610c23e8920e4c2aca54876bc2dec2e0

commit_message:
JSCS cleanup - Angular framework widgets (partial2)

We need to do cleanup before we can enable JSCS globally
(https://review.openstack.org/#/c/185725/).

Widgets included: modal, modal-wait-spinner, table, toast,
transfer-table, wizard

Change-Id: Ifa53fde6e0c4119a092e657fc07627ffb68dd248
Partially-Implements: blueprint jscs-cleanup

commit_message:
Add config option to override url for versions

The versions url returns the wrong data when nova api is behind
a proxy. This adds a new config option so it can be set properly.

DocImpact

Change-Id: Ifdda22506fe6518a8835f8df5b6a3b406d5f17a5
Closes-Bug: #1384379

shihanzhang, this is explained in the RFC that I linked in my review. Basically, proxy servers inject a few headers when the forward a request, so you can use those headers to find out information about the request from the client. The alternative I have been advocating for is the use of the "forwarded" headers that proxy servers set.

Just found the other day that heat already looks at one of them, X-Forwarded-Proto: https://github.com/openstack/heat/blob/1a459d409704cf6b2c90e50f9290725201b2a58d/heat/api/middleware/ssl.py#L20

If we add X-Forwarded-Host I think this problem is fully resolved without having to hardcode the URL.

Using the catalog as Steve Baker suggests is also a possible alternative solution, but I think using the headers is easier and more reliable.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-04-24 02:42:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8: Verified-1

commit_message:
Add config option to override url for versions

The versions url returns the wrong data when heat api is behind
a proxy. This adds a new config option so it can be set properly.

DocImpact

Change-Id: I231c83aae025b1b3c42e05eb6752c321d3fee5a6
Closes-Bug: #1384379

[{'account_id': 6968, 'date': '2015-05-07 09:46:46.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-05-07 09:49:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1

- gate-swift-specs-docs http://docs-draft.openstack.org/14/180914/1/check/gate-swift-specs-docs/bebd763//doc/build/html/ : SUCCESS in 2m 04s'}, {'account_id': 12193, 'date': '2015-05-07 10:18:57.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

I'm really interested in this. Looks good to me!

One concern (implemantation):
The successful requests are trapped by the middleware and then send the notification to Zaqar and send the response to users.
This might be cause of a performance problem."}, {'account_id': 6968, 'date': '2015-05-07 12:51:40.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Hisashi: yes, I'm also thinking about the performance impact. So, I'd like to make this configurable per-container, and if it's not enabled just skip the notification - thus users decide wether they accept a possible small performance degradation on their container."}, {'account_id': 6968, 'date': '2015-05-07 12:58:20.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-05-07 13:08:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1

I read your update "Security" section. Looks good to me.'}, {'account_id': 16233, 'date': '2015-05-11 13:09:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1

Nice job.'}, {'account_id': 7233, 'date': '2015-05-14 01:51:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+2

(1 comment)

Looking good. As it stands, as a living document I think this can merge.'}, {'account_id': 8542, 'date': '2015-05-14 06:34:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1

I like this idea. I wanted a similar thing (https://blueprints.launchpad.net/swift/+spec/hook-script-support) earlier.

I would suggest generalizing it a bit more so that it can be used for other use cases. I don't know how to word this in a better way: Invoke "X" (method/class/plugin) when container/account is created/changed and pass info about the change to X during invocation. Leave implementation of X to operators, thus making it pluggable.

For example, if you tie up "X" to container creation event: A operator can implement X which sends a mail to admin on container creation with the container name and IP the request came from.'}, {'account_id': 8542, 'date': '2015-05-14 06:37:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

And "sending notification to zaqar" could be reference implementation but operators could be free to plug in some other piece of code that reads the notification.'}, {'account_id': 4608, 'date': '2015-05-14 12:25:29.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1

(2 comments)

@Pai

hook-script seems interesting but, imho, we should define the target this spec focuses. I think this notification spec only for objects (i.e. not for accounts, not containers and not pluggable), right? And it seems ok to me because *pluggable* stuff might make something to be more complex far from this.

So I think pluggable would be nice (I'm really interested in that one!) *BUT* it should be discussed as another one."}, {'account_id': 5600, 'date': '2015-05-21 19:06:59.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1

(5 comments)

Left a few notes within. This is almost perfect and coincides almost precisely with some refactoring efforts we were already doing on our existing metadata search implementation. I'd much prefer to yield to upstream efforts as much as possible on this instead, and contribute as much as we can."}, {'account_id': 7847, 'date': '2015-06-11 09:14:11.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review+2 Workflow+1

Will need some thought as to dealing with events that occur 'under the hood' e.g. copies, versioned object movement, object expriy(?), any future object movement due to policy change/migration. Perhaps some of these case can all be handled by middleware hooks, but not ones that are caused by async daemon processes."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-06-11 09:14:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: -Verified

Starting gate jobs.

commit_message:
Overwrite NovaException message

I see nova reports DeprecationWarning message when using exception.message.

DeprecationWarning: BaseException.message has been deprecated as of Python 2.6

This can be fixed by overwrite message in our Nova base Exception.

Closes-Bug: #1447946
Change-Id: I7270e06622131af1565f748f69aa3497ca7ef4d2

commit_message:
Remove major version checking

Raising NotAcceptable is useless if major version is different, because major
version is checked by controller itself.

Change-Id: Ie53af7c511b436459c9bb35e34f32ec2f3cef4f6
Closes-Bug: #1464113

commit_message:
Convert ch_blockstorage.xml to RST

This patch converts ch_blockstorage.xml to blockstorage.rst
Also changes Storage Area Network (SAN) to Network Attached
 Storage (NAS), and ISCSI to iSCSI.

Change-Id: I86a8032c32a52fb912b392f72b978ce157c31653
Implements: blueprint reorganise-user-guides

commit_message:
Documentation improvements and minor fixups

* Move the Ansible README under the docs/ dir to make it more visible
to people browsing the docs.

* Add a paragraph explaining the provided inventory files.

* Add note to ensure user updates the koalla_directory var to match
  their environment.

* Add paragraph on some basic requirements for those using Vagrant.

* Add missing command for pip requirements when installing compose.

* Add recommendation to avoid the statically linked docker binary if
  possible (I had kernel incompatibilities when trying this)

Minor:
* Capitalise all usages of "Ansible", "Kolla", and "OpenStack"

* Fix some typos

Change-Id: I3d25ac47ed1f60cb23cf9f528119366a5e31d434

commit_message:
Modify cinder api-paste.ini file on Kilo upgrade

This change will allow upgdate cinder to modify the cinder
api-paste.ini file to use oslo.middleware instead of
openstack.common.middleware.

This change is required to enable Cinder moving from the
old oslo-incubator based middleware to the oslo.middleware
library.

Documentation has been add in the Kilo Release Notes.

https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/ReleaseNotes/Kilo#Upgrade_Notes_7

Change-Id: I0c2d79800f001ebc3120d12d739c7fbb6a609a5a
Depends-On: I43f4ebfc3f30d064236d570638d2dda09af4fbe9

commit_message:
Install guide reflects changes on master branch

This updates the install guide so that it reflects the changes we
are doing on master branch for the Liberty release, instead of for
the Kilo release.

Closes-bug:#1462161

commit_message:
libvirt: introduce method to get domain XML

Adds method get_xml_desc to the Guest object and updates
the libvirt driver code to use it.

Change-Id: Idb74d1900377f28c8c02a916a17a76215f142e3e

commit_message:
libvirt: introduce method detach_device to Guest object

Adds method detach_device to the Guest object and updates the
libvirt driver code to use it.
Also updates methods _detach_pci_devices and
_detach_sriov_ports to use a Guest object.

Change-Id: Ie39d3feba654c487abdd300687e9a243c84ab5cf

commit_message:
Skip trying to set project_domain_id if not using password

This is already fine for user_domain_id, and needs to be replicated
for project_domain_id. Also added more logging.

Change-Id: I3fa8f29edb3fc430d453bd0fc835312c0c8401f4

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-03-10 15:54:59.000000000', 'message': 'Fix nova-compute service spuriously marked as "up"

Currently we use the auto-updated "updated_at" field to determine
whether a service is "up".  An end-user can cause the "update_at"
field to be updated by setting the service as "down" or "up", thus
potentially causing a service that is unavailable to be detected
as "up".  This could result in the scheduler trying to assign
instances to an unavailable compute node.

The fix is to add a new field to explicitly track when the service
sends in a status report and use that if available when testing
whether the service is up.

NOTE: There are broken unit tests still, but I wanted to get the
basic concept out for comments while I work on tidying it up.

Change-Id: Ied7d47363d0489bca3cf2c711217e1a3b7d24a03
'}, {'created': '2015-03-10 18:55:48.000000000', 'message': 'Fix nova-compute service spuriously marked as "up"

as "up".  This could result in the scheduler trying to assign

The fix is to add a new field to explicitly track when the service

NOTE: I feel like what I've done with _do_compute_node() and

many of the unit tests and I think it might help when upgrading.
Thoughts?

'}, {'created': '2015-03-11 20:44:26.000000000', 'message': 'Fix nova-compute service spuriously marked as "up"

Currently we use the auto-updated "updated_at" field to determine
whether a service is "up".  An end-user can cause the "update_at"
field to be updated by setting the service as "down" or "up", thus
potentially causing a service that is unavailable to be detected
as "up".  This could result in the scheduler trying to assign
instances to an unavailable compute node.

sends in a status report and use that if available when testing
whether the service is up.

_from_db_object() is a bit of a hack, but it lets me avoid modifying
many of the unit tests and I think it might help when upgrading.

Currently we use the auto-updated "updated_at" field to determine
whether a service is "up".  An end-user can cause the "updated_at"
field to be updated by setting the service as "down" or "up", thus
potentially causing a service that is unavailable to be detected
as "up".  This could result in the scheduler trying to assign
instances to an unavailable compute node, or in the system
mistakenly preventing evacuation of an instance.

the last time the service sent in a status report and use that if
available when testing whether the service is up.

We also add a new conductor API call to explicitly report state.
This will update the "last_updated_at" field using the current
time as seen by nova-conductor.  This should minimize any issues
with compute node time not being in sync.

'}, {'created': '2015-05-21 07:35:25.000000000', 'message': 'fix "down" nova-compute service spuriously marked as "up"

Currently we use the auto-updated "updated_at" field to determine
whether a service is "up".  An end-user can cause the "updated_at"
field to be updated by disabling or enabling the service, thus
potentially causing a service that is unavailable to be detected
as "up".  This could result in the scheduler trying to assign
instances to an unavailable compute node, or in the system
mistakenly preventing evacuation of an instance.

The fix is to add a new field to explicitly track the timestamp of
the last time the service sent in a status report and use that if
available when testing whether the service is up.

DocImpact
This commit will cause a behaviour change for the DB servicegroup
driver.  It will mean that enabling/disabling the service will
cause the "updated_at" field to change (as before) but that will
no longer be tied to the "up/down" status of the service. So
"nova service-list" could show the service as "down" even if it
shows a recent "updated_at".  (But this could happen for the other
servicegroup drivers already.)

Closes-Bug: #1420848
Change-Id: Ied7d47363d0489bca3cf2c711217e1a3b7d24a03

commit_message:
fix "down" nova-compute service spuriously marked as "up"

Currently we use the auto-updated "updated_at" field to determine
whether a service is "up".  An end-user can cause the "updated_at"
field to be updated by disabling or enabling the service, thus
potentially causing a service that is unavailable to be detected
as "up".  This could result in the scheduler trying to assign
instances to an unavailable compute node, or in the system
mistakenly preventing evacuation of an instance.

The fix is to add a new field to explicitly track the timestamp of
the last time the service sent in a status report and use that if
available when testing whether the service is up.

DocImpact
This commit will cause a behaviour change for the DB servicegroup
driver.  It will mean that enabling/disabling the service will
cause the "updated_at" field to change (as before) but that will
no longer be tied to the "up/down" status of the service. So
"nova service-list" could show the service as "down" even if it
shows a recent "updated_at".  (But this could happen for the other
servicegroup drivers already.)

Closes-Bug: #1420848
Change-Id: Ied7d47363d0489bca3cf2c711217e1a3b7d24a03

(1 comment)

This is currently specific to the DB servicegroup driver, though theoretically other drivers could export something similar via the REST API (presumably queried from their respective backends).

The main rationale for this is simply to avoid end-user confusion about why "updated_at" shows a recent timestamp, but the service is still marked "down".  If we don't think that's an issue worth resolving, then we don't need this feature.'}, {'account_id': 2271, 'date': '2015-06-11 07:57:05.000000000', 'content': "Abandoned

Please update this spec for Liberty if you're still interested in pursuing it."}]

commit_message:
Expose "last_seen_up" when listing services

Assuming something like https://review.openstack.org/163060 gets merged, this
blueprint simply covers adding the "last_seen_up" field as a property in the
response to issuing a GET on /v2/{tenant-id}/os-services. The rationale for
doing this is that it's possible we could end up with a recent "updated_at"
timestamp, but the service is considered as "down". Without exposing
"last_seen_up" the end-user can't tell why the service is considered "down".

If the value of "last_seen_up" is None, then we will set the value in the
property to "-" to indicate that there was no meaningful information present.

It's a simple change, but since it's an API change a spec is needed.

APIImpact

Implements blueprint expose-last-seen-up-listing-services

Change-Id: Iba0d82e7c16eb4cfd5903ddb013c2b61bf22005f

commit_message:
Make fitler to support force_hosts/force_nodes

Add an attribute for each filter and make some filters be executed
even if the force_hosts/force_nodes options are set.

Change-Id: Ibab41ffa1dcb74af5f914a0f5481cfffb13eb8d1
Implements: blueprint verifiable-force-hosts

Thanks Sahid. I agree disable == forbid and optional == unspecified per libvirt usage and regular English. The table will get simpler.'}, {'account_id': 4992, 'date': '2015-04-29 08:35:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8: Code-Review-1

(8 comments)

This spec is addressing three things, should it be split or might we keep it as one with multiple patch sets, for each subcomponent below.

1) comprehending host cpu features and that exposed via libvirt (via cpu-mode and cpu-model) configuration. the net features are what should be considered when scheduling a guest. (all the object and database table details pertain to this)
2) enriching feature specification language, to be able to specify required/disabled/optional. This follows libvirt convention. Is this necessary?
Is it adequate? -- for instance an image might prioritize cpu capabilities (AVX2, AVX1, SSE2, SSE1, vanilla) to glean the maximum speed up possible.
3) resolving feature extra specs specified features and that coming from the image meta data to determine the necessary features and deploy on a compatible host.'}, {'account_id': 782, 'date': '2015-04-29 13:54:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8: Code-Review-1

Please compare this to this alternative propose: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/168982/'}, {'account_id': 1779, 'date': '2015-04-29 14:09:22.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8: Code-Review-1

I tend to prefer the other proposal in general. This spec is described exclusively in terms of turning on/off CPU feature flags, which is a concept that only really works well on x86 architectures. Other architectures like ppc/s390/arm don't have fine grained feature flags like x86, instead the user really just has a large choice of CPU model names.

The alternative spec john link to allows use of both CPU model names or feature flags or both, which makes it more general. The only thing in this proposal that would be missing is the ability to block a feature in a guest. That could be added to the other spec if desired, but I'm not really convinced that's a useful feature in general as it is pretty harmless to expose extra features - the guest can just choose whether to use them or not."}, {'account_id': 5754, 'date': '2015-04-30 07:22:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

Hi Daniel, Thanks for your comment.

Actually I also have cpu model propose in the depend patchset https://review.openstack.org/#/c/170397/

Hope I have something good, and can merge those similar specs.

Actually I wrote a lot of detail in this spec, about how hypervisor report the cpu capabilites.

I reviewed Chris spec, and wrote down some different between I and Chris works at https://review.openstack.org/#/c/168982/

Hope it helpful for the review.
Also appreciate if you can take a look if there are something good we can merge them.

Thanks
Alex'}, {'account_id': 2271, 'date': '2015-06-11 07:56:19.000000000', 'content': "Abandoned

Please update this spec for Liberty if you're still interested in pursuing it."}]

commit_message:
Virt driver to support cpu features

This blueprint is going to implement more flexible way to custom
guest cpu features.

implement blueprint virt-driver-cpu-features

This is separated from blueprint: more-image-properties

Co-Authored-By: Bhandaru, Malini K <malini.k.bhandaru@intel.com>
Co-Authored-By: Jiang, Yunhong <yunhong.jiang@intel.com>

Change-Id: Ia9006dc721f27a0cd85ad3e1e667222880a61a50

[{'created': '2015-06-03 21:13:09.000000000', 'message': "don't leave glance with open file descriptor on error

If we run into a problem writing the image file (full filesystem
for example) the current code will leave glance stuck with an
open file descriptor.  This prevents the image file from being
deleted.  glance will eventually time out and release it, but
this takes hours.

The fix is to continue to iterate over the rest of the
image_chunks even if we can't actually do anything with them.
This allows glance to close the file right away.

Change-Id: Ia05231202cc7c23374ca95dcf2fbcc84fef75279
Closes-Bug: #1461678
"}, {'created': '2015-06-11 06:23:49.000000000', 'message': "don't leave glance with open file descriptor on error

If we run into a problem writing the image file (full filesystem
for example) the current code can leave glance stuck with an
open file descriptor.  This prevents the image file from being
deleted.

It appears that the problem is due to nova-compute holding open
the HTTP connection to glance-api, which in turn holds open the
file descriptor.

The fix is to explicitly delete the iterator.  This results in
the HTTP socket being shut down, which in turn results in the
file descriptor being closed.

Change-Id: Ia05231202cc7c23374ca95dcf2fbcc84fef75279
Closes-Bug: #1461678

commit_message:
don't leave glance with open file descriptor on error

If we run into a problem writing the image file (full filesystem
for example) the current code can leave glance stuck with an
open file descriptor.  This prevents the image file from being
deleted.

It appears that the problem is due to nova-compute holding open
the HTTP connection to glance-api, which in turn holds open the
file descriptor.

The fix is to explicitly delete the iterator.  This results in
the HTTP socket being shut down, which in turn results in the
file descriptor being closed.

Change-Id: Ia05231202cc7c23374ca95dcf2fbcc84fef75279
Closes-Bug: #1461678
Co-Authored-By: Robert Collins <rbtcollins@hp.com>

commit_message:
oslo.msg: don't use devstack for rabbit func tests

The oslo.messaging functional tests suite currently relies on devstack
setup to setup rabbit/qpid/zmq.

This is a bit overkill and a change in devstack can break our jobs,
so we want to remove this dependencies.

The tox target of the rabbit functional tests job have been rabbit enhanced to
not depends on devstack,

This change add a job the run it on a non devstack vm.

When this new job will be validated, the old one will be removed.

Depends-On: I27eb2c1d3d0ca67aa361c83e41372138e03d9bdd
Change-Id: If5b510783d530e36adf225fd02bd3a6e704a715c

commit_message:
Change schema type of `additionalProperties` in unittests

Right now the `additionalProperties` field in image schema in unittests
has type set to 'string'. It's invalid behaviour, because additional
properties can contain null values as well, so we are changing it to
support ['null', 'string'] types.

Additionally new test has been added to cover nullable property.

Change-Id: Ie124fc47fec8219401e9d0d1b3f17394af30089e
Partial-Bug: 1419823

commit_message:
Refactor SAML2 auth plugins

This patch refactors saml2 authentication plugins and inherits from
``keystoneclient.auth.identity.v3.federated.FederatedBaseAuth`` class.
Also, a small typo in the docstring is fixed.

Change-Id: I16a89183c7f900851bbf3f5e1a7e9d98340a9ea6
Partially-Implements: bp refactor-federated-plugins

commit_message:
Consume oslo.policy

Some non intrusive changes to tests are needed, so that we don't rely on
library symbols that are now private (f.e. parse_rule).

Closes-Bug: #1458945

commit_message:
Refactor magnum functional test to add Kubernetes API test

To test Kubernetes API, we need bay created and as already in
magnum functional test, we were creating bay. So this patch
refactors the code to seperate methods for each operation. So
that it can be used at other places.

Change-Id: I64d1b13cdc7c86a007b200bf2e2547216a66eefc
Partial-bug: #1460236

commit_message:
Improved server actions api

The list server actions API is often used in situation of
troubleshooting by cloud administrator. However, This API has
some limitations. We need to remove these limitations for
make it more useful.

Blueprint: improved-server-actions-api
Change-Id: I0988295d0e74be1ebfb83bbd4fd56540f8728e71

commit_message:
Add liberty priorities

At the summit we agreed the priorities for the liberty release.
This records the outcome of that discussion, and allows those unable
to be at the summit to be involved in  that discussion.

In addition, I have added some information about the most important
things that were discussed, but don't yet have a firm enough plan
to go on the list of priorities.

The raw discussion notes can be found here:
https://etherpad.openstack.org/p/YVR-nova-liberty-priorities

Change-Id: I806b35a29f70a09fd06692adff6d0af9ef486fe3

commit_message:
Add data field to action DB model for policy_check

This patch added a data field to action DB model. This field is
used to store result data that generated during policy_check and
action execution. Based on this, policy_data parameter is not
needed anymore when invoking attach/detach/pre_op/post_op methods
of policy and all action methods.

This patch also recorded the id of nodes which was deleted or
created during action progress. This id list will be persisted
into DB as action data and then consumed by policies whose check
target is 'AFTER'.

Change-Id: I88cb033974b57acda1678039a8362bdbee5bf7a4

[{'created': '2015-06-11 02:00:53.000000000', 'message': "autohelp: use correct option names from extensions

autohelp's OptionsCache.load_extension_options() loads options from
libraries. An oslo_config.cfg.Opt object has a 'name' attribute and
a 'dest' attribute. The option name that we're interested in (that
the user sets) is the 'dest' value, not the 'name' value. The
load_extension_options() method was incorrectly using the option's
'name' attribute.

This fixes it so that the option's 'dest' attribute is used instead.
Eg, from oslo_log library, it now correctly uses 'log_config_append'
instead of 'log-config-append'.

Change-Id: I01422bf33be286cc0176a3e1e4ac1c348c6821ef
Closes-Bug: #1464058
"}]
commit_message:
autohelp: use correct option names from extensions

autohelp's OptionsCache.load_extension_options() loads options from
libraries. An oslo_config.cfg.Opt object has a 'name' attribute and
a 'dest' attribute. The option name that we're interested in (that
the user sets) is the 'dest' value, not the 'name' value. The
load_extension_options() method was incorrectly using the option's
'name' attribute.

This fixes it so that the option's 'dest' attribute is used instead.
Eg, from oslo_log library, it now correctly uses 'log_config_append'
instead of 'log-config-append'.

Change-Id: I01422bf33be286cc0176a3e1e4ac1c348c6821ef
Closes-Bug: #1464058

commit_message:
Convergence resource operations

Updates enging resource module with required
wrapper functions for supporting convergence.

commit_message:
corrected the wrong url in admin instance detail

In admin instance detail page, the image url pointing to image detail page in project panel.

This behavior is wrong, it should be link to admin panel only.

This patch corrected the url to point to the admin panel image detail page.

Change-Id: I4ec2687cc208e61b2be00dc86e42f95fa8a1a363
Closes-Bug: #1463312

(43 comments)

I don't understand most of the things in helper.py and seems totally related to Cisco hardware.  It would better off  it there was a wrapper module (something like python-ucsclient) which can work over UcsSdk. That way 

* Ironic code would be much cleaner and easier to maintain
* Any changes related to your hardware - support for newer hardware, bug fixes in particular models of hardware, would be very easy. You don't need to change Ironic code for that. You could just fix the bug in your module and ask your users to install a newer version of the module.
* python-ucsclient could be used outside Ironic to easily manage cisco servers.

You can maintain python-ucsclient in stackforge. With stackforge, you can make use of openstack resources for CI - which includes gerrit workflow, automated unit tests running, automated merges and pypi releases.  Do talk in the IRC if you are interested."}, {'account_id': 10239, 'date': '2015-03-03 14:59:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

commit_message:
Add pxe_ucs and agent_ucs drivers to manage Cisco UCS servers

This commit adds pxe_ucs, agent_ucs driver changes.
Adds support for the following:

- Power driver changes
- Management interface changes
- UCS Helper code, which can be reused with other parts of the driver,
  ex: to support vendor apis.

Change-Id: I02211da5fad039dc7e6b509d547e473e9b57009b
Implements: blueprint cisco-ucs-pxe-driver

commit_message:
Remove UPDATE_CANCELLED cluster state

This state doesn't make sense. When a cluster update is cancelled, we
can put the cluster in ERROR or WARNING status, depending on the
severity of errors detected.

Change-Id: If200d375d6505237a3aa4b266ece3e69871d4474

commit_message:
Refactor request methods onto request object

Take advantage of webob Request objects to move methods that deal with
manipulating the request onto the request.

This removes a debug statement that prints a static list of headers that
will be removed because we no longer keep the static list. This list was
not really useful to debugging as the list doesn't change.

Change-Id: I8601cd7ff9cea778911cbfc306dc03089530bc9d

Hi gordon chung, Julien dandjou, thanks for clarify me, maybe the paginaion is worthless, for metrics, the main use cases is statistics query, so the pagination query of samples (or meters) query is useless. The pagination also include sorting, limit, marker query. pagination for alarms, events, the list result of this resources may will be used in dashboard show, user may want to get the list of all the events (and may apply specified sort key(s) and sort direction(s) additionally), but the the massive items may will crash the API or dashboard, the pagination is needed.

commit_message:
Remove pagination code

This code is actually dead code we carry over for a long time now, as
the pagination support never landed completely. Let's clean that old cruft.

Change-Id: Idbb2c93ed00dc2359f555d245c2283844d5a1da4

commit_message:
Remove custom header handling

Now we have a webob request remove all the transformation between a
header and an environment variable in favour of webob's handling.

Change-Id: Ifb79e1ea30663efca4696a219739a15d27bb76ef
